<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan on Ties Between Disarmament, Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said Monday that "disarmament and development are
intimately connected."
</P>
<P>
Annan made the statement at the opening of a general debate on
disarmament by the First Committee of the 53rd General Assembly
session. The First Committee is in charge of disarmament and
international security affairs.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Annan further elaborated the relations in two
ways.
</P>
<P>
"First, disarmament is essential to effective conflict
prevention or post-conflict peace-building in many parts of the
developing world, and conflict is the worst enemy of development
everywhere," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Secondly, even when an arms race does not lead directly to
conflict, it still constitutes a cruel diversion of skills and
resources away from development," he said.
</P>
<P>
"While so many human needs remain unsatisfied, millions of
people on this planet depend for their livelihood on producing, or
distributing, or maintaining engines designed only to destroy --
engines of which the best one can hope is that they will not be
used," he said.
</P>
<P>
"That is a terrible waste. More than that, it is a source of
deep shame. As long as it continues, none of us takes much pride
in our humanity," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The world looks to the United Nations, and the United Nations
looks to the committee, to lead it in a different and more hopeful
direction," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Disarmament lies at the heart of this organization's efforts
to maintain and strengthen international peace and security," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The First Committee began its general debate at a time when the
world attention was focused on disarmament issues with particular
intensity due to the underground nuclear tests successively
conducted by India and Pakistan in May this year.
</P>
<P>
As Annan said earlier, those tests tipped "the balance on which
the nuclear-non-proliferation regime rested" and dealt a serious
setback to decades of international efforts aimed at disarmament
and non-proliferation.
</P>
<P>
"We must be concerned about the nuclear tests carried out by
India and Pakistan this year," Annan said, "Of course I warmly
welcome the declaration of intent to adhere to the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty, made here in the General Assembly by the prime
ministers of those two states."
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations has worked for over half a century to
eliminate nuclear weapons everywhere and to oppose their
acquisition anywhere," he said. "Given the potential devastation
from the use of even one nuclear weapon, I believe global nuclear
disarmament must remain at the top of our agenda." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
