<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Business Confidence Plunges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Business confidence in Britain
plunged over the last three months with the balance of
manufacturing companies expecting business to decline, according
to the Institute of Directors.
</P>
<P>
The result of the institute's findings, revealed in its latest
quarterly survey of business opinion, adds to a growing body of
data pointing to an economy slowing quickly, with many observers
saying a recession is now likely.
</P>
<P>
Ruth Lea, head of the policy unit at the institute, was quoted
by local media reports as saying, "The deterioration in confidence
is such that we need a further quarter point cut in interest
rates."
</P>
<P>
The survey of the institute's members in the three months to
September found that optimists outnumbered pessimists by just 2
percent, down from 19 percent in the last quarter and down from 51
percent in March.
</P>
<P>
The gloomy outlook was most pronounced in the manufacturing
sector where the pessimists outnumber the optimists by 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
The continuing fall in business confidence comes despite
findings from the same survey which show a large number of
companies doing well. Directors saying their business was
performing well outnumbered those saying performance had declined
by 77 percent, a marginal increase on last quarter's 76 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the report warned against assuming good performance today
meant the future was bright.
</P>
<P>
The survey provides more evidence that Britain is a two-speed
economy. While confidence is plummeting in the manufacturing
sector particularly among exporters, most service companies are
still confident that business will get better.
</P>
<P>
The survey also measures efficiency in companies by asking
whether they are working to full capacity. Most directors survey
said their business was not working to full capacity with
manufacturing once again the worst effected.
</P>
<P>
The decision last week by the Bank of England Monetary Policy
Committee to cut interest rates by 0.25 percent to 7.25 percent
was broadly welcomed by business although the institute had been
calling for a cut of 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The central bank had resisted calls for a cut with most of its
members fearing that inflation had not been squeezed hard enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
