<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finland Supports Peace Process on Cyprus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Finnish Foreign
Minister Tarja Halonen Monday expressed her country's support for
the U.N. peace process to settle the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after talks with her Cypriot counterpart
Ioannis Kasoulides, Halonen said Finland considers the U.N. peace
effort to solve the Cyprus problem "very important for the
European Union (EU) and Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
"We respect very very strongly U.N. resolutions and role and we
are prepared as president of EU in the second semester of 1999 to
give our full support to facilitate this process," she said.
</P>
<P>
Halonen, who is currently on a three-day visit to the island,
focused her talks with Kasoulides on EU enlargement, cooperation
with applicant countries, the Cyprus problem, developments in the
region and issues of bilateral interests.
</P>
<P>
She said she hopes to see more practical steps forward in EU's
enlargement process. "We did the first part well and have no
reasons to stop the proceeding from going now smoothly forward,"
she added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The internationally recognized Greek Cypriot-dominated
government submitted its application for full EU membership in
1990. The EU started accession talks with it in March this year.
</P>
<P>
But some EU members such as France and Italy have tried to
associate Cyprus's accession with a settlement of the Cyprus
problem. The idea was rejected by another EU member, Greece, a
strong supporter of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Halonen said "I encourage Cyprus to be patient in her efforts
to join the EU." "Cyprus has to fulfill all EU criteria but also a
right to get equal treatment, have same tasks, same homework as
other candidates," She noted.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Kasoulides said Halonen's visit "shows keen
interest of Finland in Cyprus" and described their talks as "very
useful."
</P>
<P>
He said Cyprus and Finland enjoy excellent bilateral ties and
announced the Cypriot government's intention to open an embassy in
Helsinki in early 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
