<HEADLINE> Lesotho Talks to Go Ahead Despite Sunday's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Planned talks between the
ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) and its opposition
rivals would go ahead Wednesday despite Sunday's political
violence, Lesotho Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Even though we suspect that the opposition parties sent their
youths to assassinate us, we are still determined to sit around
the table with them with a view to solving the current political
impasse," South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted Mosisili
as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said his party was considering laying an attempted murder
charge against the opposition alliance.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance has denied the allegations, saying
that the violence was stage-managed by the LCD to justify the
continued existence of foreign troops in the country.
</P>
<P>
South African and Botswanan troops entered Lesotho on
September 22 under the auspices of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) to help the Lesotho government quell
the rising unrest in the tiny mountain kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The unrest stemmed from a dispute over the outcome of the May
23 general election, which the opposition said was rigged in
favor of the LCD.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho police Monday began investigating Sunday's incident
that resulted in the death of three youths and the injuring of
one at an LCD rally in the east of Maseru, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted Lesotho Police Commissioner Bolutu
Makoaba as saying that a murder docket had been opened, but that
no one had been arrested.
</P>
<P>
Makoaba said a policeman was injured when a crowd from the LCD
rally attacked a police vehicle after speculation that some of
the youths arrested for inciting the violence had been released.
</P>
<P>
He said the youths, who were arrested and released, were
searched and no arms and ammunition were found on them.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to those who witnessed Sunday's incidents to help
police with the investigations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
