<HEADLINE> Survey: Inflation Squeezed Out of UK Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Prices for manufactured goods
leaving Britain's factories are hardly rising as the growth rate
of prices is at its lowest for nearly 40 years.
</P>
<P>
Newly released official figures indicate that inflation is
being squeezed out of the British economy.
</P>
<P>
Output prices of manufactured products were down 0.1 percent in
September from the previous month, and were up 0.3 percent
year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics said the year-on-year growth
rate of output prices fell to its lowest level since March 1960.
Economists generally had expected output prices to rise 0.1
percent on the month and 0.4 percent year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
The figures provide further evidence that inflation is
currently no threat to the U.K. economy and will add to growing
pressure for further interest rate cuts by the Bank of England,
according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers have been forced to keep prices down because of a
flood of cheap imports due to the strength of the pound.
</P>
<P>
Extremely gloomy figures for manufacturing found that excluding
food, drinks, tobacco and petrol, output prices fell for the first
time since January 1959.
</P>
<P>
Food manufacturers were particularly hard hit as the prices at
which manufacturers bought their goods fell by 1 percent between
August and September.
</P>
<P>
This was largely caused by tumbling prices for British produced
food and imported metals.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil prices rose by 3.3 percent between August and
September, significantly down on a year-on-year basis.
</P>
<P>
The figures have been rebased to a 1995 basis to reflect the
changing pattern of the industry's sales and purchases in the
index weights.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics said the new calculations
had had a minimal impact on the output figures, reducing the index
by 0.1 point every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
