<HEADLINE> UK Embassy in Belgrade Closed Amid Strike Fears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain is to close its embassy
in Belgrade Monday afternoon as NATO moved closer to air strikes
against Yugoslavia, said a report of the British Broadcasting
Corporation (BBC).
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a Foreign Office spokesman as saying that the
embassy closure was "in view of the growing expectation of
military action" over the troubled Serbian province of Kosovo,
where about 290,000 civilians had fled their homes due to attacks
launched by Serbian security forces.
</P>
<P>
A NATO council meeting scheduled late Monday in Brussels will
discuss plans for a possible air strike against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The BBC report said that last week, non-essential staff and
families of officials stationed in British embassy in Belgrade
already left for Budapest, Hungary. The remaining staff of around
10 are also heading there now.
</P>
<P>
David Landsman, deputy head of mission at the British Embassy
there, told the BBC that the move was "prudent" in the light of
the expectation of air strikes, saying that "we all very much hope
that a peaceful solution can be found."
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, British Chief of Defense Staff Charles Guthrie
met Prime Minister Tony Blair, Foreign Secretary Robin Cook and
Defense Secretary George Robertson at Downing Street to update
them on the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Blair's spokesman played down the significance of Charles'
briefing, saying it was the first chance the prime minister would
have to catch up on the latest developments after last week's trip
to China.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister has been away and, along with Robin Cook
and George Robertson, he will just be taking stock of where we are
diplomatically and militarily," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Cook will fly to Brussels to discuss the Kosovo
crisis with NATO Secretary Javier Solana and U.S. General Wesley
Clark, the Supreme Allied Commander in Europe, the BBC report
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
