<HEADLINE> Kenya Tea Production Down in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's tea output went down
in August but for the year as a whole remains well up against
last year, the Africa Tea Brokers (ATB), a leading brokerage
house in Kenya, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tea yield of the east African country dropped to 16.8 million
kilograms in August, down 1.88 million compared with that in the
same month last year, and also below the previous month's 17.3
million kilograms, said a statement reaching here from the ATB
based in the Indian Ocean port Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
During the first eight months of 1998, tea output in Kenya
reached 195.1 million kilograms, a rise of 64.5 million against
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Tea production traditionally falls in June, July and August as
colder weather sets in, before rising again in September.
</P>
<P>
However, the ATB said that the conditions remained unfavorable
in some key growing areas of the country in August.
</P>
<P>
"West of the Rift (Rift Valley Province), Kericho has remained
fairly cold and wet with some hail reported earlier in the month,
while in Nandi district rainfall has been intermittent and
temperatures warmer," said the ATB.
</P>
<P>
In the view of the tea exporters, Kenya was on course to
reclaim its place as the world's largest exporter of black teas
this year, a position it briefly ceded to Sri Lanka last year
after drought cut production to just 221 million kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Production in 1998 was boosted by the El Nino-charged heavy
rains from October last year to February this year.
</P>
<P>
Whereas the heavy rains devastated infrastructure and damaged
other crops such as coffee, tea emerged as the major beneficiary,
enjoying better leaf crop and a higher harvest once the generous
spells of sunshine came.
</P>
<P>
Four auction sales were held in August, when a total of
325,679 bags of tea were sold at an average price of 1.70 U.S.
Dollars per kilogram compared with five sales during the same
month last year when 296,382 bags were sold at an average price
of two Dollars.
</P>
<P>
At auction, tea is sold in bags that range from 50 to 70
kilograms, depending on grade and quality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
