<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primakov: NATO Strikes in Kosovo, "Tragic Mistake" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov said Monday that NATO airstrikes on Yugoslavia over the
Kosovo crisis would be a "tragic mistake."
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with Italian Acting Prime Minister
Romano Prodi, Primakov reiterated Moscow's staunch opposition to
the use of NATO force over Kosovo, the Itar-Tass news agency
quoted Primakov's spokesman Igor Shchegolev as saying.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear who initiated the call, but Tass said Prodi
told Primakov about the Italian government's decision to support
NATO's combat operation in Kosovo, if it is held, and stressed
Italy's role would be limited to the provision of NATO air force
bases stationed on its territory for the operation.
</P>
<P>
Also Monday, Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said Moscow
was preparing a "broad spectrum of measures" to be announced in
case NATO launched a military action in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"Russia is preparing several options of possible return
measures that will be taken and published in case NATO delivers a
strike in Yugoslavia," Tass quoted Sergeyev as saying at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
The defense chief said the "broad spectrum of measures" could
include "change in Russia's relations with NATO" and pulling out
of the international embargo on military-technical cooperation
with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
However, he expressed the hope that the Kosovo crisis would be
resolved in a peaceful way.
</P>
<P>
"Russia is ready to consider participating in the observer
mission and provide its planes for implementation of the
international control of the air space over Yugoslavia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev said Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic had agreed
to the presence of 1,500 international observers in the breakaway
Kosovo province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
