<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Tongues to Be Employed in Adult Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan Education Ministry
has decided to use five ethnic languages in the country's adult
education next year, a senior Angolan education official said
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Francisco Domingos, Director of Adult Education Department of
the Angolan Education Ministry, said that the five ethnic
languages are Kimbundo, Umbundo, Kikongo, Ochikuanyama and
Tchokwe. These languages are used as native tongues by most of
the illiterate adults in the southwestern African country.
</P>
<P>
Domingos said that the Angolan government has made the
decision in a bid to wipe out illiteracy across the country.
</P>
<P>
Since a national adult literacy campaign was launched in 1997,
the official said, the Angolan government has been helping 50,000
adults with their education, 500 of them already graduated.
</P>
<P>
And in order to use the ethnic languages in the adult
education, the Angolan Education Ministry has been working
together with the Institute of the Ethnic Languages in preparing
the needed teaching materials, said Domingos.
</P>
<P>
He added that handbooks in ethnic languages will be formally
published in January next year.
</P>
<P>
The 11 million Angolans come from more than 30 ethnic groups
including Ovimbundo, Mbundo, Bakongo and Lunda.
</P>
<P>
The official language of Angola is Portuguese. But most of
the ethnic groups have their own tongues which largely belong to
Bantu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
