<HEADLINE> Arafat Hopes to Clinch Deal with Israel in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 12 (Xinhua) -- President of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) Yasser Arafat here Monday expressed
hope that his upcoming meeting with Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu will yield concrete results.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said that he wants to clinch a deal with Israel on a
peace proposal put forward by the United States for further
Israeli troops withdrawal from the occupied West Bank during their
meeting in the U.S. on October 15.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made these remarks at a press conference held after he
met with Crown Prince Hassan, and other senior Jordanian officials
on the latest developments of the Palestinian-Israeli peace
process.
</P>
<P>
At the same press conference, Hassan on his part reiterated
Jordan`s consistent stand that the Palestinians should establish
their own country on their national soil.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and his six-member delegation, including the PNA
Executive Committee`s Secretary Mohammoud Abbas, arrived here
before noon Monday on a short visit for continuous consultation
with Jordan on peace issues, the official Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will then leave for the U.S. where he will take part in
the summit with Netanyahu and U.S. President Bill Clinton, the
Jordan Times newspaper said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. made its peace proposal months ago, calling Israel
to withdraw its troops from 13.1 percent of the West Bank in
order to reactivate the long-stalled Palestinian-Israeli peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians accepted the proposal, while Israel rejected
it citing security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Late last month Arafat and Netanyahu talked in the U.S. with
Clinton, and the three sides agreed to meet again in the U.S. on
October 15 to hammer out a deal on the long-overdue pullback.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel on Sunday played down hopes for the
long-awaited agreement on the U.S. proposal, saying that nothing
was ready yet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
