<HEADLINE> Russia Still Demands Political Solution to Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Russia insisted during
Tuesday's NATO-Russia Permanent Joint Council (PJC) that the
Kosovo crisis be solved via a political settlement.
</P>
<P>
Russia is strongly opposed to the use of force in solving the
Kosovo crisis, and threatened to veto any United Nations Security
Council (UNSC) resolution that would give the Western military
alliance the mandate for military intervention.
</P>
<P>
NATO, however, decided early on Tuesday without a U.N.
resolution to activate the orders for both limited air strikes and
phased air campaign in an attempt to force Belgrade into full and
verifiable compliance with UNSC Resolution 1199.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's PJC had been planned for ambassadors from both sides,
but Russian Ambassador to NATO Evgeny Kislyak suddenly returned to
Moscow on Sunday after the allies said again and again that the
decision on activation order was imminent.
</P>
<P>
NATO and Russia both expressed continued support for the aim of
securing a political solution to the Kosovo crisis and to avert a
humanitarian catastrophe there.
</P>
<P>
During the day's PJC, NATO informed Russia about its decision
to issue the activation orders and underlined its determination to
help put an end to the intolerable humanitarian situation in
Kosovo, said a written statement issued after the PJC meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
