<HEADLINE> Reported Crimes in Japan Hit Record High in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The number of reported crimes in
Japan in 1997 hit a record high of more than two million, 53,000
more than 1996, the Justice Ministry reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 White Paper on Crime, a report approved at a cabinet
meeting, said a total of 2,518,000 criminal cases were reported in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Theft topped the list of the reported crimes, accounting for
66.1 percent, followed by traffic-related crimes with a proportion
of 24.6 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The number of women arrested in criminal cases was about
70,000, 22.4 percent of the total arrested and 16 percent more
than 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report, which also included juvenile crimes, showed that
the number of young people, aging from 14 to 19 and arrested on
charge of violating juvenile criminal laws, reached 215,600, up
9.8 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Among serious crimes, the number of juveniles arrested on
suspicion of robberies reached 1,701, increasing by 60 percent,
according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
