<HEADLINE> One American, One British Win 1998 Nobel Chemistry Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Two professors from American
universities, Walter Kohn of University of California and John
Pople of Northwestern University, won this year's Nobel prize in
chemistry on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Walter Kohn won the prize "for his development of the
density-functional theory" and John Pople "for his development of
computational methods in quantum chemistry," said the Royal
Swedish Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"The Laureates have each made pioneering contributions in
developing methods that can be used for theoretical studies of the
properties of molecules and the chemical processes in which they
are involved," he said.
</P>
<P>
Quantum chemistry is used nowadays in practically all branches
of chemistry, always with the aim of increasing the knowledge of
the inner structure of matter. The scientific work of Walter Kohl
and John Pople has been crucial for the development of this new
field of research, said the Academy.
</P>
<P>
Walter Kohn, born in 1923 in Vienna, Austria, has been teaching
at University of California at Santa Barbara since 1950.
</P>
<P>
John Pople, a British citizen born in 1925, has been a
professor of chemistry at Northwestern University since 1986.
</P>
<P>
They will share the 7.6-million-krona (978,000 U.S. dollars)
prize. 
</P>
</TEXT>
