<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Scientists Share 1998 Nobel Prize in Physics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Royal Swedish Academy of
Sciences decided Tuesday to award the 1998 Nobel prize in physics
to three university professors for "their discovery of a new form
of quantum fluid with fractionally charged excitations."
</P>
<P>
"The three researchers are being awarded the Nobel Prize for
discovering that electrons acting together in strong magnetic
fields can form new types of 'particles', with charges that are
fractions of electron charges," said the Academy.
</P>
<P>
The Nobel prize winners are Professor Robert Laughlin from
Stanford University, Professor Horst Stormer from Columbia
University and Professor Daniel Tsui from Princeton University.
</P>
<P>
Professor Stormer and Professor Tsui made the discovery in 1982
in an experiment using extremely powerful magnetic fields and low
temperatures. Within a year of the discovery Professor Laughlin
had succeeded in explaining their result.
</P>
<P>
The Academy regarded the contributions of the three laureates
as having "thus led to yet another breakthrough in our
understanding of quantum physics and to the development of new
theoretical concepts of significance in many branches of modern
physics."
</P>
<P>
Professor Laughlin was born in 1950 in Visalia, USA. He
obtained PhD in physics in 1979 at Massachusetts Institute of
Technology and has been Professor of Physics at Stanford
University since 1989.
</P>
<P>
Professor Stormer was born in 1949 in Frankfurt, Germany. He
obtained PhD in physics in 1977 at Stuttgart University in
Germany. He has been Professor of Columbia University, New York
since 1998.
</P>
<P>
Professor Tsui was born in 1939 in Henan of China. He got his
PhD in physics in 1967 at the University of Chicago. He has been
Professor at Princeton University since 1982. He is now an
American citizen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
