<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peaceful Settlement on Kosovo Crisis Reached </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 13 (Xinhua) -- After nine-day tough
negotiations, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and U.S.
special envoy Richard Holbrooke finally reached an agreement on
Kosovo crisis Tuesday, which would avert NATO operations against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke told a news conference in Belgrade after the talks
that Yugoslavia had agreed to international ground and air
verification of its compliance with U.N. resolutions on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We're not out of the emergency yet. We're still in it,"
Holbrooke said before flying back to Washington.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed with President (Slobodan) Milosevic on a ground
verification program augmented with an important aerial
verification program," he added.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana and Supreme Allied
Commander in Europe General Wesley Clark will visit Belgrade soon
to sign an agreement allowing unarmed aircraft to verify
compliance with a cease-fire and the withdrawal of Serbian
security forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Kosovo's ethnic Albanians will be given
autonomy within Serbia.
</P>
<P>
In a separate statement to the nation, Milosevic said the
accord had averted the danger of Western military intervention and
would safeguard the rights of all citizens in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
According to the deal, the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) would sign an agreement allowing for
2,000 "compliance verifiers" with diplomatic status to ensure
freedom of movement for refugees and eventually "organize any
election that takes place" in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
If the agreement were not reached, NATO, which has built up
military presence in Italy, would certainly launch devastating air
strikes against Yugoslavia to force it to fully comply with U.N.
demands to allow refugees to go back home.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of ethnic Albanians have been driven from their homes
during a seven-month conflict between Yugoslav security forces and
the Kosovo Liberation Army which demanded independence of Kosovo,
a southern province of Serbia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
