<HEADLINE> U.S. Former Heavyweight Boxer To Sue Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 13 (Xinhua)-- American former heavyweight
boxing champion Joe Frazier, acquitted of drunken driving last
month, says police used excessive force when they arrested him
and damaged his reputation when they testified at his trial.
</P>
<P>
Frazier said Monday that he has filed court papers, indicating
he will sue the city police over the April incident.
</P>
<P>
He was returning from an appearance at a police benefit
function in Hudson County, New Jersey when he was stopped on
April 7 in his white Jaguar.
</P>
<P>
He said a police officer yanked his arms behind his back and
shoved him into the back of a police car, where he was forced to
sit at an awkward, painful angle for 35-40 minutes until a police
wagon arrived to take him to the police station.
</P>
<P>
Frazier said he complained that the handcuffs around his
wrists were too tight but was told to "shut up and get in the
van." Now he contends he needs surgery on his right shoulder to
repair torn ligaments. 
</P>
