<HEADLINE> Britain Cautiously Welcomes Kosovo Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair Tuesday gave the new agreement over Kosovo a cautious
welcome but insisted that NATO still prepare to use force if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
Blair was speaking after NATO put air strike against Yugoslavia
on hold when Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic agreed to allow
the presence of international observers in the province, where
ethnic Albanian population outnumbers local Serb residents by nine
to one.
</P>
<P>
"It's only been achieved by the mixture of diplomacy and the
threat of force," Blair said, also warning that NATO still
prepared to use force to make sure Belgrade comply with the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The deal was struck between U.S. special envoy Richard
Holbrooke and President Milosevic after another round of talks in
Belgrade early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic agreed to allow the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) to monitor the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, who was in Brussels for
talks with NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana and senior Western
military leaders, also issued a statement saying the West must keep
threat of force over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"The only way to ensure Milosevic keeps his promises is to keep
the credible threat of force hanging over him," he said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
NATO on Tuesday night authorised air strikes on Yugoslavia at
any time but gave Yugoslav government four days to comply with all
U.N. demands which also include the free access of international
aid agencies in Kosovo and allow thousands of refugees to go back
home. 
</P>
