<HEADLINE> Libya Changes Name of Arab Radio to Africa Radio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Libya Tuesday changed "the Voice
of the Greater Arab Nation" into "the Voice of Africa", a move to
show resentment against the Arabs, The Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The change followed the Arab League's refusal to join rally
with the Organization of African Unity (OAU) in its rejection of
the U.N.-imposed embargo on Libya, including air travel in and out
of the country.
</P>
<P>
Arab foreign ministers meeting here last month said the league
will bypass the sanctions when Libya's demand for a fair trial for
the two Libyan suspects in the 1988 Lockerbie bombing is met. But
before that, it has no such intention.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, they support Libya's right to damages in
compensation for human and material losses, sustained as a result
of the seven-year U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
This development is widely viewed by observers as an attempt by
the 22-member Arab forum to court back Libya.
</P>
<P>
Tripoli on September 13 decided to disband its ministry of
promoting Arab unity in the coming few weeks, a move revealing its
grudge against Arab failure to have the U.N. sanctions against the
Afro-Arab country lifted.
</P>
<P>
Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi had criticized the league, saying
that the African nations, rather than the Arab world, were his
only supporters.
</P>
<P>
The OAU in its summit meeting in June adopted a resolution to
defy the sanctions starting from this month if the U.S. and
Britain fail to make compromise. And since then several African
leaders have flown to Tripoli. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
