<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Automobile Loans Receive Enthusiastic Welcome  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese consumers,
manufacturers and sales agents alike are enthusiastically
welcoming the Construction Bank of China (CBC) decision to begin
granting automobile loans next week.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jiamin, sales manager for the Beijing Grand Citroen
Automobile Service Company, said the company welcomes banks
involvement in the auto financing market.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers and sales agents have long been the sole source
of automobile financing.
</P>
<P>
"Not a single sales agent has the capacity to bear the heavy
burden of financing," said Chen.
</P>
<P>
The fact that buyers owe money directly to sales agents or
manufacturers requires the agencies to maintain a large contingent
of debt collectors and bookkeepers business. Higher costs have led
to high prices for automobile. As a result, one major Beijing
automobile market has witnessed a dramatic monthly fall of several
hundred finance deals since August this year to a mere 1-2 deals
per month.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xiaochun, an official with the First Automobile Works
(FAW), China's major automobile manufacturer; said that the entry
of banks into the automobile financing market will ensure
manufacturers, sales agents and consumers share commercial risks
on a reasonable basis.
</P>
<P>
He noted that manufacturers have previously shouldered most of
the risks, with the terms of financing contracts spread over long
periods.
</P>
<P>
Banks will now assume the role manufacturers played as
creditors. Manufacturers will receive immediate payment from banks
and bear no responsibility for prompt repayment of loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Automobile Loans Receive Enthusiastic Welcome  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cui Dianman, an official with CBC Credit and Loan Department
said the bank will be the first financial institution in the
nation to offer automobile loans. He noted that the move is
designed to attract more automobile manufacturers to China.
</P>
<P>
The CBC introduced automobile loans to individual buyers on an
experimental basis in 1996. Related loans facilitates sales of
well over 1,000 automobiles, said Chen. He also pointed to the
good loan repayment rate.
</P>
<P>
The CBC has signed agreements to provide automobile loans to
customers of three major automobile manufacturers in China. The
loans will be offered for purchases of automobiles offered by some
100 sales agents in Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Yang Zhensheng, an official with the State Machine-building
Industry Bureau, said that automobile loans will promote the
expansion of China's automotive market. He said the automobile
industry has long sought the support of financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Recent State Information Center projections indicate the 1998
demand will approach 1.61 million units, down significantly on the
previous forecast of 1.66 million units.  
</P>
