<HEADLINE> German Ventures Explore Chinese Textile Machinery Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The fact that state-owned
businesses in China's textile industry have cut the number of
spindles in use and downsized staff this year has not negatively
affected German interest in selling textile machinery in the
market.
</P>
<P>
Erich Thies, chairman of the German Textile Machinery
Association, is in Beijing to attend the Sixth China International
Textile Machinery Exhibition and noted that the "Chinese market is
vital to German businesses."
</P>
<P>
The exhibition which opened today had attracted 76 German
businesses.
</P>
<P>
China imported textile machinery valued at 394 million Deutsche
marks (239 million US dollars) last year, a level significantly
less than in the previous year. Nonetheless, German manufacturers
maintain full confidence in the retooling of China's textile
industry and aware of its need for high quality German machinery.
</P>
<P>
China ranked as Germany's fourth largest textile machinery
market in 1997, following Turkey, the United States and Italy.
</P>
<P>
German companies sold 2.7 percent of total exported textile
machinery to China and occupied five percent of the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
Thies said German textile machinery exports to China mostly
goes to private businesses and therefore the reform of state
enterprises had little effect on affect their business.
</P>
<P>
Some private enterprises in south China's Guangdong province
have already achieved the world standards, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
