<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Economy Must Face Challenge: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- South African business
must face the challenge and not retreat behind barriers of
protectionism, Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This is a time to realize that if you are going to be in the
world...it takes some change and some work to get there," Erwin
told delegates attending the South African Chamber of Business
(SACOB)'s annual convention in Durban.
</P>
<P>
South Africa had survived the recent financial crisis much
better than many other countries largely because a structural
reform of the country's economy which is still underway, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Problems in the economy had to be addressed by all social
partners, but within the structural parameters of reform set by
the government, Erwin said.
</P>
<P>
He played down the significance of a recent African National
Congress (ANC) discussion document which called for a review of
the government's macro-economic policy - the Growth, Employment
and Redistribution strategy (GEAR).
</P>
<P>
The ANC paper, drafted as an input for an ANC alliance summit
later this month, called for a review of fiscal deficit targets,
a cautious approach to privatization and intervention in the
financial sector without being extremist.
</P>
<P>
The paper was seen as an attempt to bridge the policy divide
within the tripartite ruling alliance of the ANC, the South
African Communist Party (SACP) and the Congress of South African
Trade Unions (COSATU).
</P>
<P>
The ANC's relationship with its allies is strained after
stinging attacks made on its allies by President Nelson Mandela
and Deputy President Thabo Mbeki earlier this year. The divisions
have centered on the GEAR macro-economic strategy.
</P>
<P>
Erwin said he believed South Africa's economy was basically on
the right track and there was much cause for optimism.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
