<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa, EU to Resume Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and the
European Union (EU) will resume their trade talks Wednesday, the
South African Trade and Industry Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During the new round of talks which will end Friday, the two
sides will discuss the agricultural offer by the EU, the
competition policy, rules of origin, and parallel negotiations on
wines and spirits, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The previous round of talks reached an impasse last month
after the EU insisted South African wine producers stop using
brands "port" and "sherry", saying the two brands belong to
Portuguese and Spanish brewers. South Africa considered the
demand to be unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
The trade department said Tuesday South Africa expected the
renewed talks on wines and spirits to lead to a mutually
beneficial agreement, and that viable solutions are found on all
issues.
</P>
<P>
But earlier reports quoted some South African officials as
saying that the new round of talks could hardly produce a
breakthrough, with neither side ready to make major concessions.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has been unhappy with the EU's existing offer of
agricultural goods and its insistence on linking the main trade
negotiations with the talks on wine and spirits and other talks
on fisheries.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, South African Trade and Industry Minister Alec
Erwin said he believed the protracted trade talks with the EU
would succeed within the next year. This was contrary to the EU's
earlier pledge that the talks would be completed by the European
autumn.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
