<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Electing Deputies to District People's Congresses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The election of deputies to the
new terms of people's congresses in Beijing's districts and
counties is in full swing.
</P>
<P>
Liu Zhuquan, deputy director of the electoral office, said here
today that the election is scheduled for completion by the end of
this year, and the time for ballot casting is set sometime around
December.
</P>
<P>
More than 8 million Beijing voters will select new deputies by
means of direct voting. New deputies will convene people's
congresses in their respective districts and counties to elect
Standing Committee members, as well as magistrate and deputy
magistrates.
</P>
<P>
The electorate will include the Communist Party of China (CPC)
and state leaders living in Beijing, staffers from Beijing
institutions and People's Liberation Army troops stationed in the
Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The electoral method requires that candidates for positions as
deputies to district and county's people's congresses will be
selected through nominations in more than 2,000 Beijing
constituencies.
</P>
<P>
Political parties, people's organizations and groups of over 10
voters are eligible to nominate candidates. The number of official
candidates must exceed the number of deputies scheduled for
election by 33-100 percent.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's current permanent population dictates that 4,403
deputies will be elected to the new term of people's congresses at
the district and county levels, a drop of 506 slots on the
previous term.
</P>
<P>
Between 20,000-30,000 representatives from the central and
municipal institutions have assumed electoral posts and the
registration process is proceeding smoothly.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0051 </DOCNO>
