<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1400 GMT October 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura hinted
Tuesday that Japan plans to express "remorse and apology" to
Beijing over its past war against China when Chinese President
Jiang Zemin visits Japan later this year.
</P>
<P>
The "remorse and apology" will be contained in a joint
statement the two countries will issue during Jiang's planned
visit, Komura told a press conference. (Japan-China-Apology)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has agreed to
allow the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
(OSCE) to monitor the situation in Kosovo, the country's news
agency Tanjug reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement came after the interruption of another round of
talks between Milosevic and U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke,
who arrived in Belgrade Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
On arrival, Holbrooke said he saw "promising possibilities" and
was hopeful of a move towards a peace. (Yugoslavia-OSCE-Agreement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Unarmed aircraft have been allowed to overfly the
territory of Yugoslavia to verify that Yugoslavia is abiding by
the U.N. resolutions on Kosovo, U.S. special envoy Richard
Holbrooke told reporters Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic also agreed, after a new
round of talks with Holbrooke, that the Organisation for Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) could monitor the situation in
Kosovo. (Yugoslavia-Kosovo-Overflight)
</P>
