<HEADLINE> Nepal Chooses New Deputy Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Bhoj Raj Joshi from the
ruling Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML) is sure
to become the new deputy speaker as he is the only candidate for
the post left vacant by Lila Subba Shrestha who resigned last
Saturday over parliament confrontation.
</P>
<P>
According to the Parliament Secretariat, former state minister
for education Joshi is the only candidate for the post by the
deadline of five o'clock Tuesday afternoon, vitiating the need of
election in the Lower House slated for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
After the expected announcement of Joshi as new deputy speaker
by Speaker Ram Chand Poudel in the House Wednesday, the House can
resume discussions on a motion tabled by the opposition parties
against Poudel.
</P>
<P>
The House session was adjourned for the last three days due to
the call for the election of a new deputy speaker.
</P>
<P>
Lila Subba Shrestha had resigned to avoid the humiliation of
forced resignation as her party, the main opposition Communist
Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML), cannot muster a
two-thirds majority in the Lower House to defeat a tit-for-tat
motion against her tabled by the ruling Nepali Congress (NC) and
the CPN-ML.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML and its ally the National Democratic Party (RPP,
Thapa) tabled their motion against the speaker on September 23,
six days after the passage in the House of the controversial Local
Autonomy Bill.
</P>
<P>
They accused Poudel from the NC of partisan conduct in
conducting voice voting on the bill and declaring its passage in
the House when the opposition MPs were voicing protest against it.
</P>
<P>
In a tit-for-tat move, the ruling parties registered in the
Parliament Secretariat the motion against Lila Subba Shrestha.
</P>
<P>
The speaker has refused to apologize or step down while the
opposition has rejected compromise and a proposal by the ruling
parties that both sides withdraw their motions.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML has threatened to make all its lawmakers to resign
en masse as an ultimate measure. However, this does not
necessarily mean the end of the majority government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
