<HEADLINE> China Becomes Mongolia's Biggest Exporter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, October 13 (Xinhua) -- China has become Mongolia's
biggest export market as its imports from Mongolia accounted for
27.1 percent of the latter's total export volume in the first nine
months of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics released Wednesday by the national
statistical bureau of Mongolia, Mongolia's foreign trade volume
totaled 555.6 million dollars, with export representing 218.2
million dollars and import making up 337.4 million dollars in the
first three quarters of this year.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign trade dropped 7.6 percent compared with
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
With the plummeting prices of copper and cashmere on the
international market, Mongolia witnessed a fall of 26.7 percent
in exports. Meanwhile, its imports increased 11.1 percent, which left
a 119.2 million-dollar trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
Among Mongolia's 71 trading partners, Russia accounted for 22.9
percent of Mongolia's total trade volume in the first nine months,
with 29.8 percent in imports and 12.3 percent in exports.
</P>
<P>
China's share in Mongolia's foreign trade amounted to 18.7
percent, with exports standing at 27.1 percent and imports at 13.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Swiss made up 10.6 percent with 26.9 percent in exports. Japan
and the Republic of Korea took 9.2 percent and 8.3 percent in
Mongolia's imports, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia's main export commodities are mineral and livestock
products such as concentrated copper powder and
cashmere. Machinery, transportation facilities and oil products
occupy 60 percent of Mongolia's import commodities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
