<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Drafts First River Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The new Yellow River Law
currently under deliberation is expected to provide legal
solutions to regional disputes resulting from water shortages and
unfair distribution, as well as serious soil erosion along China's
second largest river.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River Conservancy Commission is drafting the new
law, reportedly the first of its kind in the nation. The law has
received the full backing of the National People's Congress,
China's highest legislative body, according to Chen Xiaoguo,
deputy director of the commission.
</P>
<P>
"An expert team is currently reviewing a draft outline of the
law," said Chen. He told Xinhua News Agency today that the
commission under the Ministry of Water Resources will be
responsible for the administration of river issues.
</P>
<P>
Chen noted the lack of unified legal measures has hindered
efforts to control soil erosion and pollution, and has fueled
disputes in various areas due to the unreasonable distribution of
limited water resources.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River, which meanders over 5,400 km through nine
provinces in west and north China, is beset with mounting problems
related to the rising riverbed, interrupted water flow and
pollution. Nonetheless, the river has thus far provided an
adequate water supply for the valley area, one of most developed
and populous regions in China.
</P>
<P>
"We must adopt tough measures to rampant logging, pollution and
the abuse of water resources," said Chen.
</P>
<P>
Experts suggested the addition of stipulations for levying
water use fees and a use permission system in order to ensure the
rational and efficient use of river water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Okays Sharon's FM Appointment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli cabinet approved here
Tuesday the appointment of the hawkish Ariel Sharon as foreign
minister, the Prime Minister's Office said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu brought the appointment to
the cabinet for approval and the Knesset (parliament) Speaker Dan
Tichon will announce Sharon's appointment in the plenum later this
week or next week, the office added.
</P>
<P>
Under Israel's new election law, no vote is needed for
Sharon's appointment in the Knesset. Thus, Sharon has officially
become the new foreign minister of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry staffers on Tuesday voiced cautious
welcome to the appointment, saying that they are pleased to have a
full-time minister at the helm.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has been acting as foreign minister since David
Levy's resignation 10 months ago, and has himself admitted to
not always having enough time for the job.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu appointed Sharon, the former defense minister, to be
the foreign minister last Friday in a bid to placate the far right
as he moves closer to turning over more West Bank land to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
With his appointment, Sharon, 70, a staunch supporter of Jewish
settlements in the West Bank, is expected to quell opposition to
the concessions that Netanyahu is apparently prepared to make at
peace talks in Washington later this week.
</P>
<P>
Sharon has for months maintained that redeploying Israeli
troops from more than nine percent of the West Bank would be a
"national disaster."
</P>
<P>
But as foreign minister he will have to follow Netanyahu's
tune to withdraw from another 13 percent of the Palestinian
territories, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Sharon, a retired general and fought in every Israeli war, is a
leading figure of the Likud Party.
</P>
<P>
Sharon is Infrastructure Minister of the cabinet. Netanyahu
will name a new minister to take this post within three
months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
