Milosevic and Holbrooke held eight meetings in the past week to
find a peaceful solution to the crisis of Kosovo and a
breakthrough seems possible after Milosevic agreed to withdraw
troops from Kosovo and allow the presence of international
monitors in the province, where ethnic Albanian population
outnumber local Serb residents by nine to one.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, NATO on Tuesday night authorised air
strikes on Yugoslavia at any time but gave Yugoslav government
four days to comply with all U.N. demands which also include
the free access of international aid agencies in Kosovo and allow
thousands of refugees to go back home. 
