<HEADLINE> U.S. House Resolution on Taiwan's WHO Membership Opposed: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- China is strongly opposed to
the recent resolution adopted by the U.S. House of Representatives
on Taiwan's membership in the World Health Organization (WHO),
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Tang Guoqiang announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Tang described in his comments the resolution supporting
Taiwan's membership in the WHO as a document which "totally
disregards basic norms governing international relations and the
principles outlined in the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques."
</P>
<P>
He voiced China's strong opposition and stressed the resolution
encroaches upon China's sovereignty and interferes with the
nation's internal affairs."
</P>
<P>
As known to all, Tang noted, the WHO is an international
organization composed solely of sovereign states. Taiwan, an
integral part of China, is not eligible for WHO membership,
according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He added that U.S. President Bill Clinton visited China earlier
this year and explicitly reaffirmed that the United States would
adhere to "one China policy", refrain from supporting "one China,
one Taiwan," "two Chinas" or Taiwan's independence and would
refuse to support Taiwan's membership in international
organizations composed of sovereign states.
</P>
<P>
"We urge the U.S. government to strictly adhere to its serious
commitment on the Taiwan issue in real terms, clarify its
opposition to the aforementioned resolution, and adopt effective
measures to withhold support for any form of Taiwan's membership
in the WHO and various other international organizations composed
of sovereign states in order to avoid damaging the development
momentum of Sino-U.S. relations," the spokesman said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
