<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Criticizes Romania for Granting NATO Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav ambassador to
Bucharest Desimir Jevtic Tuesday criticized Romania for granting
NATO air access against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the daily Adevarul, Jevtic said that the
recent decision taken by the Romanian Supreme National Defense
Council (CSAT) to allow the NATO aircraft's access in emergency
and unforeseen situations is contrary to the bilateral treaty
between Romania and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He noted that paragraph 7 of the bilateral treaty stipulates
that "the sides are not to take part in or back war actions
against one another."
</P>
<P>
CSAT Sunday decided to grant access to its airspace to NATO's
aircraft "in case of emergency and unforeseen situations," in
response to a NATO request asking Romania to provide air corridor
for its possible strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the statements made by Romanian officials created a
climate where Romania could hardly be a mediator for resolving the
crisis in Kosovo, under the present circumstances," Jevtic said.
</P>
