<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Arrests Army Deserters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan police and army have
launched an islandwide massive operation to arrest security
personnel who have deserted the security services, according to an
official news release issued Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
According to a military spokesman, within only a few days after
the operation began, 2,106 deserters had been arrested, the
release said.
</P>
<P>
Both urban and rural level voluntary organizations have
extended their cooperation to this campaign to arrest army
deserters.
</P>
<P>
The security services are collecting information of hideouts of
the deserters. It is an offense punishable under Sri Lanka's law
to harbor the personnel who have deserted the security services,
the release said.
</P>
<P>
The army has announced that stringent action will be taken
against institutions which harbor or provide employment to such
deserters, the release added.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, the army has offered an amnesty to deserters on
seven occasions, and a total of 20,000 army deserters have
returned for their duty. During the latest amnesty on May 5-10
this year, over 5,000 deserters reportedly returned to duty.
However, there are still about 8,000 army deserters who failed to
respond to the amnesty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
