<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Lower But Market Tips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar slipped
a little lower Tuesday but traders tipped a resurgence in the unit
above 63.00 U.S. cents before the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
The local unit closed here at 62.36 U.S. cents, down from 62.58
at Monday's close.
</P>
<P>
"There's very good interest in the Aussie at the moment and I
think perceptions are a little bit more positive than they were a
few months back," Rothschild Australia treasury manager Paul
Macarounas said.
</P>
<P>
He said hedge funds were again particularly active in the
market.
</P>
<P>
"There's been a very good American name around the 62.20 U.S.
cents area buying and certainly he's absorbed a lot of Aussie
selling down there."
</P>
<P>
Macarounas said the local unit had consolidated over the past
24 hours within a 62.20 and 62.80 U.S. cents range.
</P>
<P>
"It's building up a little bit of a base around the 62.00 U.S.
cents area for an assault on 63.00 probably in the near future,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Such a move higher would be dependent on the direction of the
U.S. dollar/yen exchange rate, he said.
</P>
<P>
A sliding yen in local trade was blamed for the slight pullback
in the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
Japan's lower house of parliament passed the second part of its
crucial bank reforms, analysts regard the move as good news for
the Japanese economy in the long run which would in turn have a
beneficial impact on Australian exports.
</P>
<P>
However, speculation that the Bank of Japan would back the bill
by easing monetary conditions led to the Japanese currency's fall
against the U.S. dollar Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The local currency was buying 1.0274 German marks from 1.0274
Monday and 74.16 yen from 72.63 previously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
