<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen arrived in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia Tuesday where he
will hold talks with top Saudi leaders on the latest developments
in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
U.S. diplomatic sources told the Kuwait News Agency that Cohen
will meet with his Saudi counterpart Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz
on both political and military issues after inspecting U.S. troops
at Prince Sultan air base, south of Riyadh where U.S. military
aircraft are based.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the talks between the two defense ministers
will involve Iraq's refusal in August to cooperate with
U.N. inspectors in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Cohen reiterated Monday in Kuwait that "Iraq must fully comply
with the U.N. resolutions" and warned that the U.S. "reserves the
right to take military action if necessary."
</P>
<P>
He will also discuss with Prince Sultan issues concerning a
potential regional missile defense system that would, as claimed
by the U.S., help protect the area from missile attacks, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen is also scheduled to hold talks with Saudi King Fahd Ibn
Abdul-Aziz on matters of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is the last leg of Cohen's current Gulf tour which
has taken him to Bahrain, Qatar, the United Arab Emirates, Oman
and Kuwait. 
</P>
