<HEADLINE> Rwandan Army Kills 378 Infiltrators in Northwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan army mounted a big
military operation in northwest Rwanda in which 378 infiltrators
were killed, 19 captured, and 73 guns seized, Rwanda News Agency
(RNA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The operations covered Ruhengeri Region, and the region of
Bushiru, home region of late President Juvenal Habyalimana in
Gisenyi District in northwest of Rwanda which is known to be the
breeding ground of the two-year armed insurgency, a military
source in Ruhengeri said Monday night.
</P>
<P>
"From October 6 to 11, in Bushiru alone, 101 infiltrators were
killed, 16 assault rifles captured," the source
said, adding that among those captured in the area, there was
one commander Lt Col. Juvenal Ndayambaje, code -named "Magaara".
</P>
<P>
It is said that Magara acknowledged that he participated in
all attacks on Bushiru, including the big battle in which their
supreme commander, Lt Col. Leonard Nkuniye was killed on July 23.
</P>
<P>
Magara made important revelations about the collaboration
between the Rwandan infiltrators and the regime of embattled
Congolese president Laurent Desire Kabila.
</P>
<P>
"My commanders told me that they are in liaison with Kabila...
they communicate by Telcel," Magara was quoted as saying. He
explained that during the September 14 aborted attack on Goma,
they had been asked by Kabila to capture the airport.
</P>
<P>
"The capture of Goma would have been followed six hours later
by the landing of Kabila's planes loaded with arms and
reinforcement troops," Magara confided.
</P>
<P>
In clashes which took place in Ruhengeri region from October 8
to 11, 277 infiltrators were killed, 19 others captured alive,
military sources in Ruhengeri further indicated. A lieutenant
and a second-lieutenant of the rebels were killed in the
fighting, they told RNA.
</P>
<P>
One of the Rwandan infiltrators admitted that they lost many
men as well as an important military equipment.
</P>
<P>
Karenzi Karake, commander of the 408 Brigade, said the
army is putting military pressure on the infiltrators. Much of
the success of these operations is a result of a solid
collaboration between the army and local residents, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
