<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Opposes Possible NATO Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANTALYA, TURKEY, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Prime Minister
Momir Bulatovic warned Tuesday that possible NATO air strikes
against his country will destroy regional peace and stability and
be detrimental to neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference held here after the signing of a
joint declaration of a Balkan summit on the Kosovo crisis,
Bulatovic said Yugoslavia "strongly" opposes the would-be attacks
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) is preparing.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the military balance in the Balkans will be
jeopardized and arms race be triggered by NATO's possible actions.
</P>
<P>
NATO has threatened military attacks on Yugoslavia if it does
not comply with a United Nations Security Council resolution
demanding it to withdraw troops from its troubled province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia has pulled back its troops from Kosovo and fightings
there have ended, Bulatovic said, stressing that "the police
stationed there is not an army."
</P>
<P>
Albanian refugees have returned to their homeland, he added.
More than 90 percent of the Kosovo residents are ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav troops have been fighting since February the
separatist ethnic Albanians seeking independence of the Kosovo.
The armed conflicts have sparked refugee floods.
</P>
<P>
Bulatovic called those who were killed by the Yugoslav troops
"terrorists and separatists" attempting to remove Kosovo from
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
But Albanian Foreign Minister Paskal Milo disputed the Yugoslav
prime minister. Milo told the press conference that many innocent
Albanians in Kosovo have been killed by the Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
He said the Albanian government supports all NATO efforts aimed
at stopping violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said that "we are trying to
stop and prevent bloody conflicts in Kosovo and give the human
rights to all the nations in the region."
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz declined to comment on the possible NATO air strikes. "I
have no comment on this in the good atmosphere of the summit," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The prime ministers of Bulgaria, Greece, Macedonia, Romania,
Turkey and Yugoslavia and the Albanian foreign minister attended
the two-day summit, which ended Tuesday afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
