<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Urges Punishment for Foreign Exchange Rule Violations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- China's Supreme People's Court
has called for a major crack down on illegal activities involving
foreign exchange in order to safeguard the nation's smooth
economic order.
</P>
<P>
A court circular released recently notes that China has
maintained a stable exchange rate stable in spite of the economic
crisis sweeping some Asian nations countries.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the circular, some businesses and
individuals have falsified certificates or commercial documents to
purchase foreign exchange and illegally engage in foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
The illegal activities have seriously damaged the nation's
administration on financial order and foreign exchange
activities, menaced economic security and negatively impacted the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
The nation's highest court ordered courts at all levels to
investigate and deal with related criminal cases without delay,
with related investigation to be carried out in line with the
revised Criminal Law and the specific regulations issued by the
Supreme People's Court.
</P>
<P>
Local courts should investigate and punish any business or
individual involved in related offense, according to the
circular.
</P>
<P>
Court must also must severely punish criminal elements which
illegally purchase large amounts of foreign exchange and
unscrupulous government officials engaged in
related acts.
</P>
<P>
The state will confiscate all profits and property accrued
through illegal activities, as well as funds illegally used to
purchase foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme People's Court also urged local courts to cooperate
with public security departments and procuratorates in the
campaign.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strengthened Training of Labor Force Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 13 (Xinhua) -- An educated, skilled and
adaptable workforce is essential to employment growth and strong,
competitive enterprises in today's global economy, says a report
by the International Labor Organization (ILO).
</P>
<P>
The World Employment Report 1998-99, received here Tuesday,
said training systems worldwide are under pressure as employment
training cannot keep pace with demand in the labor market.
</P>
<P>
As the demand for skills shifts, it is not only "higher" skills
but "different" skills which are required to ensure the creation
of an employable labor force, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Training systems must react quickly and flexibly, as jobs and
skills are changing, said the report.
</P>
<P>
"There is a need for lifelong training, and more emphasis on
teamwork and interpersonal skills. The wage gap between skilled
and unskilled workers is increasing," it said.
</P>
<P>
The report estimated that at the end of 1998 over 1 billion
workers worldwide out of a total labor force of 3 billion will be
either unemployed or underemployed. Of these, 150 million are
estimated to be searching for work and cannot find it.
</P>
<P>
In East Asia, the numbers are staggering and show the immense
hardship, suffering and social tensions created by the financial
crisis. Open unemployment in the countries directly affected by
the East Asian crisis could rise by between 15 and 20 million,
with increases in poverty levels between three and four times this
amount, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report was the theme of a just-concluded workshop held
here, with the participation of representatives from the Thai
government, employers' and workers' organizations, academics and
the diplomatic community.
</P>
<P>
Rashid Amjad, former director of the ILO's Southeast Asia
Multidisciplinary Advisory Team, said at the workshop that
despite some positive developments, the global employment
situation remained grim. "There is mounting concern over the
social exclusion that follows limited employment opportunities."
</P>
<P>
At special risk are unemployed youth, the long-term unemployed,
older displaced workers, the less skilled, workers with
disabilities and ethnic minority groups, particularly women across
these categories who face barriers to employment, Amjad said.
</P>
<P>
He gave four main reasons for high and rising unemployment --
the East Asian crisis; far-reaching structural change in the
economies in transition to a market economy; a large growth of
labor supply as against slow growth and limited employment
opportunities, especially in South Asia; and jobless growth, where
growth has picked up but its impact on employment has been
minimal, as in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Amjad mentioned some characteristics of a well-functioning
training system:
</P>
<P>
-- Co-financing by the public and private sectors;
</P>
<P>
-- Co-determination and social partnership between government,
employers and workers to develop a training culture;
</P>
<P>
-- Greater cost-effectiveness through decentralization of
training delivery, with involvement of the private sector; and
</P>
<P>
-- Proper recognition systems for skills and competence.
</P>
<P>
Mitsuko Horiuchi, assistant director-general for ILO activities
in Asia and the Pacific, said at the workshop that the ILO "is
striving for more and better jobs for people everywhere." She
hoped that the workshop would stimulate discussion of skills
training in Thailand as a way of coping with a competitive global
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
