<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Lower on Japanese Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
Tuesday took little heed of buoyant United States and European
markets overnight, closing half a percent lower after taking its
lead from Japan, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index closed 13.1 points weaker at
2,488.5 after reaching a high of 2,517.9 earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Charlton Jones client adviser Brett O'Donovan said
the Australian bourse had a very disappointing day considering the
strong showing on overseas markets overnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the Dow Jones Industrial Average closed up 101.95
points at 8,001.47, after being up more than 170 points at one
stage.
</P>
<P>
"We were led lower by the Japanese market. It had a big impact
on us," O'Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei 225 in Japan closed down 312.22 points at 13,242.79,
down 2.3 percent and off a low of 13,241.20 points on the back of
investor caution over a government plan to inject additional funds
into banks' capital, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
On Australian equities markets, the all industrials index shed
20.1 points to 4,324.9 and the all resources index offloaded 8.1
to 1,016.5.
</P>
<P>
The National Australia Bank was the only major bank to buck the
negative trend, firming 3.6 cents, the ANZ slumped 29 cents, with
analysts saying it was likely someone was using the current low
share price to build up a strategic stake in the bank.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Bank shed 16, Westpac eased three.
</P>
<P>
News Corp. fell from a high of 9.38 Australian dollars to 9.17
following its annual general meeting in Adelaide.
</P>
<P>
News Corp. chairman and chief executive Rupert Murdoch said
Tuesday that no significant acquisitions were planned as the
company braced itself for a significant downturn in world markets.
</P>
<P>
Telstra topped the turnover table with 22.15 million
installment receipts traded as the stock slid 9.6 cents to 4.43
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resource sector, BHP fell 12 cents, WMC eased three and
Rio Tinto firmed four.
</P>
<P>
The gold index retreated 37.5 points to 1,175.1, with the gold
price in Sydney Tuesday afternoon closing at 296.75 U.S. dollars
an ounce, compared to a close of 296.65 Monday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 287.21 million shares traded for 867.44
million Australian dollars (546.48 million U.S. dollars) with
falling stocks outnumbering rising stocks 629 to 447, while 377
stocks remained steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
