<HEADLINE> Drivers Urge SADC to Standardize Toll Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's long distance truck
drivers have called on members of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) to standardize road transport toll
fees in the sub region.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Tuesday quoted the drivers as saying the
present arrangement where countries in the region charge
different toll fees is cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made in the wake of increased toll fees by the
Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The toll fees for vehicles delivering goods to Congo (K) have
gone up from 150 U.S. Dollars to 250 Dollars, according to the
Zambian newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"SADC has standardized vehicles registration books and driving
licenses in the region. The same should be extended to the toll
fees," said one Zimbabwean fuel truck driver.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia charges 116 Dollars toll fee per truck entering
the country from Chirundu to Kasumbalesa, a distance of 582
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
"Why should we pay 250 Dollars per truck from Kasumbalesa to
Lubumbashi (the second city in southern Congo) only 95 kilometers
away? " asked the driver. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
