<HEADLINE> Indian Military Exercises to Vitiate Pak-Indian Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Tuesday expressed
serious concern over the planned Indian military exercises near
Pakistan's border and described it as an attempt to vitiate the
atmosphere for the forthcoming bilateral talks.
</P>
<P>
"We are extremely disturbed over the nature, large size and
timing of these exercises," Foreign Ministry spokesman Tariq Altaf
said here at the weekly press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has conveyed its concern to the Indian High
Commissioner in Islamabad, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Defense Ministry Monday announced that India would
hold "routine" military exercises this month near the border with
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Foreign secretaries of Pakistan and India will resume their
stalled talks here from October 15 to 18 after suspension of about
13 months. The forthcoming bilateral talks will focus on two
issues--- peace and security, and Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
"We wonder as to what is the purpose of these exercises," the
spokesman said, adding that India has informed Pakistan that these
are routine exercises and not very close to Pakistan's border.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the date of the bilateral talks, the spokesman said
that separate meetings will be held on separate days on the two
priority issues -- peace and security, and Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the wake of the nuclear tests conducted by
India and Pakistan, "an inextricable linkage between stability of
the region and the issue of Jammu and Kashmir has been
established."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has always advocated a just and peaceful settlement of
the Kashmir dispute, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
It has always asked India to recognize the primacy and
paramountcy of the wishes of the Kashmiris which should be
determined through a fair and free plebiscite under the auspices
of the United Nations, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
