<HEADLINE> Ill-Prepared Cities Urged to Abandon World Cup Matches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 13 (Xinhua)-- The South Korean government on
Tuesday called for some of the 10 host cities for the 2002 World
Cup finals to drop out so that the games could be concentrated in
fewer cities.
</P>
<P>
Amid the economic crisis many of the 10 cities are
ill-prepared, falling short of cash for new stadiums, transport,
accommodation and other facilities. Some have not even begun
preparations.
</P>
<P>
But all the mayors of the 2002 cities rejected the call made
at a meeting with Culture and Tourism Minister Shin Nak-Kyun,
fearing the reaction of voters, a ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
The official stressed South Korea would never scale down the
2002 events, despite the country's prolonged economic crisis
which has depleted coffers of provincial cities, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Even if some cities give up their rights, other cities will
be able to digest the 32 matches as planned," he said.
</P>
<P>
Any modifications of South Korea's World Cup plan needs
approval from the world's football governing body, FIFA.
</P>
<P>
The ministry official said the issue could be discussed next
month when a six-man FIFA delegation visits South Korea and Japan
to inspect preparations for the 2002 World Cup finals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
