<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Tonnes of Narcotics Seized in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran seized more than two tonnes
of illicit drugs last week across the country, the official news
agency IRNA reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
IRNA quoted a report issued by the security forces as saying
that during anti-drug operations in the country's east, the
security forces seized 1,200 kilograms of opium and 800 kilograms
of morphine.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the security forces in Tehran confiscated 11
kilograms of heroin and arrested five people, including an Afghan
national in connection with drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Iranian Deputy Interior Minister
Gholamhussein Bolandian said that Iran seized more than 1,400
tonnes of various narcotics during the past 19 years and some 200
tonnes of drugs last year.
</P>
<P>
Iran passed a strict anti-drug law in 1989, which imposes
capital penalty on those who are caught with five kilograms of
opium or 30 grams of heroin.
</P>
<P>
No report was available about how many drug smugglers have been
executed since the law took effect.
</P>
<P>
Drug trafficking has been a serious problem for Iran during
the past decade since it serves as one of the major transit routes
for smuggling narcotics to Europe from Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea, Japan to Make Joint Scientific Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 13 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and Japan will carry
out a joint research on how hormone-disrupting chemicals pollute
fish and other creatures inhabiting streams near industrial
complexes, the South Korean Ministry of Environment said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Researchers from the two countries will investigate deformities
of fish, amphibians and reptiles as well as air, water and soil
polluted by hormone-disrupting chemicals.
</P>
<P>
They will also conduct a joint research on the testing method
of hormone-disrupting chemicals, which will be proposed by the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will meet in Seoul next month to determine
detailed issues concerning the research program.
</P>
<P>
The research is based on an action plan for a new Seoul-Tokyo
partnership for the next century, which was signed by South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung and Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obichi
last week in Tokyo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
