<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Media Baron Warns of Global Economic Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Media Baron Rupert Murdoch
Tuesday warned that the world was facing global economic crisis
and there was little governments could do about it.
</P>
<P>
Murdoch, chairman and chief executive of the global media group
News Corp. Ltd., repeatedly said at the company's annual general
meeting in Australia Tuesday that the world could be slipping into
a period of deflation or recession.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody is worried about the possibility of it," Murdoch
said when asked about the possibility of the world slipping into
recession in Adelaide, a coastal city in south Australia.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by the Australian Broadcasting Corporation Radio
as saying the big question globally was how much governments would
be able to do in such an economic climate.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's interesting around the world, the big question is
just how much governments will be able to do as against how much
central bankers will be able to do or how much markets will just
go past all those forces," Murdoch said.
</P>
<P>
"We are in a new paradigm today altogether and governments can
maybe soften the effects of violent movement in the markets, but
not much else," he said.
</P>
<P>
Murdoch has substantial stakes in printed and electronic media
in the United States, Britain, Australia and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The success of the film The Titanic helped boost the News Corp.
profits to 1.68 billion Australian dollars (one billion U.S.
dollars) for the past financial year ending June 30, 1998, with
the film reaping 1.8 billion U.S. dollars at the box office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
