<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Agrees to Allow OSCE to Monitor in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic has agreed to allow the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) to monitor the situation in Kosovo,
the country's news agency Tanjug reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement came after the interruption of another round of
talks between Milosevic and U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke,
who arrived in Belgrade Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
On arrival, Holbrooke said he saw "promising possibilities" and
was hopeful of a move towards a peace.
</P>
<P>
"In the last week, we've been engaged in tense discussions with
President Milosevic. As (U.S.) President (Bill) Clinton said a few
minutes ago in a public statement in New York, these discussions
have resulted in opportunities for significant steps forward on the
path towards peace and away from the danger of the war," Holbrooke
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic, who had held eight meetings with Holbrooke in the
past week over the issue of Kosovo, agreed to withdraw troops from
the province and allow the presence of international monitors in
the province where ethnic Albanian population outnumber local Serb
residents by nine to one.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, NATO on Tuesday night authorized air
strikes on Yugoslavia at any time but gave the Yugoslav government
four days to comply with all the U.N. demands which also include
free access of international aid agencies in Kosovo and permit
thousands of refugees to go back home.
</P>
<P>
Western countries have exerted tremendous military pressure to
force Yugoslav leaders to back down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
