<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Globalization to Be Continued in Face of Crisis: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Deputy Prime
Minister Lee Hsien Loong said here Tuesday that the world should
continue to pursue more openness and globalization although the
current economic crisis has exposed the downside risk of
globalization.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a luncheon jointly organized by the Singapore
Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong and the General Chamber of
Commerce of Hong Kong, Lee said that the world should not
backtrack on the trend towards liberalization and market oriented
policies in face of the economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
Lee arrived in Hong Kong Sunday to attend a gala charity
concert of the Singapore Symphony Orchestra for the HK Red Cross
together with Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
Lee told hundreds of local and Singapore businessmen present at
the luncheon that the progressive lowering of barriers to trade
and investment and the adoption of market oriented policies in
many countries underpinned an unprecedented period of sustained
growth and prosperity in the half century since World War Two.
</P>
<P>
Free trade enabled many economies to take advantage of global
markets, and promoted the efficient allocation of resources, Lee
said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign capital brings growth, but it can also transmit
instability and external shocks, Lee pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Some countries are attempting to solve these problems brought
on by globalization by cutting off free flow of capital and
isolating themselves from the effects of global markets.
</P>
<P>
"But backtracking from globalization cannot be the solution for
the world," the Singapore deputy prime minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
Without global free trade, there would not be global companies
like Intel, Airbus, Citicorp or Honda.
</P>
<P>
In the 1930s, countries erected trade barriers and sought to
solve their problems individually. This led to not a more stable
systems but to a world war, Lee noted.
</P>
<P>
In particular, small, open economies like Singapore and Hong
Kong, which are heavily dependent on a free flow of trade and
investments, cannot afford to cut themselves off from the world,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"We should therefore reaffirm our faith in the global economic
and trade system," Lee said. "We should contribute to
international efforts to strengthen the global financial
framework, and strive to maintain and expand the liberalization in
trade and investment achieved over the years."
</P>
<P>
"Both Singapore and Hong Kong are too small to have a decisive
voice. But we should nevertheless participate actively in the
debate, to help bring about an outcome that furthers not only our
vital interests, but also the common interest of the global
trading community," he continued.
</P>
<P>
Tackling the crisis requires international efforts to deal with
the systemic dangers to the global financial system and national
efforts to resolve problems within each country, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
Internationally, the immediate priority is to calm the world
capital markets, and prevent shaky economies in Latin America and
Russia from spreading the contagion to the United States and
Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
The longer term task is to remedy weaknesses in the
architecture of the international financial system, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
Transparency, accountability, and disclosure standards of key
macroeconomic data must all be improved and internationally
accepted standards of auditing and accounting must be developed
and adopted.
</P>
<P>
Surveillance mechanisms should be put in place to head-off
potential crises, he added.
</P>
<P>
In response to the crisis, Singapore is reducing business costs
to help firms tide over the crisis and workers to keep their jobs.
</P>
<P>
Singapore is also looking beyond the crisis to make strategic
shifts in the policies, and enable the economy to grow on a
sustained basis after this crisis has passed, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
"Singapore and Hong Kong are friendly rivals," the deputy prime
minister said. "We have always believed that Singapore benefits
from a vibrant and prosperous Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
"Knowing the resilience and enterprise of the Hong Kong people,
I have every confidence that you will soon overcome your current
problems and bounce back, as you have done so often before," lee
said.
</P>
<P>
When the region recovers, Hong Kong and Singapore can once
again become twin cities of prosperity in Asia, contributing to
and benefiting from the region's growth and process, Lee
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
