<HEADLINE> APEC Tourism Working Group Meeting Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The 13th Meeting of Asia
Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) Tourism Working Group (TWG)
opened Tuesday in Malaysia with an appeal for greater cooperation
among APEC members to promote tourism growth in the region.
</P>
<P>
Opening the two-day meeting in Langkawi, a resort island in
northern Malaysia, Malaysian Culture, Arts and Tourism Minister
Sabbaruddin Chik stressed the need for greater and more active
role through cooperation among APEC member economies to alleviate
the effects of the currency crisis by promoting tourism growth in
the affected economies.
</P>
<P>
In this time of financial crisis in some of the APEC member
economies where the tourism sector had been adversely affected, it
is even more important to reexamine the TWG programs to ensure
sustainable growth of the tourism industry, Sabbaruddin said.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia supported the APEC objectives set in the Seoul
APEC Declaration of November 14, 1991 and concurred with the
recommendation that sustainable growth of tourism in the APEC
region should be encouraged as a means of generating benefits for
all member economies.
</P>
<P>
Sabbaruddin said efforts should be made to remove impediments
in order to facilitate the flow of tourists whilst human resource
development should be promoted to ensure quality tourism service.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia, therefore, seeks the cooperation of all member
economies and together we shall find solutions to overcome the
problems facing the tourism industry", he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 tourism officials from Malaysia, Australia, Indonesia
and Singapore are attending the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
