<HEADLINE> Urgent: Unarmed Aircraft Allowed to Overfly Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Unarmed aircraft have been
allowed to overfly the territory of Yugoslavia to verify that
Yugoslavia is abiding by the U.N. resolutions on Kosovo,
U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke told reporters Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic also agreed, after a new
round of talks with Holbrooke, that the Organisation for Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) could monitor the situation in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"On the ground, the OSCE will have in Kosovo 2,000 persons who
will be a verification mission, not monitors, not observers, and
they will be here with full permission of the Yugoslav
government," Holbrooke said at a press conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
