<HEADLINE> Culture Feature: Verdi's Aida Back to Pyramids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The background is the Great
Pyramids sihlouetted against the starry sky. Bravos are from an
audience of 3,600. On the stage is Giueseppe Verdi's Aida, one of
the most performed opera in history, coming back to where it
premiered 127 years ago.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to boost the sluggish tourism, Egypt spent 12
million Egyptian pounds (about 3.5 million U.S. dollars) to make
Egypt's version of Aida the most lavish production of the opera.
</P>
<P>
In one scene, the soldiers trekked 50 meters to a real-size
temple in the desert where the hero was to be executed.
</P>
<P>
At the Monday night's opening show in Cairo, the world's
leading Verdi sopranos, Maria Guleghina, Leona Mitchell and Lucia
Mazaria, shared the title role, while tenors Vladimir Galouzine
and Nicola Marinucci played Radames, Aida's lover.
</P>
<P>
About 800 singers and dancers from Egypt, Italy, France, Russia
and Germany unrolled the doomed love story between an Ethiopian
slave girl and an ancient Egyptian conqueror on an elevated stage
at the foot of the pyramids.
</P>
<P>
"It is like Aida back home, a feast," remarked local opera buff
Amal Fahmy, a part-time writer for local Al-Ahram newspaper's art
and entertainment news and a two-time goer of Egypt's version of
Aida.
</P>
<P>
The opera was commissioned to Verdi (1813-1910) by Khedive
Ismail of Egypt to mark the opening of the Suez Canal in 1869 but
its debut in Cairo was delayed for about three years.
</P>
<P>
"This Aida is very Egyptian," said Yelman Fiorilo, an Italian
architect working in Cairo. "Its music is enhanced by the
pyramids, temples and Egypt's rich heritage."
</P>
<P>
But for Egyptians, Opera Aida is rather more a measure to bring
the tourism from the year-old doldrums than merely a cultural or
business event.
</P>
<P>
Aida chief director and ballet dancer Abdel Monem Kamel told
Xinhua that he does not care how much money is spent, because
Egypt is using it as a major event to restore its tourist heaven
image.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's tourism is recovering from a heavy blow by a terrorist
attack in November last year which killed 58 tourists in southern
city Luxor.
</P>
<P>
"We're marketing for Egypt, instead of Aida. It tells the world
Egypt is still alive, and Egypt has something big (to offer),"
Kamel said.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Kamy, opera singer and executive producer of Aida
events, said he does not expect Aida to spin money.
</P>
<P>
The prices of the six shows in Cairo ranges from 75 to 250
U.S. dollars. The opening night was mainly reserved for VIPs and a
handful of journalists. At the rest of the five shows, one third
of the audience will be tourists, and the rest, the local
celebrities.
</P>
<P>
With heavy presence of security men around the site, Egypt's
First Lady Susan Mubarak, Prince Henrik, husband of Queen
Margrethe II of Denmark and wives of a number of heads of state
attended Monday night's three-hour opening show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
