<BODY>
<HEADLINE> River Dredging Program Begins in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
taken up a massive river dredging program to reduce the impact of
floods in the future, it was learned from the Prime Minister's
Office Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Through dredging, the depth of the rivers in the country will
be increased, thus helping reduce the impact of floods, official
sources told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the soil coming from the dredging will be
used for reclamation of land beside the rivers, they said, adding
such land will be used for setting up townships and industries.
</P>
<P>
Under this year's program for dredging, 25 million cubic meters
of soil will be removed from the river beds.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 11.5 million cubic meters of soil will be removed by
dredging the Gorai river only this year.
</P>
<P>
A rough estimate of over 36 million cubic meters of silt
usually accumulate in the rivers across the country every year due
to floods.
</P>
<P>
About 30 million cubic meters of soil will be removed from the
navigational routes in the rivers of Padma, Jamuna, Meghna and
Buriganga.
</P>
<P>
Dredging of the Padma started on September 25 and 70,000 cubic
meters of soil have already been removed by utilizing two
dredgers. Another dredger is being used to dredge the Jamuna
river, they added.
</P>
<P>
Situated in South Asia between India and Myanmar, Bangladesh
has as many as 230 rivers which form three major river systems --
Ganges, Brahmaputra and Meghna with their tributaries
crisscrossing the country.
</P>
<P>
Flood is a common phenomenon since the country is low-lying.
</P>
<P>
This year, this South Asian country experienced the worst-ever
floods in a century, which had gripped as much as two-thirds of
the country for 10 weeks and seriously affected 30 million people,
inflicting a preliminary estimated loss of around 4.3 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
