<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Infrastructure Giant Unveils New Structure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's biggest
infrastructure company Conglomerate Renong Bhd Tuesday announced
an overhaul of its corporate structure.
</P>
<P>
Publicly listed Renong Bhd's activities are now streamlined
into four business divisions comprising construction and
engineering, expressways, property development and transportation
against seven divisions -- engineering, construction and
infrastructure; expressways and tolls; telecommunications, power,
information technology and media; property development and hotel;
oil and gas services department; transportation and financial
services.
</P>
<P>
Renong Bhd's Managing Director Zakhir Sidek said at a press
conference here that the restructuring was to ensure the companies
within the group fully realize the synergy possible among the
various companies and to ensure the management focused on core
activities meet corporate goals.
</P>
<P>
Renong Bhd made the announcement four days after it proposed a
major debt restructuring exercise involving the issue of 10.5
billion ringgit (2.763 billion U.S. dollars) of government-backed
bonds to settle its short-term debts and national strategic
infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
Renong's new corporate structure is purely a management
governance restructuring exercise and not a change in legal
ownership, the managing director said, adding, "There will also be
no asset and capital shuffling."
</P>
<P>
He said each of the four divisions will be headed by a
president who will report directly to Executive Chairman Halim
Saad.
</P>
<P>
The decentralization of operational decision-making and the
consolidation of operating companies by sector are expected to
provide for clearer accountability, greater attention to
developing national and regional competitiveness in each industry
and a sharper focus on maximizing value and returns to all stake
holders, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
