<HEADLINE> Asia's Largest Electronics Fair Held in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Electronics Fair
'98, the largest of its kind in Asia, opened here on Tuesday,
highlighting Hong Kong's role as Asia's top sourcing hub for the
electronics industry.
</P>
<P>
"With nearly 10,000 enterprises producing and trading
electronics products, Hong Kong is Asia's top sourcing center,"
enjoying a "well-deserved reputation as a reliable supplier in all
major markets," Victor Lo, chairman of Provisional Hong Kong
Science Park Company Ltd., told the fair's opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"While economic problems have certainly dampened our business
prospects in some markets, the demand for Hong Kong electronics
remains exceptionally strong elsewhere, including North America,
Europe and beyond," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the world's fourth largest electronics exporter.
Last year, electronics accounted for almost 30 percent of all Hong
Kong exports.
</P>
<P>
For the first seven months of this year, Hong Kong's
electronics trade continued to flourish, with exports amounting
to 29.5 billion U.S. dollars, up 1 percent against last year, Lo
said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the rising demand is partly because Hong
Kong excels in efficient management which allows for short
delivery time and compliance with international quality standards,
and partly due to new technology, which creates new products and
shortens the products' life cycles.
</P>
<P>
The four-day event, organized by the Hong Kong Trade
Development Council (TDC), celebrated its 18th anniversary this
year and boasted itself the largest ever electronics fair in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,380 exhibitors from 19 countries and regions are
participating, 21 percent more than last year, with group
pavilions staged by the Chinese mainland, South Korea, Taiwan and
Malaysia, Allan Wong, chairman of TDC's Electronics/Electrical
Appliances Advisory Committee, told the ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
