<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Normalizes Ties With WB, IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Minister of Finance
Malam Ismaila Usman has said the coast is now clear for Nigeria
to resume normal relations with the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) as well as its creditors.
</P>
<P>
He told the News Agency of Nigeria that after holding a series
of meetings and intensive consultations with officials of the Two
Bretton Woods institutions during their just-concluded annual
meetings, he was in a position to say that Nigeria was back on
the right track with its friends, including the multi-lateral
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
"We have been involved in a series of talks that are positive
and we are now in a position to begin to talk normally and
regularize our contacts and connections with them," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister also met with the vice-chairman of the Paris Club
of creditors, which is the first time Nigeria is having access to
the club in the five years.
</P>
<P>
According to Usman, the vice-chairman agreed to give him some
information to help update figures on Nigeria's indebtedness.
</P>
<P>
A technical team from Nigeria was also invited to talks with
the Paris Club to sort out figures on the country's external
debts, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that because of lack of contact between Nigeria
and its creditors, it has been impossible for both parties to
reconcile their figures on the level of Nigeria's debtedness.
</P>
<P>
Now that Nigeria has normalized its relations with the World
Bank and the IMF, he said, the country expects to seek some
assistance from the institutions in respect of the infrastructure
that would enable the country to keep a tab on its debts.
</P>
<P>
"The fact is that if we need technical assistance from them,
they will help us put the computers in place and train our
people, then these figures will be made available readily and
easily," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
