<HEADLINE> Closure of Refinery Set to Worsen Fuel Crisis in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The existing fuel crisis in
Nigeria is set to worsen following the closure of the Warri
Refinery and the Warri oil depot, according to press reports here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The refinery which was the only one working out of the four in
the country and the Warri Depot of the Pipeline and Product
Marketing Company were compelled to shut down following the
collapse of its three turbines which generate power for the two
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The management of the power plant had been using one gas
turbine for its operations since the other two packed up two
years ago, sources in Warri said, adding that the only one also
broke down last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Efforts by the management to repair the power plant failed as
it could not find the spare part to replace the damaged one in
the local market.
</P>
<P>
The disruption of the refinery's activities has heightened
fears of a worsening of the lingering nationwide fuel scarcity as
the Warri Refinery is the only one functioning in the major
oil-exporting country in Nigeria, press reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
