<HEADLINE> Vietnam Not to Devalue Forex Rate: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam will not devalue further
its foreign exchange rates, the Saigon Times daily reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The English-language daily quoted Nguyen Doan Hung as saying
that further adjustment of foreign exchange rates is not needed as
the state can now control the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
"The state has sufficient tools to control and regulate the
forex market through administrative and economic measures and
especially newly adopted forex policies," said the official.
</P>
<P>
Asian currencies have begun to pick up, so Vietnam will not
need to further devalue the dong if it does not experience any
substantial (financial) turmoil, Hung said.
</P>
<P>
The interbank foreign exchange market is playing an
increasingly important role, the official said, adding that
"Through it, the state can maintain forex rates at the current
levels."
</P>
<P>
The free forex market does exist, but it cannot affect forex
rates as unofficial dealers only account for a small share of the
market, Hung noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the regional financial crisis has indirectly resulted
in the appreciation of the dong against other regional currencies.
</P>
<P>
But the local currency has started to rebound as the state bank
has set the official daily rate at 12,998 VN dong per dollar
instead of 11,815 VN dong, and narrowed the upper limit of the
pivot rate from ten percent to seven percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
