<HEADLINE> Justice Int'l Wants to Be Observer at Malaysian  Former Deputy PM's Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The London-based Justice
International Commission on Human Rights (JICHR) wanted to be an
observer during the trial of former Malaysian deputy prime
minister Anwar Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
The request was made by JICHR Director Sayyad Mohy Eddeen in a
note handed to the secretary of Chief Judge of Malaya Wan Adnan
Ismail.
</P>
<P>
Sayyad and JICHR Chairman John Platts-Mill failed to see Wan
Adnan at his chambers Monday as they did not make prior
appointment to see the latter, Sayyad said at a news conference in
his hotel suite here.
</P>
<P>
The Justice International Commission officials arrived here
Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
Sayyad said the JICHR hoped to get a clear picture about
Anwar's arrest under the Internal Security Act and his impending
trials.
</P>
<P>
The JICHR is an independent non-governmental global network of
lawyers promoting international human rights standards, justice
and fair trial worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Sayyad denied they were attempting to interfere in Malaysia's
law administration but were merely trying to see that justice is
carried out.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to make clear that we are in no way trying to interfere
into the administration of the law in the country. We're not going
to legally defend Anwar although we had been asked by his family
when we met them yesterday, to help in ensuring that justice is
obtained by him," he said.
</P>
<P>
Platts-Mill, who was also present at the news conference, said
the JICHR would send three to four representatives here to observe
the trial scheduled to begin next month.
</P>
<P>
The High Court here has fixed November 2 to 14 to hear four of
the five charges of corrupt practices against Anwar who has
pleaded not guilty to the five charges and also to five counts of
sodomy.
</P>
<P>
The trial dates for the other six charges have yet to be fixed.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, 51, was dismissed as deputy prime minister and finance
minister on September 2 and removed from the ruling United Malays
National Organization (UMNO) of which he was deputy president a
day later and was detained under the ISA on September 20. 
</P>
