<HEADLINE> Foreign Firms to Make Privatization Plan for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Two foreign consortiums signed
their final agreements with the Royal Jordanian (RJ) late Monday
here to hammer out plans to privatize the debt-ridden national
carrier, the semi-official Jordan Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
France's Bank Paribas, the RJ's financial adviser, and the
British Clifford Chance Company, the RJ's legal adviser, will
get 2 million U.S. dollars from the World Bank to complete the
plan in eight months, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements, the consortium of financial advisers
will evaluate the RJ's assets, restructure its balance sheet and
recommend ways to handle its debts and financial obligations.
</P>
<P>
The consortium will eventually market the main parts of the
airlines, which will include the aviation and technical support
sectors, while its remaining business, such as duty-free shops,
engineering services and catering, will be part of a
government-owned company.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the consortium of legal advisers will help the
government improve its regulations of the airlines, make clear the
RJ's legal liabilities, establish reasonable relationship between
the RJ and the Civil Aviation Authorities under the government
as well as between the RJ and other concerned parties.
</P>
<P>
The RJ is now 700 million Jordanian dinars (about 989 million
U.S. dollars) in debt due to years of mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
Privatization of the airlines is part of the government's plan
which was launched in 1989 to tap potential of the private
sector, draw foreign investment and finally streamline and
privatize large-scale and state-owned companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
