<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Say Water Waste Dries Yellow River Lower Reaches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists recently
discovered that the waste of water in the Yellow River valley is
the major cause of frequent interrupted water flow on the lower
reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) visited four
provinces on the lower and middle reaches of the river in July to
document existing problems.
</P>
<P>
CAS academician Liu Changming said that most parts of the river
valley are arid areas without rich water resources, and per capita
water use here is only-fourth that of the national average.
</P>
<P>
"Sharp declines in rainfall and surface runoff during the 1990s
are one of the reasons for interrupted water flow," he said.
</P>
<P>
But he noted that even during the decade-long droughts in the
1920s, when runoff water declined by 34 percent, water flow was
not interrupted. Since 1990, however, the runoff has declined 19
percent, and the lower reaches recorded 13 dry spells last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the investigation, booming agriculture and
industry along the river banks have increased the demand for
water. Water pumped from the river is now one and a half times
more than in the 1950s, and nearly five times more on the lower
reaches. Thus, the river is now failing to meet water-supply demand.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that serious waste and pollution of these limited water
resource are worsening an already grave situation.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of the water drawn from the river is used
for irrigation, but poor diversion facilities and a blunted sense
of conservation has resulted in the low utilization rate of 25
percent. The water recycling rate of industry is about 40 percent
or lower, and the waste water disposal rate in the valley is
lower than 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
Satistics show that frequent interrupted water flow has
occurred since the 1970s, and this situation has only become worse
over the years.
</P>
<P>
The Lijin Hydrometric Station in east China's Shandong Province
at the Bohai Sea estuary recorded dry conditions for 330 days
last year, and water stopped flowing in sections of the river
stretching a total of 704 kilometers, with 90 percent of this
section located on the lower reaches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Role in Vietnam's Socio-Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese women play an
important role in the country's socio-economic development,
official media here reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Women make up 52 percent of Vietnam's national workforce in all
branches and occupations, especially in health care and education.
</P>
<P>
Women account for 26 percent of all deputies to the National
Assembly, tenth legislature (1997-2002), up 8.5 percent over the
ninth legislature.
</P>
<P>
According to the inter-Parliamentary Union, this percentage has
placed Vietnam 13th among 171 countries in the number of female
parliamentarians.
</P>
<P>
Women make up 10-15 percent of the Party Central Committee
members and 15-20 percent of the People's Council members at all
levels.
</P>
<P>
During the past 10 years, 19 Vietnamese women scientists and 13
groups of Vietnamese women scientists have received the
Kovalevskaya Prize for their achievements in maths, physics,
chemistry, biology, medicine, agriculture and industry.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese women have also proved their adaptability to the
market economy.
</P>
<P>
Between 1992 and 1997, the number of women directors of private
enterprises nationwide increased five-fold.
</P>
<P>
In Ho Chi Minh City alone, there are 1,842 women directors
employing 44,700 work hands. The private enterprises directed by
women entrepreneurs in the city have a total investment capital of
1,265 billion VN dong (973 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, women are still facing difficulties in their work.
Working women get only 72 percent of men's wage for the same type
of work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elephants Terrorize Zambian Village </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Wild elephants crossing over
from neighboring Zimbabwe into Chalokwa village in Siavonga, 200
kilometers southeast of the Zambian capital Lusaka, are
terrorizing residents there.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the villagers have been forced to stay indoors
and their children abandoned school, according to Times of Zambia
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The elephants crossed the Zambezi River into the area in
search for food like their favorite acacia trees which are
abundant there.
</P>
<P>
Banana plantations and gardens have been damaged by the
elephants.
</P>
<P>
The headman of the village is worried that the elephants
inundating the area will derail field preparations before the
onset of the rains next month, saying this will perpetuate hunger
in the area while grade-seven pupils may perform badly in their
final examinations which are just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
The Department of National Parks and Wildlife has since sent a
game scout to clear the elephants from the area but villagers are
not happy with the way he is handling the situation by just
scaring them away with gunshots.
</P>
<P>
The villagers said the elephants will continue to terrorize
them unless some are shot at.
</P>
<P>
They demand a permanent security arrangement by the wildlife
services department.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the villagers called on the wildlife services to
crop a hippo which is also terrorizing them, saying it is more
vicious as it charges at people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
