<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half Italian Young Women Do Not Want Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 12 (Xinhua) -- One out of two Italian young women
do not want to have children, according to a poll taken recently
by a women's magazine "Noi Donne" (We Women).
</P>
<P>
The magazine polled 520 women aged between 16 and 24. The
result is 52 percent of those women do not want children, with 29
percent uncertain and only 19 percent, or one out of five, wanting
children.
</P>
<P>
The study found that about 70 percent of Italian young women
intend to have children several years after marriage, maybe over
30 years old or even 35.
</P>
<P>
More than half the women not wanting children gave the
professional advancement as the cause while less than half are
concerned with the social environment the child would have to grow
up in, the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
Other reasons included fear of responsibility, fear of
childbirth and dislike of children.
</P>
<P>
Among those who want children, 27 percent said one is enough,
23 percent want two, and only one of ten want three or more.
</P>
<P>
This age group of women approve child-adoption by gay couples
and single parents. The study found that single parenthood was
popular. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swaziland's Economy on Downward Trend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Swaziland is confronted
with a high unemployment rate, massive retrenchment, excessive
government spending, high inflation, huge domestic and foreign
debt and declining social service.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, the Swazi economy has been on a downward trend,
manifesting itself in an increasing unemployment rate, which
stands above 20 percent of the total economically active male
population and a decline in real incomes, local daily Business
Day reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This high unemployment rate and stagnated food production
levels are indicative of an economy that is failing to support
and sustain the population, University of Swaziland lecturer
Mandla Masuku was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
When outgoing Swazi Finance Minister Themba Masuku presented
his budget speech earlier this year, he announced a national
deficit which now stands at about 32 million U.S. Dollars, up
from about 7.16 million Dollars in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The deficit represents 4.5 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP) and Swazi economists say it poses serious future
economic implications.
</P>
<P>
The Swazi economic growth has stagnated at 2.7 percent a year,
way below the population growth estimated at 3.4 percent
annually. This means Swaziland is becoming poorer by 0.9 percent
each year, local economic analysts said.
</P>
<P>
A possible revenue loss of millions when the sharing formula
of the Southern African Customs Union is effected later this
year, will provide more economic challenges.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland received half of its revenue of more than 17 million
Dollars last year from the union's common revenue sharing pool.
</P>
<P>
More than one-third of the country's GDP and about 40 percent
of government revenue comes from union proceeds.
</P>
<P>
Dumisani Masilela, senior official and financial expert in the
Swazi Finance Ministry, said Swaziland's economy was pillared by
the share received from the union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
