<HEADLINE> Stolen Beijing Buddhist Statue Recovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Police in this Chinese capital
have recovered a precious ancient Buddhist statue that was stolen
six month ago and have arrested four suspects believed to be
involved in the theft.
</P>
<P>
The stone Buddhist statue, weighing about one ton, dates back
1,500 years to the Northern Wei Dynasty. It is one of the oldest
Buddhist statues ever found in Beijing and is considered a gem of
a cultural relic for its graceful shape and finely crafted
workmanship.
</P>
<P>
The statue was kept at a village temple in the Haidian District
of Beijing from which it was stolen on March 25 this year.
</P>
<P>
After six months of intensive investigation, police discovered
the statue buried in five pieces at the home of Liu Xueru, a
farmer in Quyang County in Hebei Province which surrounds the city
of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
According to confessions from the detained suspects, seven
people took part in the theft and planned to sell the statue
for 200,000 yuan (about 25,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Police are trying to trace the other three suspects while
cultural-relics professionals restore the fragmented statue, which
eventually will be displayed at the Beijing Stone Crafts
Museum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
