<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientists Plan to Map Soybean Genetic Code </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists are
planning to map some of the soybean genetic code, or genome,
according to reports from a number of U.S. universities Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously we are not going to determine the function of all
80,000 or 100,000 genes in the plant. But we're providing a set of
information that will be useful for other researchers," said Lila
Vodkin, a professor of soybean genetics at the University of
Illinois and leader of the study.
</P>
<P>
The project is part of the National Science Foundation's Plant
Genome Program, and the other researchers involved are based at
Iowa State University, Northern Arizona University, the University
of Missouri and the University of Minnesota, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The University of Illinois is the leading institution for the
project, which is somewhat similar to the national human genome
project.
</P>
<P>
But scientists said the soybean project is more limited in scope
because it will only focus on determining the "expression" of
thousands of soybean genes. That means where the genes actually
show up in the plant -- in roots, shoots, leaves, flowers and
seeds -- which then gives researchers a clue to what factors the
gene actually influences.
</P>
<P>
The information could then be used by other researchers to help
increase soybean yields, develop disease resistance or make
soybeans more nutritious, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is expected to continue for four years, will
cost 4.4 million U.S. dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
