<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poorer S. African Schools to Get More Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will direct
more funds to poorer schools in order to correct educational
injustices of the past, local media reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the new National Norms and Standards for School Funding
Bill, South African schools will be divided into five categories
based on their financial needs, measured against the level of
poverty in the community, and the condition of the school itself.
</P>
<P>
Unveiling the bill, South African Education Minister Sibusiso
Bengu said recently that the richest 20 percent of schools would
receive five percent of resources available to provincial
education departments, while the poorest 20 percent would get 35
percent.
</P>
<P>
Bengu said the new norms were based on the principles of
equity and redress.
</P>
<P>
"They ensure that whatever funds are available to provincial
education departments will be spent fairly, so that schools in
greatest need get preference."
</P>
<P>
The bill would be implemented in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to regulations drafted alongside the bill, parents
could apply for full or partial fee exemptions.
</P>
<P>
If the combined gross annual income of the parents is less
than 10 times the annual school fees per pupil, the parents
qualify for full exemption. In the case of a combined annual
gross income of less than 30 times of the annual fee per child, a
partial exemption will be granted.
</P>
<P>
But once the parents have signed agreements with schools to
pay fees, they cannot renege on the deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
