<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerians Favor President from South: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- A poll on the on-going
transition program indicated an overwhelming support for the
emergence of the next civilian president from the southern part
of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The poll conducted by Polls and Ratings Limited showed that
390 out of the 500 respondents support a president from the south
of the country while 100 respondents are undecided and only 10
stand for a northern presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
The poll also said 311 respondents representing 62.2 percent
express optimism at the credibility of the on-going transition
program while 37 (7.4 percent) have reservations, The Post
Express newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Prior to National Day broadcast made on October 1 by Nigerian
Head of State General Abdulsalam Abubakar, respondents were more
optimistic about the transition program, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
However, it noted, this reduced drastically after his
broadcast with many returning "can't say" verdict.
</P>
<P>
Roland Arabome, managing director of Polls and Ratings Limited
which is a public opinion polls, market surveys, research and
propaganda outfit, said the choice of Lagos for the exercise is
because the city is reportedly "replete with about 20,000 of the
officially declared ethnic groups in Nigeria". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
