<HEADLINE>   Malaysian Former Deputy PM Files Appeal Over Bail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Former Malaysian deputy
prime minister Anwar Ibrahim, facing charges of corrupt practices
and sodomy and now in police custody under the Internal Security
Act, Tuesday filed a notice of appeal over the High Court decision
to refuse bail.
</P>
<P>
The notice was filed at the High Court registry here by Messrs.
S. N. Nair &AMP; Partners, according to the Malaysian national news
agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
The appeal will be heard at the Court of Appeal, but the date
has yet to be fixed, Bernama quoted lawyer S.N. Nair as saying.
</P>
<P>
Anwar's application for bail was made on October 5 after the
High Court fixed November 2 to 14 to hear four of the five charges
of corrupt practices against Anwar who has pleaded not guilty to
the five charges and also to five counts of sodomy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the High Court has fixed October 24 to hear a
'habeas corpus' application filed on October 8 by Anwar's wife for
his release from detention under the Internal Security Act.
</P>
<P>
The application names Inspector-General of Police Abdul Rahim
Noor as the respondent.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, 51, was dismissed as deputy prime minister and finance
minister on September 2 and removed from the ruling United Malays
National Organization (UMNO) of which he was deputy president a
day later and was detained under the Internal Safety Act on
September 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
