<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Apologize to China Over War: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Minister
Masahiko Komura hinted Tuesday that Japan plans to express
"remorse and apology" to Beijing over its past war against China
when Chinese President Jiang Zemin visits Japan later this year.
</P>
<P>
The "remorse and apology" will be contained in a joint
statement the two countries will issue during Jiang's planned
visit, Komura told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese foreign minister said that he thinks it better for
Japan to express in the joint statement the country's official
view of its 1937-1945 war against China.
</P>
<P>
Japan expressed "deep remorse and heartfelt apology" to South
Korea for its 1910-1945 colonial rule of the Korean Peninsula
during South Korean President Kim Dae Jung's state visit to Japan
last week.
</P>
<P>
Japan invaded China from 1937 to 1945, inflicting great pain
and damage on the Chinese people during the eight-year period.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the timing of Jiang's visit, Komura said the two
countries are making last-ditch efforts to finalize his itinerary.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's visit was originally scheduled for early September but
postponed due to massive flooding in central and northeastern
China.
</P>
<P>
The visit will be the highlight of bilateral events this year
to mark the 20th anniversary of the signing of the China-Japan
Peace and Friendship Treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Falling Interest Rates Bring Hope to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 13 (Xinhua) -- A dramatic decline in Kenya's
leading interest rates has brought a ray of hope to the country's
battered economy and stock market, analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's benchmark 91-day treasury bill yield fell to 20.88
percent at this week's central bank auction, down by 1.12 percent
in the last two weeks and more than six percent since April, the
East African Standard newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Rates are coming down faster than we thought or anticipated
they would," said Abdalla Abdulkhalik, treasurer at Citibank in
Nairobi. "It looks like there is room for further falls."
</P>
<P>
Commercial bank base lending rates, still stuck at over 27
percent, are also set to fall, albeit with a lag, said analysts.
</P>
<P>
This will bring blessed relief to an economy which has been
strangled by last year's rise in rates, and to a stock market
starved for cash by the higher returns available in treasury
bills, they said.
</P>
<P>
"It is good interest rates are falling," said Amish Gupta, an
associate director at brokers Shah, Munge &AMP; Partners, "We are
going to look quite attractive on certain stocks."
</P>
<P>
Nairobi's stock market has been on a steady decline since the
middle of last year, and hit a four and half year low last month.
</P>
<P>
Gupta said, however, the bearish tone is unlikely to be
reversed overnight, especially with brokers continuing to revise
earnings forecasts down for many companies.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of them in the industrial sector haven't given out good
results... the index might be depressed for quite a while," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates first shot skyrocketed when the International
Monetary Fund suspended a key loan in July last year, citing
corruption and poor governance.
</P>
<P>
They stayed high as the government then lost control of its
budget and domestic borrowing rose sharply.
</P>
<P>
The latest fall in interest rates is partly a reflection of
the government's efforts to keep a much tighter rein on its purse
strings in the 1998/99 (July/June) budget, reducing the amount of
money the central bank needs to raise each week through the
treasury bill auction.
</P>
<P>
"The government is really doing very well," said Gupta.
</P>
<P>
"They (the government) are having a good collection in terms
of revenues, and are exceeding their budgeted numbers -- although
they are not doing equally well in terms of expenditures," said
Abdulkhalik.
</P>
<P>
The central bank can also take some credit for the fall in
rates. Twice since June's budget, it has cut the cash reserve
ratio -- the proportion of deposits commercial banks need to keep
with the central bank.
</P>
<P>
The moves, which have brought the cash ratio down to 13
percent from 15, have freed up liquidity in the money market, and
loosened the monetary reins.
</P>
<P>
A strong Shilling -- the Kenyan currency has actually
strengthened this year despite a global emerging market crisis --
has also been a major factor, according to the analysts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
