<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Inflows Into Zambia Less </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's foreign exchange
inflows continue to decrease as the country's international
reserves drop further, according to a weekly local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's foreign reserves fell to 117.6 million U.S. Dollars
as at June this year from a balance of 136.5 million Dollars in
the previous month, said Financial Mail Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Zambia fortnightly statistics showed that the foreign
reserves have reached the lowest level in the past one and half
years and the donor inflows have remained minimal since January
this year.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's statistics also indicated that only 3.5
million Dollars flew into the country from cooperating partners
this year. This is against a projection contained in the 1998
budget that 35 percent of the funding was supposed to come from
donors.
</P>
<P>
Inflows from other non-governmental sources, such as retention
on non-traditional exports (NTE), has also been minimal. Total
earnings from NTE amounted to about 25 million Dollars as at
September 30 of this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines, the country's
largest traditional foreign exchange earner, continued to sell
its foreign exchange straight on the market.
</P>
<P>
However, the lion share of the country's foreign reserves are
swallowed when the government continues to service its heavy
foreign debt which stands at about 7.1 billion Dollars at
present.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months, Zambia spent a total of 94 million
Dollars on debt-servicing.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, the government expenditure amounted to
39 million Dollars while other non-government organization drew
over 12 million Dollars from the central bank, said the paper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
