<HEADLINE> Clashes Occur in S. Somalia on Roadblocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Armed confrontations
continued in southern Somalia as operations to dismantle the
roadblocks along the Mogadishu-to-Afgoie road went on.
</P>
<P>
At least four militiamen were killed and seven others wounded
when heavy clashes broke out between rival militiamen loyal to
faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid at the former custodian
police headquarters near the strong point of K-7 late Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
According to eyewitnesses, a technical vehicle belonging to
Hussein Aidid's men with about a dozen armed men on board went to
demolish the illegal roadblock Monday.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen manning the checkpoint who also had a battle wagon
at their disposal returned fire as they saw the armed men coming
in their direction.
</P>
<P>
Heavy gun fire ensued. Those opposing the setting up of
roadblocks were reinforced with four battle wagons. The five
battle wagons then forced the militiamen manning the roadblock to
flee.
</P>
<P>
However, the casualties were more on those roadblock opposers
with three died during the clashes.
</P>
<P>
The operation demolished the 27th of the illegal roadblocks
since last week.
</P>
<P>
However, roadblocks manned by militiamen loyal to Osman Ali
Atto still remain in position at the K-7 strong point and its
surrounding areas, demanding that commercial vehicles pay
extortion money when passing.
</P>
<P>
The campaign against the illegal roadblocks came at a time
when commercial goods from the natural port of Merca in southeast
Somalia began reaching the capital Mogadishu after the high tide
season ended and the commercial ferries began to flow on the
natural ports of Merca and El-Malan run by Hussein Aidid and Ali
Mahdi respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
