<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Lower in Tokyo on Profit-Taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices fell hard across the
board in Tokyo Tuesday as investors took profits from Monday's sharp
rise spurred by hopes of new legislation to inject fresh capital into
the country's banks.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange tumbled 312.22 points, or 2.30
percent, from Monday's close to end at 13,242.79. The Nikkei index
posted a 675-point, 5.24 percent gain Monday.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 24.36 points or 2.38 percent to 998.98.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section remained active with an estimated 500
million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan was the day's most heavily traded
issue.
</P>
<P>
"The Nikkei definitely gained too much yesterday, and that's the
reaction we're seeing today," a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Bank shares plummeted in the final half hour of trading, sending
all major market averages sharply downward. Export-linked blue chips
also fell after enjoying strong gains the previous day.
</P>
<P>
The slump in investor sentiment may have been sparked by Finance
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa's comments in the afternoon that he is not
sure if weak major banks would be forced to accept a capital
injection, traders said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
