<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Minister Dismisses Fear of Firearms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's Minister of
Home Affairs Ali Ameir Mohamed has dismissed fears that the
government decision to liberalize the trade of firearms and
explosives would jeopardize national security.
</P>
<P>
The government will strictly supervise the types and
quantities of firearms and explosives sold by businessmen,
Mohamed was quoted by media reports Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said in Dar es Salaam Monday that such sales would not be
like those of "match boxes in every corner of the street."
</P>
<P>
The government announced last week that it will allow private
businessmen to import and sell firearms and explosives for
civilian use in the country.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen interested in starting dealerships for
distribution of guns, shotguns, rifles, bullets and explosives
are required to send their applications to the Inspector General
of Police and Commissioner of Minerals before October 30.
</P>
<P>
The move has virtually broken the monopoly by the state-run
Agricultural and Industrial Supplies Company Limited (AISCO) over
the business.
</P>
<P>
The government said the businessmen must have a substantial
working capital, clean records at the immigration and taxation
departments, well-established and safe warehouses as well as
other conditions.
</P>
<P>
The decision has raised people's fears of worsened social
security, especially at a time when the bombing of U.S. embassy
on August 7 in Dar es Salaam remains fresh in people's memory.
</P>
<P>
In defense of the decision, the minister said the government
will also limit the shops doing the business and keep records of
individuals who buy them.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen will be allowed to sell firearms and explosives to
citizens only after they were approved by the Inspector General
of Police, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He further said the government decision is a move to
restructure the parastatal sector.
</P>
<P>
"Because parastatals have all along been selling firearms and
explosives to citizens and now that the government has adopted
the privatization policy, it is evident that changes have to be
made," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
