<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment Helps Improve Roads in Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Overseas investment is
playing a vital role in improving road conditions in the
mountainous areas of northwestern Guangdong Province in south
China.
</P>
<P>
The city of Qingyuan is just one example of the benefits to
road construction from such overseas investments.
</P>
<P>
When increasing traffic on the Qingyuan section of No. 107
state highway required the city to build a new and modern highway,
the city was quite troubled since construction of the 215-km-long
mountainous road would cost an enormous sum of three billion yuan,
as compared with the 260 million yuan in revenues the city
received in 1994.
</P>
<P>
At the crucial moment, a Singaporean came to the rescue,
agreeing to invest over 100 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
When a shortage of funds left the road half-completed, the city
managed to secure loans of 50 million U.S. dollars from six Hong
Kong banks with the help of the Guangdong provincial government.
</P>
<P>
Another Hong Kong-based company also injected 30 million U.S.
dollars to become a new shareholder in the project.
</P>
<P>
With overseas investment accounting for 83 percent of the
funding, the road was opened to traffic at the end of 1997. It is
now the longest mountain highway in China.
</P>
<P>
At present, several highways are being constructed in Qingyuan
with the help of overseas funds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 07:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Willing to Better Ties With Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANTALYA, TURKEY, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister
Costas Simits has said that Greece is willing to improve its
relations with Turkey through talks and dialog, Greek sources
said Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Simits held a meeting with his Turkish
counterpart Mesut Yilmaz late Monday in "a friendly and useful
atmosphere" in the southern Turkish city of Antalya where the
Balkan summit is being held.
</P>
<P>
The sources quoted Simitis as saying that Greece and Turkey
have had many negotiations in the past years but no substantial
results have been achieved. But he said that the two countries
have to make progress in improving bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The Greek premier said that the Greek-Turkish disputes could
be presented to the Hague-based International Court of Justice for
settlement.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors have long been at odds over the limits of
air space, sovereignty over some Aegean islands and the Cyprus
issue.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has always said that the problems between the two
coubtries should be solved through bilateral negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Simitis reiterated that the Cyprus issue, which is one of the
major obstacles for the normalization of the Turco-Greek
relations, is an international issue.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the two prime ministers agreed that the Balkan
leaders should reach a common position on the Kosovo issue which
is posing a direct threat to peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
But they said that all possible diplomatic means should be
exhausted before a military action is taken.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, have expressed their support for international
efforts to stop bloody conflicts in the Yugoslav province.
</P>
</TEXT>
