<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's Tea Output in Sharp Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's tea output is
projected to reach a record 25 million kilograms this year, 20
percent more than that of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest figures released by Uganda Tea
Authority (UTA), some 21 million kilograms of tea will be
exported this year, the Monitor paper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of this year, 15.8 million kilograms
or 63 percent of the projected output has been realized. A total
of 14 million kg has been exported, 90 percent of which through
the weekly Mombasa (Kenyan port city) auction.
</P>
<P>
The report said 11 million kg and 9.9 million kg of tea were
produced and exported respectively in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
UTA officials said they are confident the projected output can
be achieved.
</P>
<P>
The splendid performance of the tea industry is attributed to
heavy rains earlier this year which resulted in good leaves.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's acreage under tea has increased to slightly over
25,000 hectares up from around 10,000 hectares in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The country's tea industry, which was at its best in 1972/1973
when 23 million bags were produced, suffered decay following the
expulsion of Asians by dictator Adi Amin. Asians then controlled
most of the tea estates in the country.
</P>
<P>
It was then (1972) Uganda's third highest commodity hard
currency earner after coffee and cotton, a position it is soon
reasseting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
