<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Onion, Potato Become Luxuries in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Onion and potato, once humble
staples in the Himalayan kingdom of Nepal, now become luxuries for
many people.
</P>
<P>
The Kathmandu Post Tuesday reflected the situation with a
cartoon, in which one man whispers to another: "He smells of
onion. He must be very rich!"
</P>
<P>
One kilogram of onion in not-so-good quality sells at 70 rupees
(one U.S. dollar) at market here and one kilogram of potato costs
30 rupees (44 U.S. cents).
</P>
<P>
But before the monsoon season which started in June and ended
in September, it cost only 8 to 12 rupees (12 to 18 U.S. cents)
for one kilogram of onion.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, the price of potato soared from 4
rupees (6 cents) to 14 rupees (21 cents) and all the way to 30
rupees (44 cents) now.
</P>
<P>
"They are out of season now," a retailer said.
</P>
<P>
She said that onion in her shop was imported from India, where
its price was reported to be as high as 60 Indian rupees (1.4
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Another retailer also attributed the soaring prices to
scarcity. He said that onion and potato sold in his shop were
imported respectively from India and Bhutan.
</P>
<P>
The Kathmandu Post said that bad monsoon, which caused flood
and landslide in some parts of the country, was largely blamed for
the massive shortfall of potato and onion.
</P>
<P>
Those in the low-income bracket, for whom potato has been the
chief supplier of starch, protein and minerals, have been badly
affected, the English-language daily said.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a retailer as saying that sales of potato have gone
down by about 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, the average income of the
Nepalese people is a meager 200 dollars per annum, and about 45
percent of the population live below the poverty line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half Italian Young Women Do Not Want Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 12 (Xinhua) -- One out of two Italian young women
do not want to have children, according to a poll taken recently
by a women's magazine "Noi Donne" (We Women).
</P>
<P>
The magazine polled 520 women aged between 16 and 24. The
result is 52 percent of those women do not want children, with 29
percent uncertain and only 19 percent, or one out of five, wanting
children.
</P>
<P>
The study found that about 70 percent of Italian young women
intend to have children several years after marriage, maybe over
30 years old or even 35.
</P>
<P>
More than half the women not wanting children gave the
professional advancement as the cause while less than half are
concerned with the social environment the child would have to grow
up in, the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
Other reasons included fear of responsibility, fear of
childbirth and dislike of children.
</P>
<P>
Among those who want children, 27 percent said one is enough,
23 percent want two, and only one of ten want three or more.
</P>
<P>
This age group of women approve child-adoption by gay couples
and single parents. The study found that single parenthood was
popular. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
