<HEADLINE> Six Men Killed by Train in U.S. Southwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Six men, sleeping on
railroad tracks in south Texas of the United States, were killed
by a freight train early Monday, local authorities reported.
</P>
<P>
"The train crew saw some debris on the tracks, that next
split-second, they saw heads raise up and then six people were
killed instantly," said Letty Garza, s spokeswoman for the Border
Patrol.
</P>
<P>
Texas Department of Public Safety spokeswoman Tela Mange said
the victims, believed to be illegal aliens from neighboring
Mexico, likely slept on the tracks in the belief they would be
safe from snakes.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred about 60 miles north of the Mexico
border. The freight train was rolling through ranchland on its way
from Houston to Brownsville when it struck the victims.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities were working to identify the men through
fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
Mange said it is not unusual for people to sleep on the tracks
in south Texas and there had been cases of people surviving
similar incidents because trains had passed over their sleeping
bodies between the rails without actually hitting them.
</P>
<P>
The area, sparsely populated ranchland and desert, is where
nine illegal aliens died in searing heat last summer as they made
their way from Mexico. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
