<HEADLINE> Chinese Beer Industry Faces Surplus Output, Lower Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese beer industry's
survival is not threatened mainly by foreign beer but by
competition among its own companies, according to today's Market
Daily.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that one-third of the national beer output
is from Sino-foreign joint ventures, and only around three percent
of this output bears foreign brand names such as Kirin, Blue
Ribbon, Beck's and Budweiser.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the newspaper said, foreign beer poses no
significant threat to domestic beer producers.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted industry analysts as saying that China's
beer production has outstripped demand since 1996, forcing beer
producers to compete in slashing prices to ensure their
market shares.
</P>
<P>
This year's beer output is estimated to be five million tons
more than last year's output of 18 million tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
