<HEADLINE> U.N. Agency President to Visit Uganda on Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- President of the International
Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD) Fawzi H. Al-Sultan will
arrive here Tuesday for a five-day official visit during which a
vegetable oil development project will be launched.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued by IFAD Tuesday morning,
he is expected to meet with President Yoweri Museveni and other
senior officials of Uganda to discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
He will also review with the government the Fund's present and
future operations in the country. Particular emphasis will be
placed on IFAD's role in poverty alleviation and food security on
the occasion of celebrations to mark the 20th anniversary of the
organization.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sultan is also expected to launch a vegetable oil
development project in Uganda which is aimed to lessen the
country's dependence on oil imports and to revitalize domestic
vegetable oil production.
</P>
<P>
The main thrust of the project will be to develop the palm oil
industry by promoting partnerships between small-holder raw
material producers and private sector processors.
</P>
<P>
This project brings IFAD's total investment in the country to
111 million U.S. Dollars from its Regular Program, the special
program for African Countries Affected by Drought and
Desertification and the Belgian Survival Fund Joint Program.
</P>
<P>
IFAD, a specialized agency of the United Nations based in
Rome, Italy, has taken the initiative of reducing the net present
value of Uganda's debt within the framework of its participation
in the Heavily-Indebted Poor Countries Debt Initiative.
</P>
<P>
On May 26 this year, IFAD and Uganda signed a loan agreement
for 20 million Dollars to finance the eight-year vegetable oil
development project in Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
