<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Houses Mushrooming in Tibetan Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since the early 1980s, these Tibetan farmers have renovated
their homes at least twice, and now more buildings are under
construction in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
In the city of Xigaze and in Banam and Gyaze counties, almost all
the farmers have moved into new buildings.
</P>
<P>
Zhaxi Wangbo, a former serf in Qugo Township in Lhunzhub
County, built the first two-story building in his village this
year.
</P>
<P>
Zhaxi was allocated a house in 1959 when democratic reforms
began. "Though the house was shabby, it was my home," he said.
</P>
<P>
He lived in the house for more than two decades. Working on a
farm, he earned 30 yuan a month and did not expect to renovate his
house.
</P>
<P>
Things changed in the 1980s when Tibetan farmers were
encouraged to engage in diversified production.
</P>
<P>
"Since then, our lives have gotten better day after day," Zhaxi
said.
</P>
<P>
He has now learned to operate farming machinery such as
tractors, threshers and seeders.
</P>
<P>
Zhaxi also bought a bus last year to start transportation
service. "The former house was too small for us, and I thought of
building a two-story building earlier this year," he said.
</P>
<P>
Now he has a two-story building with a yard where his bus and a
tractor stand side by side.
</P>
<P>
"My courtyard is like a manor house in the past, but serf owners
didn't have buses and tractors," Zhaxi said proudly.
</P>
<P>
Goinsong, a farmer of Banxung township in Xigaze, constructed a
two-story building with 24 rooms for his 11-member family.
</P>
<P>
Goinsong said, "My new house was built on my harvest from
contracted farmland and animal husbandry.
</P>
<P>
His family has contracted 7.6 hectares of farmland on which
they produce 40,000 kg of grain annually, and they also have 124
domestic animals. Goinsong's annual income reached about 100,000
yuan in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
