<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of The Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Kosovo, the political and
cultural center of the Serbian Kingdom in the Middle Ages, has
been regarded by the Serbs as the cradle of their history and
culture.
</P>
<P>
During the 400-year-long occupation by the Ottoman Empire,
there was an exodus of Serbs before Albanians began to immigrate
into the area. After World War I, Kosovo again became part of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The following is a brief chronology of unrest in the region
since World War II:
</P>
<P>
1945 -- About 10,000 ethnic Albanians fought against 40,000
Yugoslav troops for the control of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
1963 -- Yugoslavia amended its constitution under which Kosovo
was upgraded as an autonomous province.
</P>
<P>
1968 -- Yugoslav President Josip Broz Tito granted a first
tentative measure of self-rule to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
1974 -- The new Yugoslav constitution recognized Kosovo's
autonomy status. The area became attached to the Republic of
Serbia as a "federal unit."
</P>
<P>
1981 -- Kosovo Albanians demanded the establishment of a
separate republic within Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
1988 -- About 6,000 Serbs and Montenegrins living in Kosovo
staged a mass protest against harassment by ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
1989 -- Following continued strikes and protests in the region
by ethnic Albanians, Serbian leader Slobodan Milosevic removed
from the Yugoslav constitution the right to autonomy which Kosovo
had been granted in 1974.
</P>
<P>
February 1990 -- Yugoslavia sent troops, tanks, fighter planes
and more than 2,000 police troops to Kosovo and imposed a curfew
in the region.
</P>
<P>
July 1990 -- Ethnic Albanian legislators in Kosovo declared the
Kosovo province independent from Serbia. Belgrade dissolved
Kosovo's parliament and government.
</P>
<P>
1991 -- The parliament of Albania recognized Kosovo as an
independent republic.
</P>
<P>
May 1992 -- Ibrahim Rugova was elected "president" of the
self-claimed republic of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
October 1992 -- Serb and ethnic Albanian leaders in Kosovo held
their first face-to-face peace talks in three years.
</P>
<P>
July 1995 -- A Serbian court sentenced 68 ethnic Albanians to
up to eight years in prison for attempting to organize a police
force.
</P>
<P>
February 28, 1998 -- A guerrilla group known as the Kosovo
Liberation Army attacked Serbian police forces, resulting in the
death of 16 ethnic Albanians and four Serbian policemen.
</P>
<P>
March 6 -- Serbian police destroyed a stronghold of the Kosovo
Liberation Army in central Kosovo, killing a guerrilla leader and
capturing 30 guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
March 9 -- The six-nation Contact Group for the former
Yugoslavia held an emergency meeting in London to discuss the
situation in Kosovo. The meeting urged the government of
Yugoslavia and the ethnic Albanian leaders in Kosovo to settle
their dispute through political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
March 31 -- The U.N. Security Council imposed an arms embargo
on Yugoslavia while reaffirming its pledge to respect the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of Yugoslavia and appealing
to Yugoslavia to solve the Kosovo issue through political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
April 2 -- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic proposed a
referendum on international mediation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
April 23 -- In a referendum, 95 percent of Serbian voters
backed Milosevic's rejection of international mediation.
</P>
<P>
May 15 -- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and Kosovo
ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova held their first-ever talks
in Belgrade. Both sides exchanged views on how to solve the Kosovo
issue and agreed to meet once every week.
</P>
<P>
June 12 -- The six-nation Contact Group for the former
Yugoslavia discussed the worsening Kosovo crisis in London. In a
statement issued at the end of the meeting, the foreign ministers
of the six countries urged all parties in the conflict to halt
violence and settle the dispute through dialogue. All but Russia
reiterated their decision to ban new investment in Yugoslavia,
freeze Yugoslavia's assets abroad and ban all Yugoslav flights to
land in their cities. Russia said that it does not support
military intervention in Kosovo and opposed any sanctions on
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
June 16 -- Milosevic met Russian President Boris Yeltsin in
Moscow, agreeing to accept some of the demands from the West, but
refused to withdraw Yugoslav troops from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
June 22 -- NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said that NATO
was preparing to take actions in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
September 1 -- Milosevic put forward a provisional agreement to
ethnic Albanian leaders, which provided Kosovo a certain degree of
self-rule for a period of three to five years.
</P>
<P>
September 4 -- Rugova agreed to accept Milosevic's proposal.
</P>
<P>
September 22 -- Serbian forces launched an all-out offensive on
"terrorist organizations" in northern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
September 23 -- The U.N. Security Council adopted Resolution
1199, calling on all sides involved in the Kosovo conflict to
cease fire immediately and start political dialogue to solve the
crisis peacefully.
</P>
<P>
October 4 -- A Russian delegation composed of Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov and Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev visited
Yugoslavia. The delegation discussed the Kosovo issue with
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
October 7 -- NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said that
NATO was ready to launch air strikes against Yugoslavia and the
countdown had begun.
</P>
<P>
October 8 -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said that he had
decided to authorize the U.S. ambassador to NATO to vote for air
strikes against Yugoslavia if the Yugoslav leadership failed to
fully comply with the U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
October 11 -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said that if
NATO uses force against Yugoslavia, Russia will not retaliate. But
another Cold War would begin.
</P>
<P>
October 12 -- The NATO allies approved an order for air strikes
against Serb forces in Kosovo but gave Belgrade 96 hours to fully
comply with U.N. Security Council resolutions. U.S. Balkan envoy
Richard Holbrooke returned to Belgrade for last-ditch talks with
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President on Priorities in East Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 13 (Xinhua) -- President of the Philippines
Joseph Estrada Tuesday listed deeper reform, innovation,
interdependence and commitment to social justice as four
priorities for the East Asian region reeling with the economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
In his keynote speech to a plenary session of the Seventh East
Asia Economic Summit here this morning, Estrada said the crisis is
an opportunity for the East Asian economies to do more than simple
repair work.
</P>
<P>
He said the reform now being undertaken throughout the region
must be deeply institutionalized, adding "band-aid remedies will
not do, change is necessary in order to survive change."
</P>
<P>
The president also said reforms should take care of the
immediate emergency and mid-term adjustment in a bid for
sustainable economic growth and the region must use standards of
accountability, corporate behavior, and an early warning and
surveillance devices as components of a wide transparency so as to
stay at the forefront of the global economy in the next century.
</P>
<P>
The president called for launching a second industrialization
wave aimed at higher productivity rather than production output,
noting the first wave of industrialization turned his country from
old-fashioned production into modernized agro-industry and
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Estrada laid emphasis on the importance of innovation in
boosting business and trade.
</P>
<P>
On social justice, Estrada drew attention to the stark
contrasts between the rich and the poor in the region and
underlined there can be no economic adjustment without extensive
safety nets for the poor.
</P>
<P>
Estrada stressed the importance for interdependence and
linkages within East Asia and with the rest of the world which he
said would benefit long-term growth.
</P>
<P>
As East Asian demand momentarily collapses, he said, demand
from other regions is now crucial for the regional recovery,
particularly with Japan's sluggish growth.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he will supports the reaffirmation of the Bogor
objectives and targets, and seek enhanced implementation of APEC
ecotech cooperation at the APEC leaders' meeting slated for next
month in Kuala Lumpur, capital of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
However, when answering a question, he said he has not yet
decided on his attendance at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He also advised the region to manage the political and security
dimension of regional stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
