<HEADLINE> Opposition Criticizes Poland's Siding with NATO on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Polish Social Democratic
Party (PSDP), the country's left-wing opposition party, on Monday
criticized the government's decision to participate in possible
NATO armed intervention in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In a front-page article "We Do not Want to Suppress Yugoslavia"
carried on the PSDP's Trybuna newspaper, the opposition said the
Polish government has been trying in the last week to justify its
plan to take part in NATO's military action in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The move, which the government claimed to be a peace operation
and humanitarian activity, in fact just serves one purpose -- "to
turn Polish soldiers into cannon fodder," the article accused.
</P>
<P>
If the war breaks out, Kosovo, and then all of Yugoslavia, will
become a new Afghanistan where NATO forces, including Polish
soliders, will encounter tough resistance from the guerrilla
forces, the article said.
</P>
<P>
It said that if any Polish soldiers involved in the military
action were to seen on the street with crippled legs, the Trybuna
newspaper would be the first to sue Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek for
plunging Poland in the war in violation of Poland's interests.
</P>
<P>
Another article -- "Kosovo Issue", also carried on Trybuna,
said that armed intervention does not tally with the interests of
anyone, neither the United States, nor other NATO members; neither
the people in Kosovo, nor the Europeans.
</P>
<P>
Intervention will only aggravate the situation, leading to
local warfare and unpredictable results, the article warned.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that no one can solve any problem by using missiles
in Kosovo, where persistent and skillful diplomatic efforts as
well as firm, civilized and unhostile support from the world are
needed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
