<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Independent Forecaster Predicts Drop in Indian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 13 (Xinhua) -- An independent forecaster
predicted a 0.5 percent drop in the Indian economy during the
current fiscal year from April 1, 1998 to March 30, 1999, the
Times of India reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Center for Monitoring Indian Economy (CMIE) said that
growth rate of the Indian economy would drop to 4.5 percent in
1998-99 from an earlier projection of 5 percent due to a decline
in agricultural production and a substantial slowdown in the
industrial and service sectors.
</P>
<P>
Growth rate in 1997-98 had also been revised downwards from 5.1
percent to 4.5 percent, according to CMIE's monthly review for
September released on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The forecast is sharply lower than the 6.5 percent projected by
the Reserve Bank of India (RBI), the central bank of the country,
and the government's expectation of 6.5 to 7 percent of growth
rate for 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
CMIE said that both the RBI and government forecasts were made
before the latest data were available and therefore tended to be
more optimistic.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures released by the Confederation of Indian Industry
(CII) showed that majority of Indian industries had less than 10
percent or negative growth rate in the first half of the current
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The biggest slump had been experienced by the automobile sector
which saw a 41 percent dip in commercial vehicles production, 53
percent in the middle and heavy commercial vehicles, 20 percent in
light commercial vehicle and three percent in cars.
</P>
<P>
Growth in the basic goods sector also remained depressed with
only 2.5 percent increase in aluminum, 5.4 percent in cement, and
5.2 percent in fertilizer but the production of cold rolled steel
and lead and lead alloy decreased 2.5 and 13 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
CMIE's revised growth projections for 1998-99 indicate that the
service sector would grow at 6 percent against the earlier
forecast of 7.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
It has, however, increased its farm output growth forecast to
1.0 percent from 0.7 percent and industrial output growth to 4.5
percent from 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
"With some data for the first quarter (April to June) now
available and the monsoon behind us, we have reason to believe
that our earlier forecast was a trifle optimistic," CMIE said in
its monthly review.
</P>
<P>
"The economy is in the throes of a major slowdown and it is
likely to grow by no more than 4.5 percent in 1998-99," it
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
