<HEADLINE> Chinese Loggers Seeking Fortune Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Forestry enterprises in
northeast China's Liaoning Province has made initial achievements
in carrying out the foreign operation strategy when it began to
sell the timber they produced overseas back to the home market.
</P>
<P>
One of the pioneer enterprises is the Dashitou Forestry Bureau,
which entered into a joint timber-harvesting venture with partners
in Chita, Russia, in September last year.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture, with a cooperation term of 20 years and a
cost of 12 million U.S. dollars, is designed to harvest 300,000
cubic meters of timber annually. It has so far produced 23,000
cubic meters during trial production, and sold 13,000 cubic meters
back to China.
</P>
<P>
Over the past several years, China has been exercising a limit
on forest logging and carrying out a program to protect
forests. As a result, many forestry workers have to stay idle and
a large number of machinery become unused.
</P>
<P>
The pinch is felt especially in Jilin, China's second largest
timber producer. Many local forestry companies are starting to
turn their eyes overseas where forest resources are plentiful.
</P>
<P>
The Jilin Forestry Industrial Group, the province's largest
forestry enterprise, plans to establish six new logging companies
abroad by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to a company executive, the six overseas logging arms
will be able to produce 600,000 cubic meters of timber annually
and generate a net profit of 30 million yuan each year.
</P>
<P>
The conglomerate, which established its first overseas logging
operation in Equatorial Guinea in 1995, has sent 16 business
delegations to Australia and a dozen other countries in Africa and
Latin America, looking for business opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Preparations for the six new overseas logging ventures,
including those in Papua New Guinea, Surinam, Cameroon and Laos,
have been well carried out, said the company executive.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
