<HEADLINE> New Zealand Nominates FM for Commonwealth Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
has officially announced its nomination of Minister of Foreign
Affairs and Trade Don McKinnon for the position of Commonwealth
secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
The position will become vacant at the Commonwealth Heads of
Government Meeting in South Africa in November next year when
Nigerian chief Emeka Anyaoku retires after 10 years' service.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley said
Monday that McKinnon "is widely respected in New Zealand and
internationally" and his nomination for the position has "the
wholehearted backing of the government and the warm support of the
wider New Zealand community".
</P>
<P>
McKinnon's candidature, she said, is an opportunity "for New
Zealand to take a leading role in a major international
organization" and to continue to encourage "cooperation between
countries of all levels of development to ensure that the
interests of small states especially are enhanced".
</P>
<P>
It is learned that McKinnon himself has been lobbying for the
post informally for some time. According to him, more than 30 of
the Commonwealth's 54 members have showed their support for him.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's former foreign minister Farooq Sobhan is the only
other declared candidate for the position of next Commonwealth
secretary-general. However, other South Asian nations are likely
to consider their own nominations. 
</P>
