<HEADLINE> Italians Want New Government, Prodi Preferred </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 12 (Xinhua) -- About 50.5 percent of Italians
want a new government and 44.4 percent favor early general
elections, an opinion poll showed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a poll by the SWG polling institute, 70.5 percent of
respondents believe the government crisis that burst onto the
political scene last Friday is bad for the country.
</P>
<P>
The results, to be published by the Catholic weekly Famiglia
Cristiana, showed that 57.6 percent of respondents said the
outgoing Premier Romano Prodi was "little or in no way effective"
in government, yet he was believed to be the most likely candidate
to lead a new government.
</P>
<P>
The poll of 600 Italians showed 44.6 percent blamed the
Communist Refoundation Party for the crisis and 20 percent lay the
blame at Prodi's door. 
</P>
