<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diarrhea-Related Death Toll Rises to 770 in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The latest diarrhea-related death
toll till Monday evening had risen to 770 since the disease broke
out in the country's 52 flood-hit districts, according to official
figures.
</P>
<P>
So far, 571,863 people had been affected by the water-borne
disease, the Associated Press of Bangladesh Tuesday quoted an
official of the Diarrhea Control Room under the Health Department
as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, she said that the situation "is not alarming now and
the disease would not turn into epidemic."
</P>
<P>
The epidemic form is measured when the case fatality rate (CFR)
is 1 percent, she stated, but the CFR was 0.14 percent on October
11 and 0.23 percent on October 12.
</P>
<P>
To cope with the situation, she said, a total of 4,732 medical
teams are working in the diarrhea-affected areas besides the
non-government organizations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Red Crescent is expanding the post-flood relief
program with 40 more medical teams which will start operating this
week, and by then, a total of 100 Red Crescent mobile medical
teams will be working in the 33 districts worst hit by post-flood
diseases, according to a Red Crescent press release.
</P>
<P>
The 100 mobile teams are funded by the International Federation
of Red Cross and Red Crescent societies which appealed for more
than 338 million taka (about 7.19 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"The need of medicine and medical care is still enormous in the
post-flood period and reports from our medical teams indicate that
diarrhea and other diseases are still spreading," said the
release.
</P>
<P>
Besides, thousands of Red Crescent volunteers working in over
50 flood-hit districts have distributed more than 400 tons of
foodstuffs in flood relief, the release added.
</P>
<P>
The recent flooding, which had lasted for ten weeks starting
from mid-July and was the worst in a century, had gripped as much
as two-thirds of the country and affected about half of its 127
million people. It also left over 1,000 people dead and caused an
estimated loss of 4.3 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
