<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Targets 70 Percent Literacy by 2001: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has a
target to raise literacy rate up to 70 percent by the year 2001,
press reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina disclosed this while meeting
leaders of the Bangladesh Primary Teachers' Association (BPTA)
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"You are the prime tools for making the nation educated," she
said, adding that despite resource constrain, the government
increased the salary of the primary teachers and placed them under
national pay scale.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that the main problem of the nation is poverty
and the main reason of poverty is illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
With the spread of the education the country's unemployment
problems will be solved, she added, referring to the recent
establishment of the Employment Bank with a view to providing
capital to the educated unemployed youths for generating
self-employment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
In the last two years, the country's literacy rate increased to
51 percent from 47 percent, she told the BPTA leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
