<HEADLINE> International Coffee Prices Expected to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The average price of coffee on
the international market could fall to 125.88 U.S. dollars per
quintal (100 pounds) in the next 12 months, down 21.82 dollars
from the 1997-1998 level, a Costa Rican expert predicted on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Guillermo Canet, executive director of the Costa Rican Coffee
Institute, attributed the price fall to reports of Brazil's bumper
harvest for the 1998-1999 period, which said the country would
harvest 32 million sacks (60 kilograms per sack) of coffee in 12
months.
</P>
<P>
Canet called on Costa Rica's coffee producers to "reasonably"
reduce their cultivation and coffee-grain processing.
</P>
<P>
Coffee is an important export crop in Costa Rica. According to
official figures, coffee exports in the first eight months of this
year reached 290.04 million dollars, 26.7 percent of the country's
total exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
