<HEADLINE> Environmental Law to Be Formulated for Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- A national workshop is being
held here to propose a national framework environmental
legislation and an environmental impact assessment legislation for
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The two-day workshop, which began on Monday, is organized by
the National Commission for Environmental Affairs (NCEA) of
Myanmar and the Hanns Seidel Foundation of Germany.
</P>
<P>
Participants of various Myanmar ministries are seeking ideas
and recommendations for drafting the two laws that are best suited
to the environmental, cultural, social and economic conditions of
the country.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar NCEA, since its inception in February 1990, has
made efforts to enhance environmental management in the country,
promoting public attention to environmental matters through public
environmental awareness programs.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar adopted a national environment policy in late 1994 with
the aim of achieving harmony and balance between the environment
and development through the integration of environmental
consideration into the development process to enhance the quality
of life of all its citizens.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the NCEA formulated and published Myanmar Agenda 21
which is the plan of action for sustainable development in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Presently, Myanmar has altogether 57 environmentally related
laws. However, most of these sectoral laws are incidental
environmental laws and are not specifically intended for
environmental protection.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
