<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals Increase in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals in Thailand
rose to 5.04 million in the first eight months of this year, a
5.59 percent rise over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
European arrivals registered the highest rise, the Tourism
Authority of Thailand (TAT) said in a statement available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Overall tourist arrivals from European countries rose to 1.37
million or 22.6 percent up over the 1.12 million in the same
period of last year. The number of British tourists rose by 38.74
percent to 322,815 and followed by German tourists numbering
246,439 with a 12.52 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of tourists from East Asian countries
dropped by 4.06 percent to 2.79 million.
</P>
<P>
As for Japanese arrivals, Thailand's largest market, the
number dropped by 3.82 percent to 640,089. In a bid to increase
Japanese arrivals, the Thai government recently approved in
principle one-year visas for elderly Japanese tourists.
</P>
<P>
Pitak Intravityanunt, the new Prime Minister's Office Minister
in charge of tourism, said the authority would focus on new
markets like China and India by cooperating with the Transport and
Communications Ministry in increasing flights from these markets
to Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
