<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death of Activist Affects Indonesia's Fact-Finding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The murder of an Indonesian
activist had a strong impact on the work progress of the
fact-finding team investigating the May riots due to the "possible
political impact" over her death, the Indonesian Observer reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
An 18-year-old activist Martadinata, also known as Ita, was
brutally killed last Friday in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
"Whether or not (Ita's death) has a political dimension, it has
a wide impact, especially on current public anxiety," said Marzuki
Darusman, chairman of the fact-finding team.
</P>
<P>
Marzuki, who is also vice chairman of the National Commission
on Human Rights, said Ita's death had shocked the team.
</P>
<P>
"Even though the death itself is unrelated to the team, it
influences the work atmosphere of the team," he added.
</P>
<P>
The government established the fact-finding team in July which
includes representatives from the Armed Forces, government
agencies, the rights body and non-governmental organizations to
investigate allegations that the riots were masterminded. The team
is expected to complete its task later this month.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,200 people were killed and thousands of buildings
and vehicles damaged during the riots in Jakarta and other cities.
Activists have reported that 168 women were gang-raped or
otherwise sexually assaulted during the riots and 20 of them died
or committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that since Ita's death, public skepticism had
grown as a result of swift work by Jakarta police detectives. The
suspect was apprehended within 24 hours of the brutal murder.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, detectives arrested Suryadi, a 20-year-old
neighbor of the victim. Police later also confiscated evidence
obtained from the suspect, which was allegedly dumped in a North
Jakarta river and vacant land belonging to a neighbor of the
suspect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
