<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Pop Singers Adopt Two Chengdu Giant Pandas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Two giant pandas were adopted
by two pop singers from Taiwan a few days ago, raising the number
of giant pandas adopted at the Chengdu Giant Panda Breeding and
Research Center to a total of 25.
</P>
<P>
13-month old "Xiao Qi" and 14-month-old "Lunlun" have been
adopted by Ren Xianqi and Su Huilun who donated 5,000 U.S. dollars
to the center in Sichuan Province in southwest China, in order to
help protect the endangered species.
</P>
<P>
"Xiao Qi" is the great grandson of "Meimei," a female panda who
became famous for giving birth to nine cubs, and his mother is one
of the first twin pandas to have survived at the center.
</P>
<P>
Since the first adoption in September 1993, 25 giant pandas, or
95 percent of all the pandas kept at the breeding center, have
been adopted by eight organizations and individuals within or
outside the Chinese mainland. These organizations include the
Motorola company of the United States, an American life insurance
company, and the Chengdu Cigarette Factory.
</P>
<P>
The adopters show great concern for the pandas and usually
travel to the center to visit them each year, while the center
also makes efforts to keep the adopters informed on the well-being
of the pandas.
</P>
<P>
China has about 1,000 giant pandas in the wild, 80 percent of
which roam the mountains of Sichuan Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Milosevic Agrees to U.N. Demands Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) agreed to refrain from air strikes against
Serbia after Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic agreed to
comply with U.N. demands to end military action against Kosovo
Albanians, U.S. President Bill Clinton said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the NATO alliance had agreed to delay its air
strikes for four days to allow time for international inspectors
to verify that Milosevic has fully met his commitments to
withdrawing forces from Kosovo and initiating peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said in an impromptu statement after a campaign
fund-raising event in New York that Milosevic had agreed to allow
a "robust" team of international inspectors to see that Serb
troops pull back, that refugees be allowed to return to their
homes, and that other conditions of the U.N. Security Council be
met.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council demanded the withdrawal of more Serb
troops from Kosovo, access for humanitarian aid to refugees and
the opening up of serious talks with the secessionists on the
restoration of autonomy for the province.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said there would be about
2,000 inspectors, including an unknown number of Americans.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was hammered out during week-long negotiations
between U.S. Special Envoy Richard Holbrooke and Yugoslav leaders.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of NATO ambassadors in Brussels had approved air
strikes against Serb forces stationed in Kosovo if Milosevic
failed to comply, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
As negotiations were going on, NATO forces were awaiting the
"activation order" for air strikes. U.S. B-52 bombers armed with
cruise missiles, B-2 and F-117 stealth aircraft carrying
2,000-pound bombs and F-16 fighters with radar-seeking missiles
were among the weapons ready to be called into action.
</P>
<P>
The carrier USS Eisenhower with some 70 combat aircraft and
other ships armed with Tomahawk cruise missiles were poised in the
Mediterranean Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
