<HEADLINE> Northwest Hunan Explores Subterranean Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- A well with a plentiful and
high-quality water supply was recently drilled in the northwestern
part of central China's Hunan Province, bringing relief to a
region long suffering from water shortages.
</P>
<P>
The well was found in Baojing County, a poverty-stricken
county located in karst terrain. Seventy-two percent of the
county's villages are short of drinking water, and 68
percent of the farmland is irrigated solely by rainwater.
</P>
<P>
The county's well-drilling project is part of the country's
plan to find water sources in southwest China's karst
regions. After several months of exploration, this well was drilled
and it now supplies more than 5,500 tons of water daily, which meets
the drinking-water demand of about 50,000 nearby residents.
</P>
<P>
Similar water-discovery projects will also be launched in
southwest China's karst regions, and in Hunan's poverty-stricken
counties such as Yongshun, Huayuan, and Sangzhi as part of
the nationwide poverty-relief efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
