<HEADLINE> Czech: Airstrikes Can Not Settle Kosovo Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Airstrikes planned by the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) can not settle the problem in
Kosovo, Czech Chairman of the Chamber of Deputies Vaclav Klaus
said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
This is because of the complexity of the situation there, Klaus
told reporters after meeting with former U.S. Secretary of State
Henry Kissinger, the Czech News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
No air strikes have settled any problems at any time in
history, he said, agreeing with Kissinger that the Kosovo problem
is not the make of a single person, Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, rather a result of historical reason.
</P>
<P>
According to the news agency, Kissinger made a speech on the
"Forum for 2000" here on Monday. He stressed that the world public
should understand the roots of Balkan conflicts.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, however, Czech Foreign Minister Jan Kavan
announced support to NATO's air strikes plan after a cabinet
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Kavan also expressed the hope for a diplomatic way to settle
the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic will allow NATO aircraft fly over its
territory, and will offer a field hospital for NATO force. But it
will not send troops to join direct military intervention in
Kosovo, local news reported. 
</P>
