<HEADLINE>   Tyson's Psychological Exams Show He is Fit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Mike Tyson's attorney
revealed today that the psychological exams to be published
Tuesday will prove the former heavyweight champion is fit enough
to return to the ring.
</P>
<P>
"He is sound mentally, he is sound physically, and he is sound
neurologically," attorney Jim Jimmerson said Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to Jimmerson, a team of psychiatrists concluded in
their reports that Tyson only occasionally reacts in anger, but
can control his feelings through additional counseling.
</P>
<P>
Jimmerson said he read the reports for two hours today and
turned them over to the Nevada Athletic Commission three minutes
before the deadline for next Monday's hearing on whether Tyson
will be granted a new boxing license.
</P>
<P>
The commission plans to release the reports tomorrow morning.
There are some details in the report that Tyson would prefer the
public not see, according to Jimmerson.
</P>
<P>
"It's a hard-hitting report. There are going to be things that
talk about his innermost thoughts and innermost feelings," the
attorney said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Tyson lost a fight to keep the records private.
A divided Nevada Supreme Court refused to deny a lower court's
order that allows the report to be made public after it is given
to the commission.
</P>
<P>
Tyson and his advisers want to get the license as soon as
possible because they hope to stage a fight for Tyson in December.
</P>
<P>
Tyson faces one more big hurdle before the commission meeting.
He faces trial in Montgomery County, Md., the same day the
commission meets on assault charges filed by two men stemming
from an August 31 traffic accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
