<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Regulates Yuan Use for Overseas Financiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Only those overseas financial
institutions which have been operating in China for three
accounting years and have shown a profit for two consecutive
years, are entitled to apply for the right to deal in the Chinese
yuan in the Shenzhen Special Economic Zone, according to a newly
promulgated document.
</P>
<P>
The document issued by the local branch of the People's Bank of
China, the central bank, bans application by overseas banks with
discipline violations or bad business-performance records.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules, the overseas bank branches should have
average monthly outstanding loans of between 100 to 500 million
U.S. dollars, at least one year prior to application. The amount
set for joint-venture banks and financial companies and solely
owned banks and financial institutions is over 100 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Authorized overseas financial institutions will have the right
to wholely or partly operate using yuan in receiving deposits,
issuing loans, making settlement and guarantees, and trading
treasury bonds. But financial companies will be banned from yuan
settlements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
