<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says Belgrade Agrees to Kosovo Concessions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said here on Monday that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic had
agreed to end the seven-month offensive against ethnic Albanians
in Serbia's province of Kosovo and to allow the presence of
international observers.
</P>
<P>
However, Clinton recalled Milosevic's past "intransigence" and
warned that NATO troops were ready to stage air strikes if
Belgrade failed to honor the agreement to withdraw Serb forces
from Kosovo, allow refugees to return, and allow in international
observers.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president said the international community had been
pressing Milosevic for months to end the violence in Kosovo, but
the Yugoslav leader had failed to comply with a United Nations
Security Council resolution, which, adopted on September 23,
demanded an immediate ceasefire and the start of political
dialogue over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
As a result, he said, NATO ambassadors had decided, for the
second time in history, to authorize military action against
Yugoslavia. In light of Milosevic's most recent pledges to comply
with U.N. demands, however, they had agreed to hold off from any
air strikes for four days.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton stressed that the U.S. and its allies would be
watching very carefully -- through an "intrusive" monitoring
scheme -- to ensure that Milosevic live up to his promises this
time.
</P>
<P>
"Let me be very clear, commitments are not compliance. Balkan
graveyards are filled with President Milosevic's broken promises,"
he said. "In the days ahead we will focus not only on what
President Milosevic says, but we will see that he does through a
robust, on-the-ground and in-the-air verification system."
</P>
<P>
Milosevic made the key concessions after marathon talks with
U.S. Special Envoy Richard Holbrooke, who, after briefing NATO in
Brussels on the four days of talks, is scheduled to have more
discussions with Milosevic in Belgrade on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Conflict broke out in Kosovo in February, when ethnic
Albanians, who make up some 90 percent of Kosovo's population of
two million, began fighting Serb forces for independence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
