<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Ultimatum: 96 Hours to Comply or Air Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- NATO early on Tuesday gave
Belgrade 96 hours to comply with United Nations Security Council
resolutions on Kosovo before beginning air strikes.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said after two prolonged
sessions of NATO's decision-making body, the North Atlantic
Council, from Monday morning to early Tuesday, that it was an
important day for NATO to have announced the activation order.
</P>
<P>
He said United States Special Envoy Richard Holbrooke reported
to the council the diplomatic progress made in recent days.
</P>
<P>
"There has been progress, but largely due to the pressure of
the alliance in the past few days," said Solana, adding that the
allies had to keep up the pressure for a diplomacy settlement.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief said the delay between order activation and the
real attacks was designed to allow situation on the ground to
improve, that is for Belgrade to comply with the U.N. Security
Council Resolution 1199 calling for an immediate end to
hostilities.
</P>
<P>
NATO demanded that the compliance be verifiable while the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) will
provide an unarmed civilian monitoring team to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The allies still believed that diplomacy could succeed and the
use of force could be avoided, said Solana.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, after briefing OSCE officials in Brussels, will
return to Belgrade immediately to resume negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"Slobodan Milosevic knows what he should do and the
responsibility lies solely on the shoulders of Milosevic," said
Solana.
</P>
<P>
The activation order covers five phases of the airborne attack
and each phase needs a case-by-case authorization from the North
Atlantic Council.
</P>
<P>
One NATO official said that the mechanism of re-authorization
is designed to put the phased air strikes under political control.
</P>
<P>
NATO has reportedly amassed a total of 650 warplanes including
260 from the U.S. which provided the NATO air strike operation
with two B2 Stealth bombers and six B52 bombers.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., Britain, Germany, Belgium and Australia reportedly
started evacuating embassy staff and families from Belgrade for
fear that they would be taken hostage once air strikes were
underway, as was the case in 1994 when NATO missiles hit Serbian
targets in Bosnia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
