<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Media Keen on Reporting Reform and Opening Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Since early October, major
Chinese media outlets have been reporting special stories marking
China's 20 years of reforms and opening up which began with the
Third Plenary Session of the 11th Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua News Agency, China's national wire service, distributed
on October 5 a special series titled "Reforms and Breakthrough,"
recalling the important events of the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
As the official newspaper of the CPC Central Committee, the
People's Daily established "The Glorious 20 Years," a special
column on its front page which reviews the country's economic and
social achievements in the period.
</P>
<P>
The China Central Television (CCTV), the most influential media
outlet in China, began to broadcast a program called "Historical
Leaping Over" on China's National Day, October 1.
</P>
<P>
The Third Plenary Session of the 11th CPC Central Committee,
which was held December 18-22, 1978, was a meeting of historic
importance for bringing order out of chaos in political affairs
and correcting the mistakes of the "Cultural Revolution."
</P>
<P>
Since the strategic shift of the Party's focus to economic
construction which was decided upon at the meeting, China has
entered the era of reforms and opening to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Although there are still two months towards the 20th
anniversary of the meeting, Chinese media have shown great
enthusiasm for the occasion, frequently featuring the title
"Reforms and Opening Up" for their stories.
</P>
<P>
The Central People's Broadcasting Station has begun to
broadcast a 100-part program on hot issues and all the new things
that are turning up in China, such as the first private restaurant
and the first law firm.
</P>
<P>
Many leading media outlets including CCTV, the Guangming Daily,
the Beijing Daily and the Xinmin Evening News have started columns
about the changes in the lives of ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
Yu Guomin, professor with the Institute of Media Research under
the People's University of China, said that reports focusing on
this topic indicate a strong journalistic awareness by the media
outlets, which itself is also a result of the 20 years of reforms
and opening up.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Company Congress Opens in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Some 1,200 representatives of
small and medium enterprises from 60 countries gathered in the
Brazilian city of Sao Paulo on Monday for a three-day conference
here.
</P>
