<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Dialogue Between Turkey, Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Monday called on Turkey and Syria to show restraint
and to solve their differences through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Annan's appeal came after he met with the U.N. Permanent
Representatives of Egypt, Lebanon, Morocco and Syria.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued through his spokesman's office, Annan
said he shared the ambassadors' concern at the recent increase in
tensions between Turkey and Syria, and he welcomed the efforts by
Egypt and Iran to mediate a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he had been in contact with both parties and was of
the view that every effort should be made to avoid a further
deterioration in relations.
</P>
<P>
Turkey accused Syria earlier this month of backing Kurdish
separatist guerrillas seeking autonomy in southeast Turkey and
demanded that Syria hand over Kurdish Workers Party leader Abullah
Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
Syria denied harboring Ocalan or helping the Kurdish Workers
Party, and has looked to Arab countries for support. 
