<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Finds Underground Water in Western Hunan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese hydrologists have
found underground water in a poverty-stricken area of northwestern
Hunan Province, Central China.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, clean water flows out of a wildcat
well sunk recently in Meihua Township in Baojing County, and the
projected exploitable water reserves is estimated at over 5,500
tons daily.
</P>
<P>
This finding will help solve the problem of supplying drinking
water to 50,000 residents living in the county seat of Baojing and
nearby rural areas.
</P>
<P>
In Baojing County, where most of the land consists of karst
formations, 72 percent of the villages have difficulty getting
drinking water, 68 percent of the paddy fields depend on natural
rainfall and a poor population of 60,000.
</P>
<P>
As part of its poverty-elimination effort, the Chinese
government has earmarked special funds for prospecting and
searching for water resources in the karst formations of southwest
China.
</P>
<P>
The country is estimated to have 200 billion cubic meters of
water resources in these karst formations for annual use,
according to an earlier report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Cuts Price for Power to Promote Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 13 ( Xinhua) -- Cities in south China's
Guangdong Province are adopting measures to cut electricity prices
to stimulate electricity consumption and promote economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Local government sources said the province now enjoys a
sufficient power supply, but the problem of high-cost electricity
remains.
</P>
<P>
Years ago, many enterprises in the province built their own
generating facilities to avoid buying the expensive power, leaving
large power stations with a difficult task selling their output.
</P>
<P>
To cut electricity prices, the local government and related
departments are making efforts to restrain the construction of
high-cost small power stations, and effectively coordinate
electricity grids.
</P>
<P>
At present, two big cities in the province, Zhongshan and
Foshan, are taking the lead in cutting electricity prices. On
August 1, Zhongshan began to adopt the policy of preferential
prices for industrial and commercial enterprises with high
electricity consumption, while Foshan cut its urban power price by
two percent on October 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
