<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Enhances Power Generation on Upper Reaches of Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Seven large and medium-sized
hydropower stations with a generation capacity totalling 5.4
million kw have been built along the 918-km Longyangxia to
Qingtongxia section of the upper reaches of the Yellow River,
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River, China's second longest, is abundant in
hydro-electrical resources, as the water level in the
Longyangxia-Qingtongxia section falls by 140 meters every 100 km,
with a drop of 1,300 meters. The Chinese government has devoted
itself to increasing investment in power generation in the area
with a view to making full use of the resource.
</P>
<P>
The newly built Lijiaxia hydropower station, which cost five
billion yuan (604 million U.S. dollars), is designed with a
generating capacity of two million kw, according to official
figures.
</P>
<P>
The Northwest China Surveying and Designing Institute has
revised its plans for hydropower-station construction on the upper
reaches of the Yellow River, increasing the generation capacity to
16.58 million kw and an annual electricity output of 58.9 billion
kwh.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the electricity department revealed that the
power shortage in northwest China has been hindering local
economic growth, as the great potential of the region's water
resources has not been fully tapped.
</P>
<P>
For this reason, nine electric companies headed by the China
State Power Corporation have jointly worked out a timetable for
the construction of hydropower stations on the upper reaches of
the Yellow River. The first two projects are large hydropower
stations in Gongboxia and Laxiwa with a generating capacity of 1.5
million kw and 3.72 million kw respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
