<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The establishment of the
Chongqing Nokia Telecommunications Co. Ltd. on Sunday brought the
number of multinational corporations in this southwest China
municipality to 15.
</P>
<P>
This year, Chongqing has attracted investment from some 20
countries and regions, and these investments have expanded to such
sector as water supply, communications, sports, education and art.
</P>
<P>
In the first three quarters, Chongqing approved 175 joint or
cooperative ventures and foreign-funded companies, up 2.9 percent
over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The contractual foreign investment increased by 7.2 percent,
valued at 310 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
To attract foreign investors, Chongqing has adopted a series of
preferential policies this year, including the return of income
tax if the investment is in infrastructure or high-tech and pillar
industries.
</P>
<P>
Nokia official Arnold Malcolm said that Chongqing is one of the
areas in China enjoying the fastest development and there is great
market potential waiting to be tapped.
</P>
<P>
Michael Oksenberg, professor at Stanford University and a China
expert, said western China, represented by Chongqing, now presents
new development opportunities. Enitem
