<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hubei Fortifies Water Conservation Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hubei Province
is going all out to strengthen its water conservation works after
suffering serious flooding from the Yangtze River this summer.
</P>
<P>
More than 90,000 flood fighters began reinforcing the
embankments of the Yangtze last month as soon as the flood peaks
passed.
</P>
<P>
The central government will allocate 17 billion yuan (2
billion U.S. dollars) over the next four years to increase Hubei's
ability to control flooding.
</P>
<P>
The central government this year will also provide five billion
yuan (about 600 million U.S. dollars) for the reconstruction of
the flood-devastated areas in Hubei. Of the money, 3.1 billion is
for water conservation projects.
</P>
<P>
By comparison, the central government previously earmarked
about 300 million yuan each year for water conservation projects
in the province.
</P>
<P>
Hubei Province is the most flood-vulnerable region in the lower
reaches of the Yangtze. Embankments of the Yangtze and its
tributary Hanjiang River in Hubei now can only withstand floods
which occur every 10 to 20 years and every six to eight years
respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
