<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Approves Order for Military Intervention in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- NATO war planes were given the
go-ahead to begin air strikes in Kosovo by Friday after the
alliance decided early on Tuesday to activate the order for
military intervention.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana made the announcement
after NATO's decision-making body, the North Atlantic Council, met
twice during the day to decide on the activation order, ACTOR in
NATO jargon.
</P>
<P>
But NATO gave Belgrade 96 hours for it to meet the demands of
the international community before the real strikes start.
</P>
<P>
The council first reviewed the legal basis upon which the
allies based their attacks without a mandate in the form of a
United Nations Security Council Resolution (UNSCR).
</P>
<P>
It then studied the targets planned for the first of the series
of air operations. Later in the day, the North Atlantic Council
heard U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke report on the latest
development in the diplomatic negotiations in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
The council also waited during the day for the German
parliament to approve the NATO action before it could take the
decision on activation.
</P>
<P>
The ACTOR covers five phases of the air-borne attack NATO has
planned as an option to bring Belgrade to full compliance with the
demands of the UNSCR 1199, Solana said. It would also force
Belgrade to accept the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe as the unarmed civilian team to monitor its compliance
with the U.N. resolutions on the ground.
</P>
<P>
Each phase needs a case-by-case authorization from the North
Atlantic Council.
</P>
<P>
One NATO official said that the mechanism of re-authorization
is designed to put the phased air strikes under political control.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Britain, Germany, Belgium and Australia have
reportedly started evacuating embassy staff and families from
Belgrade for fear that they would be taken hostage once air
strikes are underway as it was the case in 1994 when NATO missiles
hit Serbian targets in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
NATO has reportedly amassed a total of 650 warplanes including
260 from the U.S. which provided the NATO operation with two B2
Stealth bombers and six B52 bombers.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria and Romania were said to have offered their air bases
for the NATO operation alongside the bases in Italy and Britain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
