<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Shipping Industry Opens Wider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, October 13 (Xinhua) -- China will open its shipping
sector wider to the rest of the world to ensure the sound
development of foreign trade, said a senior Ministry of
Communications official here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment is especially encouraged in port
construction, said Deputy-Minister Zhang Chunxian at an ongoing
symposium on the development of international navigable courses in
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
In the future, China's shipping sector will introduce advanced
management experience and technology and the mechanisms of
competition in a bid to increase its viability in the
international market.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, by June this year, 125 Sino-foreign
shipping companies and 13 solely foreign-funded shipping firms had
been set up in China, while overseas shippers had opened 324
offices in the country.
</P>
<P>
China has signed ocean-going shipping agreements with 52
foreign countries, and river shipping pacts with four foreign
nations, Zhang noted.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, China has used loans from the World Bank, the
Asian Development Bank and foreign governments to build up a
number of port projects with a combined annual handling capacity
of 85 million tons. At the same time, foreign consortiums have
invested heavily in port projects in Shanghai, Shenzhen, Dalian,
Tianjin and Zhuhai harbors.
</P>
<P>
He told the audience that China allows foreign companies to
lease local ports, build their own berths and facilities on leased
industrial land, and operate international liner business between
China's open ports and foreign ports.
</P>
<P>
Foreign vessels now enjoy the same fee rates as local shippers,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Currently, China has opened over 130 ports to foreign vessels,
and handles 36,000 ships from more than 100 foreign countries and
regions every year, Zhang said, noting that China is now among the
largest shipping countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, in 1997, major Chinese ports
handled nearly 1.3 billion tons of goods, including 380 million
tons from the foreign trade sector, and over 10 million TEUs.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, China had more than 320,000 civil vessels
with a total weight of over 50 million tons, including 23.8
million tons of fleets for the shipping of import and export goods.
</P>
<P>
Foreign shipping companies now play a large role in China as
they operate over 140 regular freighters, about 66 percent of the
country's total ocean-going shipping business. China now has 219
shipping agencies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
