<HEADLINE> Ex-Farmer Invests in Road Construction in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, October 13 (Xinhua) -- A private businessman in north
China's Shanxi Province has built a 21-kilometer-long cement road
with a loan of 31 million yuan and is preparing to recoup his
investment by collecting tolls.
</P>
<P>
Wang Ruheng, a farmer-turned owner of several factories and a
transportation company, built the road in Fanshi County in two
years. His road is an indispensable part of a longer road over
which the province's coal bound elsewhere must travel.
</P>
<P>
The new section will cut two and a half hours off the previous
travel time.
</P>
<P>
It also shortens the distance between the Wutaishan Mountains,
a famous Buddhist place in China, and the Yungang Grottos by some
100 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi, nicknamed the "Sea of Coal," relies heavily on coal for
revenue, and its coal is transported as far as to Shanghai.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
