<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Milosevic Gives in on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic has agreed to withdraw Serb forces from Kosovo, allow
international observers to be stationed in the province, said a
senior U.S. official said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on condition of anonymity, the official said Milosevic
made the concessions in the marathon talks with U.S. special envoy
Richard Holbrooke in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke currently is in Brussels briefing the ambassadors of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) about the talks.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Milosevic would allow planes from the NATO
to monitor the Serb withdrawal from the air and allow 2,000
international observers on the ground, reports quoted the official
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We think it's very important for a strong verification
regime," the official added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
