<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO May Wait for Holbrooke Before Making Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 12 (Xinhua) -- NATO officials may have to
wait for one or two hours more for the United States special envoy
Richard Holbrooke before making decision on air strikes against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Rumors spread in the NATO headquarters, where journalists
throned to hear the expected announcement of NATO's activation
order for the military intervention in Kosovo, that Holbrooke
would fly here after his talks with Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
The NATO ambassadors who met in Monday's North Atlantic Council
would wait to hear the reassessment report from Holbrooke to see
whether it is necessary to activate the order for the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
NATO said that it would still support for diplomatic efforts
though it had started to amass war planes for the air strikes and
evacuate embassy staff and families of NATO member states from
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Britain, Germany, Belgium and Australia have
started evacuating embassy staff and families from Belgrade for
fear that they would be taken hostage once air strikes are
underway.
</P>
<P>
NATO has reportedly amassed a total of 650 warplanes including
260 from the United States that provided the NATO air strike
operation with two B2 Stealth bombers and six B52 bombers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Peace Efforts Continue as War Drum Beats Louder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke ended another
round of peace talks on Kosovo here Monday evening without
reaching an agreement.
</P>
<P>
This was the eighth meeting in the past week. After the
meeting, Holbrooke flew to Brussels to brief the 16-nation
ambassadors who were holding talks on whether or when to launch
air strikes on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke is the American troubleshooter in the Balkan region
who played a decisive role in nailing down the historic Dayton
agreement that ended the three and half-year Bosnian war in late
1995.
</P>
<P>
But this time things are different as Kosovo is the domestic
affair of Yugoslavia. Even the West is against the independence of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
At the negotiating table, Holbrooke has been pressing Milosevic
to comply with U.N. demands, which include a withdrawal of
Yugoslav troops, access for international aid agencies to help
refugees and serious negotiations towards a political solution on
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Before sitting down at the negotiating table, Holbrooke told
reporters in Belgrade, "We remain on an intense effort to find a
peaceful and satisfactory outcome toward what can only be called
an emergency while in Brussels NATO continues to move towards a
very different form of outcome."
</P>
<P>
Although both Holbrooke and Milosevic are striking to seek a
final political solution, the gap between the two sides remains
wide and there are no signs that Milosevic is backing down.
</P>
<P>
"To allow relief organizations to work in Kosovo, OK. But to
withdraw troop from the region, no way," said a government
official who was reluctant to give his name. "If the security
forces leave, the Kosovo Liberation Army will come back and kill
Serbs there."
</P>
<P>
The diplomacy in the Balkan state is intensified; so is the
military buildup of the West.
</P>
<P>
More American and Canadian warplanes arrived at NATO's air
bases in Italy Monday as the deployment of NATO forces were close
to completion.
</P>
<P>
Western observers in Belgrade said that if the negotiation
fails, NATO's air strikes on Yugoslav military installations seem
inevitable as time is running out for the 50,000 refugees staying
in the Kosovo hills and winter is drawing in.
</P>
<P>
"NATO is pressed to the corner. If there is no result and no
action, NATO will be seen as a weak military organization and its
role in the future will be diminished," they said. "NATO's
determination to bomb Yugoslavia is very strong," they added.
</P>
<P>
Reports say the air strikes will continue for several days,
hitting ammunition dumps and military airports. The operation will
gather momentum until the Yugoslav leaders comply with the U.N.
demands.
</P>
<P>
The British government Monday ordered the closure of its
embassy in Belgrade, another sign that Western military pressure
is mounting to achieve what they might fail at the negotiating
table.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav news agency Tanjug said Holbrooke will come to
Belgrade Tuesday to continue the talks with Milosevic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Authorizes Brahimi to Pay One-Day Visit to Kandahar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Monday authorized his special envoy for Afghanistan to
pay a one-day visit to the southern Afghan town of Kandahar
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The move came after two days of talks in Islamabad, Saturday
and Sunday, between his Special Envoy Lakhdar Brahimi and a
delegation of senior Taleban representatives.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Brahimi, who is now seeking to ease tensions
between Iran and the Afghan Taleban militia, is expected to meet
Taleban leader Mullah Mohammad Omar.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. spokesman's office, the Taleban
leadership had assured Brahimi that they would address seriously
unresolved United Nations concerns, in particular Taleban's
sharing of information on their investigation into the killing of
Lt. Col. Carmine Calo, a military adviser serving with the U.N.
Special Mission to Afghanistan, as well as other security concerns
about the possible return of international United Nations staff to
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between Iran and the Afghan Taleban militia mounted in
August after 10 Iranian diplomats and a journalist disappeared
from Iran's consulate-general in Mazar-i-Sharif when Taleban
fighters captured the town. All but two of the Iranians were
eventually found dead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM: Talks With Turkish Leaders "Useful" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANTALYA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said his talks with Turkish leaders on finding a peaceful
solution to the dispute between Turkey and Syria were
"constructive and useful."
</P>
<P>
Moussa made the comment at the Ankara airport after winding up
his one-day visit to Turkey Monday.
</P>
<P>
He held talks with Turkish President Suleyman Demirel and
Foreign Minister Ismail Cem as part of his mediation mission. "I
came to Ankara with good mission. We brought a Syrian message to
Turkey," he said.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Cem said in Antalya that Moussa has told him
Syria is responding to Turkey's concerns on terrorism. "Let's hope
the message is true," he said.
</P>
<P>
During his stay, Moussa conveyed Demirel a message from
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, the semi-official Anatolia News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
No details o the message are available but it is widely
believed it contains substance that is aimed to convince Turkey to
soften its bellicose attitude toward Syria.
</P>
<P>
Moussa arrived in Ankara Monday amid mounting Turkish-Syrian
tensions.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Turkey and Syria have always been
troublesome. Turkey has long accused Syria of harboring Turkish
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), which has been fighting
since 1984 for autonomy of the Kurdish minority in southeastern
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Syria, denying the charges, repeatedly voiced its concern and
fear over Turkey's close military alliance with Israel that
threats Arab security.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has stepped up a war of words against Syria, and Prime
Minister Mesut Yilmaz has said that Turkey has to make
preparations for a war against Syria if it continues to provide
financial and military support to the PKK.
</P>
<P>
Ankara's war-like rhetoric has aroused fears of a regional
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi have
visited Turkey and Syria to try to persuade the two neighbors to
solve their disputes through dialogs.
</P>
<P>
Demirel said in meeting with Moussa that "we are sensitive
about Syiran-PKK ties on terrorism. If there is still hope for a
peaceful solution to the tension between the two countries, Syria
must persuade to the end."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
