<HEADLINE> Mozambican FM Urges Settlement of Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Foreign Minister
Leonardo Simao said here Monday that the Kosovo crisis in former
Yugoslavia should be resolved through negotiation.
</P>
<P>
The military intervention should be taken into consideration
only as the last resort, said Simao.
</P>
<P>
"We never stand for resolving crises through military means
unless it is absolutely necessary," said the Mozambican minister.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the United Nations Security Council has passed
resolutions strongly demanding Yugoslavia Federation should "stop
the intervention of the army and police and start negotiations."
</P>
<P>
"We think that the resolutions passed by the U.N. Security
Council has not yet been implemented, and therefore more efforts
should be made to reach solutions to the crisis through
negotiations," said Simao.
</P>
<P>
"Military approach should be the last of the last choices," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslavian Federation government is facing great pressure
on the issue of Kosovo as the U.S.-led North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) is amassing troops for air strikes against
the war-torn Balkan country. 
</P>
