<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Calls for New World Information Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Minister for
Information and Broadcasting Joseph Nyagah called for a new world
information order here Monday when officiating a Pan-African
media and communication conference.
</P>
<P>
"Although a lot of progresses have been made in the related
fields of technology transfers and improvement of communication
facilities, the so-called North-South imbalance still remains a
matter of concern even as we approach the next millennium," said
the Kenyan information minister.
</P>
<P>
"It is a fact that although most countries in the South are
politically sovereign, they continue to depend on technologies
developed in the North to sustain their media," said Nyagah.
</P>
<P>
"The countries of the North still largely control the supply
of programs and information through their news agencies," he
noted, calling for more efforts to develop Africa's media and
communication industry controlled by Africans themselves.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that media and communication are also
playing a key role in Africa's efforts to improve and
institutionalize good governance, which is the main theme of the
11th biennial conference of the African Council for Communication
Education (ACCE).
</P>
<P>
Participants of the one-week meeting also urged ACCE's 25
member states to draft a model curriculum for mass communication
training and media houses in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The curriculum, to be used at tertiary and postgraduate
levels, will train communication professionals who understand and
are prepared to design strategies to meet the challenges in the
information field.
</P>
<P>
A Nairobi University School of Journalism lecturer, Absalom
Mutere, suggested that the model curriculum should recognize that
development is increasingly determined by the availability of
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
"Access to wealth and power is increasingly being determined
by who can manage information and communication systems that
provide such knowledge," he said.
</P>
<P>
The conference was attended by communication institutes and
media practitioners from Lesotho, Malawi, Ghana, Nigeria,
Eritrea, Egypt, South Africa, Swaziland, Kenya and so on.
</P>
<P>
The ACCE was formally established in Accra, Ghana in 1974 by a
group of leading African communication scholars with an eye to
the development of communication education across Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
