<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Reserves Right to Act Against Iraq: Cohen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of Defense
William Cohen said Monday that the United States reserves the
right to use force against Iraq if Baghdad fails to comply with
the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Cohen made the remarks during a speech to the American troops
stationed at the Tusker Camp in west Kuwait, which is near the
Iraqi border.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iraq must fully implement all the United Nations'
resolutions and the Security Council "should stand behind its own
resolutions until seeking the use of force."
</P>
<P>
If the Iraqi regime refuses to comply with the U.N.
resolutions, Cohen said, "we reserve the right to take action at a
pleasant time of our choosing."
</P>
<P>
The defense secretary underlined that his country has "a very
formidable force in the Gulf region that can take military actions
very quickly if it becomes necessary."
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that the U.S. has maintained a force of roughly
20,000 in the region, adding that the force level can be increased
to 40,000 in a 96-hour period.
</P>
<P>
"We also have doubled the number of cruise missiles," he said
but did not give the exact number.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. top defense official arrived here earlier Monday for a
two-day visit. Kuwait is the fourth leg of Cohen's six-nation Gulf
tour, which has already taken him to Bahrain, Qatar, the United
Arab Emirates and Oman.
</P>
<P>
He is heading to Saudi Arabia Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Senior Pentagon officials had said before Cohen's departure
that, besides "near-term" matters, the secretary's Gulf visit
would also deal with such "long-term" matters as the potential
for a regional theater missile defense system and possible
agreements to smooth the insertion of U.S. troops in the region
during crisis.
</P>
<P>
On the reason that U.S. proposes to set up a regional missile
defense system, Cohen said that the proliferation of missile
technology has led to a series of tests of missiles by the
countries surrounding the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
This has put the troops and people in this region in jeopardy,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
In response to questions on what were the reactions of the Gulf
leaders to the proposed system, the secretary said "they
understand it."
</P>
<P>
Since Cohen has to cover six countries in one week, his Gulf
tour is believed to be a hasty one which observers here said is
rather symbolic than substantial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
