<HEADLINE> Massive Petrol Leakage Occurs in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 12 (Xinhua) -- A pipeline, which carries
petrol from eastern Durban Port to Johannesburg in South Africa,
burst in Alverstone outside Durban Monday morning, resulting in
leakage of 250,000 liters of petroleum.
</P>
<P>
A drop in pipeline pressure was noted at about 4:20 a.m.,
South African Press Association quoted Sanet Knoetze, spokeswoman
for Petronet Company, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 600-kilometer line between Durban and Johannesburg was
immediately closed and emergency procedures were implemented,
said Knoetze.
</P>
<P>
Repairs were underway and the line was expected to be running
again by Tuesday, she said.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the leakage is not known yet. But
environmentalists have been called to help assess the damage.
</P>
<P>
Knoetze said that officials from the Department of Water
Affairs were carrying out tests to check if the leaking fuel had
entered any water supplies. 
</P>
