<HEADLINE> Kirghiz Foreign Ministry Denies Involvement in Arms Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Kirghiz Foreign Ministry
Monday denied any involvement in an attempted shipment of 500 tons
of ammunition from Iran to Afghanistan, the Itar-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
Kirghiz customs officials seized more than 500 tons of
ammunition intended for Afghanistan at Osh in southern Kirghizstan
last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Tass quoted Nadyrbek Turganbayev, chairman of the State Customs
Inspectorate, as saying that shipment documents indicate the
consignment was humanitarian aid for Afghans and had to be loaded
on trucks and taken into the Asian country.
</P>
<P>
The Kirghiz press claimed that the Foreign Ministry had been
informed of the shipment through diplomatic channels and had given
permission for the transit of weapons through southern regions of
the country.
</P>
<P>
The arms are believed to be sent to Afghan government forces
fighting Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian embassy in Bishkek, the Kirghiz capital, declined
to comment on the detention of the Iranian train, Tass said.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and the Talibans deteriorated following
the murder of eight Iranian diplomats and a correspondent,
allegedly by Taliban fighters.
</P>
<P>
Kirghiz First Deputy Foreign Minister Alikbek Dzhekshenkulov
said the ministry is "studying the situation" and plans to release
an official statement on the scandal.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministry admitted that the Iranian Foreign
Ministry asked Kirghizstan in late September for permission to
transport humanitarian materials "including special cargo" through
Kirghizstan to the Afghan government.
</P>
<P>
"It turned out later that having failed to obtain permission
from the Kirghiz government, Iranian authorities shipped the cargo
from Mashhad. The cargo crossed several countries and arrived in
Osh on October 8, 1998," the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
"The above request was studied by Kirghiz authorities and it
was a complete surprise for us that the cargo arrived in Osh," it
added.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued by the Kirghiz Security
Ministry, officers found crates which are used for keeping arms
and ammunition in the 16 railway carriages supposed to be carrying
flour.
</P>
<P>
"National security officers have been ordered not to open the
cargo and guard it closely until all circumstances are clarified,"
Tass quoted the statement as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
