<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Urges Milosevic to Honor U.N. Resolutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Monday morning "personally urged" Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to comply with Security Council resolutions on
Serbia's province of Kosovo, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard told a press conference, "This morning the
secretary-general called President Milosevic to personally urge
the president to take necessary steps to comply with Security
Council resolutions on Kosovo as a prerequisite to a political
solution."
</P>
<P>
Annan also "encouraged the president to continue to work with
United States envoy Richard Holbrooke in pursuance of this
objective," he said.
</P>
<P>
In return, Milosevic assured the U.N. chief that he was "in the
process of complying, or trying to come into full compliance with
the Security Council resolutions," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The resolutions called for the withdrawal of Yugoslav troops
and security force from Kosovo, where the conflicts broke out in
February this year after ethnic Albanians fought Serbs for
independence.
</P>
<P>
Annan and Milosevic also discussed some of the details of the
talks between the president and the U.S. envoy, but the U.N.
spokesman declined to give any further details.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Annan was encouraged by the telephone conversation,
Eckhard said, "He just felt he was doing his duty by urging the
president to comply with Security Council resolutions -- something
he felt he had to do."
</P>
<P>
Annan made the phone call as Milosevic ended four days of talks
with Holbrooke, who, afterwards, flew to Brussels to brief NATO on
the talks. NATO is poised to authorize the use of military force
against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo crisis talks between U.S. Balkans envoy Richard
Holbrooke and President Milosevic will resume Tuesay, the Yugoslav
news agency Tanjug said in Belgrade Monday.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Annan met with Vladislav Jovanovic, charge
d'affaires of the Yugoslav Permanent Mission to the United
Nations. During the meeting, the U.N. chief voiced his concerns on
the current situation in Kosovo, Eckhard said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jovanovic briefed Annan on the latest developments
in Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians formed a majority of the
province's population of 2 million.
</P>
<P>
A spokesperson for the Yugoslav mission, reached by Xinhua on
the phone, said Monday that Jovanovic asked Annan to exercise "his
function to preserve peace in the region."
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav envoy told the U.N. chief that "things are getting
better and better" in Kosovo: the security force has withdrawal
from the field and the military force is staying in the barracks,
and Belgrade is "fully complying with" the relevant Security
Council resolutions, the spokesperson said.
</P>
<P>
Jovanovic, in an exclusive interview with Xinhua last week,
said that life in Kosovo has been nearly formalized.
</P>
<P>
Also at the Friday meeting, Jovanovic asked the U.N.
secretary-general and the 15-member Security Council to bear in
mind the latest developments in Kosovo, and take steps to verify
the current situation in the province of mainly ethnic Albanians,
the spokesperson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
