<HEADLINE> Nairobi Bourse Faces Uncertain Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Nairobi Stock Exchange
(NSE) is facing with uncertain trading in October because the
national economy is depressed and investors are wary of possible
political instability, said a report available here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"There is the vote of no confidence hanging over the
government this week and the bank crisis has also had its
impact," a stockbroker, Gupta Amish, was quoted by the Features
Africa Network as saying.
</P>
<P>
Amish said that the teachers' strike starting last Monday has
also had an adverse effect on the market.
</P>
<P>
The 250,000-strong Kenya National Union of Teachers has asked
its members to ignore President Daniel arap Moi's appeal to
resume work, and to intensify their strike nationwide.
</P>
<P>
"Investors fear the teachers demands will be accepted, leading
to increased domestic debt," said Amish.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the fall of the treasury bill rates to
20.8 percent in the just-ended week will be good for the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
"Treasury bills will be that much less attractive," said
Amish, adding that they are the stiff competition for stocks.
</P>
<P>
Sectors expected to do well include agriculturals and
commercials. British American Tobacco, Kenya Power and Lighting
Company, Kenya Airways and Brooke Bond are among the firms that
have had a good year and will be on demand, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The general commercial sector, however, is not expected to
fare well because of the depressed economy, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In September, there was a decline of turnover by two percent
over August. Shares traded fell by 8.8 percent to 9.4 million.
Market capitalization also declined by four percent from 1.86
billion U.S. Dollars in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
