<HEADLINE> Jordan: Peaceful Return of Yemeni Islands Example </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Fayez
Tarawneh said the peaceful return of the Hanish Archipegalo to
Yemen is a good lesson for other regional countries who intend to
use military forces to settle disputes.
</P>
<P>
He said this in a congratulation cable sent Monday to his
Yemeni counterpart Abdul-Karim al-Iryani on the return of the bulk
of the Hanish isles to Yemeni sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Yemen's recourse to international arbitration for retrieving
the archipegalo averts use of military force and bloodshed,
thus setting an example for other countries in the region, he
emphasised.
</P>
<P>
Any peaceful means is widely welcomed because it enhances
regional stability and security, Tarawneh added.
</P>
<P>
Yemen clashed with Eritrea in December 1995 when Eritrean
troops took over major parts of the Hanish Archipegalo. In May
1996, Eritrea accepted a France-brokered accord to seek
international arbitration of the matter.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, both sides said that they accepted the decision of a
London-based international arbitration panel which awarded the
bulk of the islands to Yemen.
</P>
<P>
While the disputes were settled through international
arbitration, the region is still uneasy with Turkey's threat to
use military force against Syria for its support to the Kurdish
rebels fighting for autonomy in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey insisted that it will use force to destroy Kurdish bases
inside Syria if diplomacy fails to settle the dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
