<HEADLINE> Schroeder Defuses His Party's Internal Power Struggle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Germany's chancellor-elect Gerhard
Schroeder Monday defused a power struggle within his own Social
Democratic Party (SPD) by naming a senior party member to be his
defense minister.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after an SPD leadership meeting Monday in Bonn,
Schroeder said that Rudolf Scharping would be defense minister in
the future government while giving up his current post as the
SPD's parliamentary leader.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder also confirmed that SPD Chairman Oskar Lafontaine
would be finance minister as previously planned and another senior
SPD member, Franz Muentefering, who is the party manager, would
also come into the new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Who will the SPD's new parliamentary leader would be decided by
the party later, Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
Such an arrangement put an end to a dispute triggered by
Lafontaine, an SPD left-winger who reportedly wanted to force
Scharping from his current post and replace him with Muentefering.
</P>
<P>
Scharping, a moderate Social Democrat, initially refused to
quit his post but finally agreed to accept the compromise solution
under the condition that there would be no further cut in
Germany's defense spending.
</P>
<P>
The SPD, which defeated Chancellor Helmut Kohl's conservative
alliance in the general elections on September 27, is still in
negotiation with the ecologist Greens party to form a center-left
ruling coalition, the first such one in Bonn since 1949.
</P>
<P>
If a coalition deal could be reached between the two parties,
Schroeder is expected to be formally elected chancellor by
parliament on October 27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
