<HEADLINE> Yemen, Eritrea Willing to Boost Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni and Eritrean presidents on
Monday voiced their desires to improve bilateral ties to
contribute regional peace and stability, after their territorial
dispute was settled through international arbitration.
</P>
<P>
Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh and his Eritrean
counterpart Isaias Aftewerki expressed their willingness in a
telephone conversation Monday, the Yemeni News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the two presidents reviewed the historically
strong ties between the two countries based on cooperation, mutual
respect and good neighborliness.
</P>
<P>
They also expected to open a new page in their relations with a
view to "achieving the aspirations of their peoples, serving their
common interests and enhancing peace, security and stability in
the Red Sea region."
</P>
<P>
During their conversation, Aftewerki congratulated Saleh and
the Yemeni people on their restoration of sovereignty over some of
the disputed Hanish Archipelago following a ruling by the
London-based International Arbitration Committee last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Yemen clashed with Eritrea in December 1995 when Eritrean
troops captured most of the Hanish Archipegalo. But the two sides
agreed in May 1996 to accept a France-brokered accord to seek
international arbitration of the dispute.
</P>
<P>
Saleh has reportedly instructed the Yemeni Airlines to resume
flights to Eritrean capital Asmara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
