<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientists Conduct Plant Genome Research Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Three U.S. groups of
researchers will soon have access to the first complete genome
sequence of a plant named Arabidopsis thaliana, according to a
press release from the U.S. National Science Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The systematic large-scale genome sequencing of the plant will
cost 12 million U.S. dollars awarded by the National Science
Foundation, the Department of Energy (DOE) and the Department of
Agriculture. Their goal is to complete the sequence by the year
2004.
</P>
<P>
The project's ultimate goal is to sequence the plant's entire
genome, at a rate of about 200 genes per month and to develop the
first complete gene sequence map of a higher plant.
</P>
<P>
Arabidopsis thaliana is a small plant in the mustard family,
and has the smallest genome and the highest gene density so far
identified in a flowering plant. What scientists learn from the
study will be immediately applicable to economically important
plant species, will lead to the creation of new and improved
plants and plant-based products. And the applications of the
genetic information learned could be used to meet a number of DOE
needs such as improved quality and quantity of biomass products.
</P>
<P>
The three groups are: the Institute for Genomic Research in
Rockville, Maryland; Consortium of Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory,
Washington University in St. Louis and Applied Biosystems in
Foster City; Consortium of Stanford University, the University of
Pennsylvania and the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
