<HEADLINE> ECA Stresses Need to Strengthen Civil Society in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) stressed on Monday that
"there are many reasons why civil society must be strengthened."
</P>
<P>
Lalla Ben Barka, Deputy Executive Secretary of the ECA, said
this when she opened a two-day experts group meeting on
capacities and services required to enhance the effectiveness of
civil society organizations in Africa at the UN Conference Center
here.
</P>
<P>
Ben Barka told participants that "Africa's major resources are
not its mineral wealth, but its people", saying that "the
long-term growth and sustained development of Africa depends on
how well it utilizes its resources -- particularly its human
capital, of which civil society represents a significant
manifestation."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the task of building capacity of civil society
organizations in Africa, Ben Barka said that one is the Committee
on Human Development and Civil Society, a new forum established
by the Conference of African Ministers responsible for Economic
and Social Development and Planning at its 23rd session in May,
1997, to facilitate in-depth consultation on how to build
mechanism and broaden the space for people's participation in the
African development process.
</P>
<P>
"Another modality for partnership is ECA's African Center for
Civil Society, established last year to provide the missing
channel of dialog between civil society and governments," she
added.
</P>
<P>
She hoped participants to discuss how they can strengthen the
African civil society organizations and enhance their impact on
the development process.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting will deliberate over the draft working
document entitled "Enhancing the Effectiveness of Africa Civil
Society Organizations Including the Non-Governmental
Organizations: Capacity Building Challenges and Opportunities".
</P>
</TEXT>
