Milosevic ended hours-long talks with U.S. special envoy Richard
Holbrooke Monday without finding a solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, the eighth within a week, Milosevic said
there was no doubt that "conditions still existed for a peaceful
and political solution to the problems in Serbia's southern
province of Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
According to the Yugoslav news agency Tanjug, Milosevic and
Holbrooke will continue their talks Tuesday in an attempt to avoid
the air strikes that seem imminent.
</P>
<P>
The talks were also attended by U.S. Ambassador Christopher
Hill and Serbian President Milan Milutinovic.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an unspecified number of Serbian policemen withdrew
from Kosovo Monday in view of the fact that the situation has come
to stabilization with little terrorist operations.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian government decided two weeks ago that police units
withdrew from the ground to their base in Klina.
</P>
<P>
The police were transported by 15 buses from Pristina to
central Serbia and the event was witnessed by foreign journalists,
the Tanjug said.
</P>
<P>
In another related development, members of the United States
diplomatic observer mission in Kosovo and the staff of the U.S.
Information Center left their headquarters in Polje near Pristina,
the capital of Serbia's southern province. They are believed to
have gone to neighboring Macedonia. 
