<HEADLINE> Clinton Discuss Peace with Netanyahu, Arafat by Phone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Monday called Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and discuss prospects for
progress in Middle East peace talks this week.
</P>
<P>
Clinton spoke to the two leaders separately for a half hour
each and tried to identify the areas of agreement and disagreement
ahead of a peace summit to begin on Thursday in the Washington
area, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Netanyahu are scheduled to meet at the Wye River
Conference Center on Maryland's Eastern Shore on October 15.
Clinton will to to Wye River when necessary after he officially
opened the summit at the White House.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and Arafat will try to hammer out an agreement on
U.S. proposals for a three-phased Israeli handover of a further 13
percent of the West Bank in return for a Palestine Authority
crackdown on militants responsible for anti-Israeli violence.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said Clinton reiterated to Netanyahu and Arafat that
the objective is to conclude the interim agreement and move to the
final status talks.
</P>
<P>
"He said he hopes we can make progress toward that goal at Wye
River and said that the real question is whether the leaders are
ready to make the hard decisions to make peace a reality,"
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously he's looking forward to participating as appropriate
and seeing if we can't narrow the differences," Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton canceled a scheduled trip on Saturday to New Haven,
Connecticut, to attend his 25th Yale Law School reunion in order
to be free to lend a hand in the talks if needed.
</P>
<P>
The president said last week he was encouraged by prospects for
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"I'm encouraged by the attitude and sense of openness I felt
from Prime Minister Netanyahu and Mr. Arafat the last time they
were here, and if they can come back here with that spirited
we're close enough now that we can get this done," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said it was important to hold the final status talks in
a relaxed atmosphere, meaning that they should begin as soon as
possible ahead of the May 1999 deadline for wrapping up those
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
