<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Has No Plans to Reduce Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Oil Minister Hamdi
el-Bambi denied on Monday reports that Egypt planned to slash its
oil output if members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) decide to reduce their production ceiling.
</P>
<P>
The 11-member cartel is due to consider during their meeting in
Vienna November 25 further lowering their production quotas in
another attempt to shore up oil prices and ease the world oil
glut.
</P>
<P>
"Any reduction in Egypt's oil exports would not affect the
world oil market," Bambi told the Middle East News Agency on the
sidelines of the 14th conference of international oil experts
underway here.
</P>
<P>
He said that Egypt's volume of production was any way small
compared to that of OPEC members and it is in no position to abide
by the cartel's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the current economic development in Egypt
absorbs most of the revenues from oil production and export, which
is one of Egypt's four major foreign currency earners.
</P>
<P>
The Oil and gas sector accounts for about one-fourth of the
foreign currency income of Egypt, a non-OPEC member.
</P>
<P>
Egypt pumps about 800,000 barrels of oil every day, a level
kept since July 1 when it decided to cut output by 50,000 barrels
per day, despite a series of new oil discoveries, to help arrest
the nose-dive in international oil prices.
</P>
<P>
On losses incurred by Egypt as a result of oil price decline
which amounted to some 80 million dollars, he said Egypt aims at
offsetting them through better use of oil in industry which would
in turn reduce production costs and establish new projects.
</P>
<P>
According to an annual report by the Egyptian General Petroleum
Corporation (EGPC) released last month, Egypt produced 3 percent
less crude oil this year than the year before.
</P>
<P>
Crude production for 1997-98 fiscal year ending June 31
totaled 40.7 million tonnes compared with 41.783 million tons the
previous before.
</P>
<P>
Crude treated in local refineries amounted to 29.442 million
tonnes this year compared to 28.273 millions in 1996-97, up 4.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local consumption of oil products and natural gas
increased by 9.1 percent to 33.753 million tonnes this year from
last year's 30.924 million tonnes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
