<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Loses $68 Billion in Export Income: WB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Africa loses 68 billion U.S.
Dollars per year in export income as a result of its declining
share of world trade, latest World Bank statistics have shown.
</P>
<P>
Africa's share of world trade has dropped from three percent
in the 1960s to less than two percent in the 1990s, the bank was
quoted as saying by a report from the PanAfrican News Agency
available Monday.
</P>
<P>
This decline is reflected even in Africa's strongest export
sector of primary commodities, which, excluding fuel exports,
fell to three percent from nine percent of total global exports,
said the bank at last week's annual meetings together with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) in Washington.
</P>
<P>
However, the picture obscures the fact that Africa's exports
have been growing at a faster rate, which was 7.9 percent in 1996
from a rate of about four percent in 1975-1984.
</P>
<P>
But the lack of impact of this growth rate in the global
context shows that Africa's rate of growth has not kept pace with
growth rates in other regions of the world.
</P>
<P>
Unlike other regions, the bank indicated that Africa's exports
have been dominated by primary products in agriculture, minerals
and metals.
</P>
<P>
"These account for 60 percent of African exports, compared
with 33 percent for all developing countries," the bank stated.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that industrialized countries have yet to open
their markets to Africa, especially in the vital agricultural
products, textiles and clothing.
</P>
<P>
Africa's exports also face the obstacles of high transport
costs and low quality of products and services.
</P>
<P>
The bank suggested increased investment in infrastructure,
reduction in monopolies, greater private ownership and more
foreign direct investment as measures needed to spur export
growth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
