<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Soar with Asian, US Bourses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Buoyant conditions in New York,
together with steady currency markets and a 5 percent rally in
Tokyo underpinned European bourses on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In London, the FTSE 100 posted its biggest ever point rise,
closing trade at 5037.6 after a rise of 214 points, or 4.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The London index mirrored the rally on Wall Street, which
surged last Friday and boosted markets everywhere at the start of
the week.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 250 index of mid-range stocks gained 1.9 percent,
while the All Share index, the broadest UK market measure,
advanced 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sentiment was also lifted by Asian markets which recorded
strong gains after the Japanese upper house passed the financial
stabilization bills. Tokyo's index notched up a 5.2 percent
increase as the prospect of a reform of the banking sector seemed
more likely.
</P>
<P>
Markets were also buoyed by the prospect of further potential
cuts in interest rates in Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
But dealers remained anxious about extreme volatility in the
market and doubted the sustainability of a recovery in the short
term.
</P>
<P>
"It's a relief to see blue on the screens," said one dealer.
"But I expect the rally was overdone. Japan being able to reflate
its economy is a very significant part of the solution but this
reaction was premature, and I think most people stepped back from
the volatility today."
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, a hefty advance on Wall Street and reports that
the new German coalition government will cut taxes saw an early
rally in Frankfurt extended. The Xetra Dax finished 298.19 points
higher at 4271.63.
</P>
<P>
Auto and banking sectors led the market higher after heavy
losses last week, with Daimler-Benz up sharply.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the strong start to the week was due to a
convincing rebound in Tokyo after the upper house of parliament
passed bills to create a framework to deal with banks that have
failed.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, last week's "double low", when the Xetra DAX twice
bottomed out at a year low around 3800 points, could signal a
gradual turnaround on the German stock market, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, follow-through buying in New York helped French
stocks build on the morning's rally as investors returned to the
markets. The Cac 40 index finished 170.42 points higher at
3263.32.
</P>
<P>
Banking shares were among the biggest winners on renewed
speculation of restructuring in the sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
