<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM Says Syrian-Turkish Detente Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said here Monday that a detente between the hostile Syria
and Turkey is still possible.
</P>
<P>
Moussa was commenting on his talks with his Syrian counterpart
Farouq Al-Shara as he made a stopover in Damascus on his way home
from Ankara.
</P>
<P>
"I was instructed by President Hosni Mubarak to brief Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad through Al-Shara on the results of the
Ankara talks," Moussa told reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"I conveyed a detailed message and I think we have what can be
deemed hope for surpassing the crisis and establishing stable
relations between the two neighbors," he said.
</P>
<P>
As for his talks in Turkey earlier in the day, Moussa said "the
security issue was a key subject of the discussions and we hope
for progress on a positive road through the Egyptian efforts."
</P>
<P>
"Contacts are going on," he added.
</P>
<P>
Moussa made a one-day visit to Ankara earlier in the day and
held talks with Turkish President Suleyman Demirel and Foreign
Minister Ismail Cem in an attempt to ease the tensions between
Turkey and Syria.
</P>
<P>
At the end of his visit, Moussa called his talks with Demirel
and Cem as "constructive and useful."
</P>
<P>
Relations between Turkey and Syria have always been
troublesome. Turkey has long accused Syria of harboring Turkish
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), which has been fighting
since 1984 for autonomy of the Kurdish minority in southeastern
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Syria, denying the charges, repeatedly voiced its concern and
fear over Turkey's close military alliance with Israel that
threats Arab security.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has stepped up a war of words against Syria recently and
Ankara's war-like rhetoric has aroused fears of a regional
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi have
visited Turkey and Syria to try to persuade the two neighbors to
solve their disputes through dialogs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
