<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Talks Postponed to Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The opening of the third
round of Burundi peace talks in Arusha, north Tanzania, was
postponed to Tuesday because some delegates have not arrived, a
senior aide to Julius Nyerere who chaired the talks said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The talks under the chairmanship of Nyerere, the international
peace facilitator, former Tanzanian president, will be attended
by 18 political parties, the government delegation and the
National Assembly of Burundi, Mark Bomani told Xinhua from Arusha
in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which had been planned to open on Monday, will
start at the International Conference Center at 3 p.m. Tuesday
and may last ten days, he said.
</P>
<P>
Bomani named some of the political parties as FRODEBU, a
pro-Hutu party, pro-Tutsi UPRONA, and the armed rebel group the
National Council for the Defense of Democracy (CNDD).
</P>
<P>
Issues on how to stop fighting and hold general elections in
the central African nation will be discussed, but the lifting of
economic sanctions on the central African nation will not be the
central topic, Bomani revealed.
</P>
<P>
More rounds of talks are expected, he said.
</P>
<P>
Observers from the United Nations, Organization of African
Unity (OAU), European Union will also attend the talks, said
Bomani, who is also a judge working for the Nyerere Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere has been holding informal talks with various factions
of Burundi trying to end the five-year ethnic conflict in
Burundi, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
East and central African nations, backed by the OAU, have
imposed economic sanctions on Burundi since August of 1996
shortly after Major Pierre Buyoya toppled a civilian government
led by President Ntibantunganya.
</P>
<P>
More than 150,000 people, mostly civilians, have died in
bloody conflicts between the ethnic Hutu majority and the ruling
Tutsi minority since the assassination of Melchoir Ndadaye, the
first president elected under a multiparty system in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Warring parties signed a ceasefire agreement in the first
round of talks in May and dwelt mainly on the genesis of the
Burundi conflict at the second round of talks in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
