<HEADLINE> UNITA Occupies Most Towns of Uige Province: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Most of the towns in Angola's
northern Uige Province have been occupied by the opposition
movement National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA), the Angolan News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the roads from the provincial capital of Uige to
outside have been cut, and Governor Cananito Alexandre has
appealed to the central government for emergent help, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the UNITA troops were attacking the city of
Bungo, only 70 kilometers from Uige City, capital of the
province, while the national police were desperately resisting
the advance of the rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
The cities of Puri, Dange and Cangola which are surrounding
Uige City have fallen into the hands of the UNITA following the
strategic towns of Maquela Do Zombo and Damba last month.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Governor Alexandre as saying that only with
the emergent support from the government troops, can the military
situation in his province be reversed.
</P>
<P>
The governor attributed the UNITA's aggressive presence in
Uige Province to its strong support from the Tutsi Banyanmulunge
soldiers fleeing from the neighboring Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The DRC rebels provided UNITA troops with not only the
logistics but also fire support like long-range artillery,
Alexandre said, adding that the Angolan national police captured
28 Banyanmulunge soldiers near the city of Damba.
</P>
<P>
It was also reported that the Angolan government and the rebel
UNITA has respectively amassed thousands of troops for a desive
battle in central Huambo Province.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA has reportedly reopened some of its former military
bases in the nearby Bie Province and a large number of troops are
gathering toward these bases.
</P>
<P>
There has been constant reports about the movement of the
UNITA and the fighting between the national police and the rebel
troops in other parts of the war-ravaged country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
