<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100 GMT, October 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The bodies of three other Iranian diplomats killed by
the Afghan Taliban militia have been returned to Iran, the
official news agency IRNA reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
A plane of the International Committee of the Red Cross carried
the bodies Sunday night to Mashhad in the northeastern province of
Khorasan.
</P>
<P>
The bodies will be identified in Mashhad before being
transferred to Tehran for a funeral procession on Friday, IRNA
said.
</P>
<P>
Taliban militia killed eight Iranian diplomats and an IRNA
reporter after the group captured Mazari Sharif, northern
Afghanistan, in August. Six bodies of the Iranian diplomats and
the reporter were transferred to Iran last month.
(BC-Iran-Afghanistan-Diplomat Bodies)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's Khordad 15 Foundation has decided to increase
its re1ward for killing British writer Salman Rushdie, the Jomhuri
Islami (Islamic Republic) daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The foundation's head, Ayatollah Sheikh Hassan Sanai, announced
Sunday in Mashhad, northeastern province of Khorasan that his
foundation would add a sum of 300,000 U.S. dollars to its
2.5-million-dollar reward.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Hezbollah Students Association also announced recently
a reward of 1 billion Iranian rials (about 333,000 dollars) for
carrying out the death sentence on Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Britain have agreed to upgrade their diplomatic
relations to the ambassadorial level after putting aside the
Rushdie issue, a step viewed by the west as Iran's retreat from
its original stance. (BC-Iran-Rushdie-Reward)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Palestinian side is well prepared for the
upcoming Washington summit which will focus on breaking the
stalemate of the Mideast peace process, said a senior Palestinian
official on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Saeb Erekat, Palestinian chief negotiator, said the Palestinian
side has completed its preparations and reports on various issues
to be discussed during the Washington summit among U.S. President
Bill Clinton, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
All these reports have been approved by Arafat, Erekat told the
Voice of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
The Washington summit will discuss the scope of Israel's troop
redeployment in the West Bank and the Palestinian side has also
prepared maps for that, he said. (BC-Israel-Palestine-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- President of the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
Yasser Arafat here Monday expressed hope that his upcoming meeting
with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu will yield concrete
results.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said that he wants to clinch a deal with Israel on a
peace proposal put forward by the United States for further
Israeli troops withdrawal from the occupied West Bank during their
meeting in the U.S. on October 15.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made these remarks at a press conference held after he
met with Crown Prince Hassan, and other senior Jordanian officials
on the latest developments of the Palestinian-Israeli peace
process. (BC-Jordan-Palestine-Arafat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen said
Monday that the United States reserves the right to use force
against Iraq if Baghdad fails to comply with the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Cohen made the remarks during a speech to the American troops
stationed at the Tusker Camp in west Kuwait, which is near the
Iraqi border.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iraq must fully implement all the United Nations'
resolutions and the Security Council "should stand behind its own
resolutions until seeking the use of force."
</P>
<P>
If the Iraqi regime refuses to comply with the U.N.
resolutions, Cohen said, "we reserve the right to take action at a
pleasant time of our choosing."
</P>
<P>
The defense secretary underlined that his country has "a very
formidable force in the Gulf region that can take military actions
very quickly if it becomes necessary."
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that the U.S. has maintained a force of roughly
20,000 in the region, adding that the force level can be increased
to 40,000 in a 96-hour period.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. top defense official arrived here earlier Monday for a
two-day visit. Kuwait is the fourth leg of Cohen's six-nation Gulf
tour, which has already taken him to Bahrain, Qatar, the United
Arab Emirates and Oman.
</P>
<P>
He is heading to Saudi Arabia Tuesday. (BC-Kuwait-Cohen-Visit)
</P>
