<HEADLINE> Mozambican President Urges Debt Relief for Sake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano Monday called on the international donors to relief
Mozambique from its heavy debts for the sake of education in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Chissano made the call at a meeting here celebrating the 17th
anniversary of the establishment of the National Organization of
Teachers.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican president urged the international donors to
make efforts to reduce or write off Mozambique's debts, increase
bilateral or multilateral assistance and provide funds on time so
as to ensure that Mozambique's Strategic Plan for Education can
be carried out.
</P>
<P>
Chissano also called upon the whole country to offer support
for schools, appealing to the government departments, private
firms and citizens to help the state with the education program.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government will continue its efforts to
strengthen the training, improve the housing and increase wages
for the teachers, said the president.
</P>
<P>
He expressed relief over the increase of the numbers of
schools, students and teachers.
</P>
<P>
According to Mozambican Minister of Education Arnaldo Nhavoto,
the number of pupils of form one to four has gone up to 1.9
million from 1.2 million in 1992 while the teachers in primary
schools have increased by 12,000, and 3,110 schools destroyed
during the war have been rehabilitated.
</P>
<P>
But the minister noted that some teachers have left
educational institutions because of the lower pay and
unsatisfactory conditions.
</P>
<P>
Chissano also admitted that the country's illiteracy rate
remains high, especially for girls. But the president believed
that all the problems will be solved through the implementation
of the national education plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
