<HEADLINE> Syria, Turkey Urged to Solve Disputes Peacefully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia on Monday
urged Syria and Turkey to solve their disputes through dialog and
avert the use of force, the Saudi Press Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi cabinet issued the call after its weekly session
chaired by King Fahd.
</P>
<P>
The appeal came amid continuing Arab and Islamic mediation
efforts to end the tension between Syria and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Turkey have long been at odds over issues including
Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), water sharing and
the Turkish-Israeli military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused Syria of harboring the PKK, which has been
fighting since 1984 for an independent Kurdish state in the
southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Syria has lashed out at Turkey, a predominantly Muslim
country, for forming a military alliance with Israel, which it
says is targeted against the Arab world, especially itself, and
undermines its bargaining position in negotiations with the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Syria has disputes with Israel over the future of the Golan
Heights, captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war. Damascus
insisted on its return as a condition for peace with Israel.
</P>
