<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Acquisition Creates Largest Online Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, October 12 (Xinhua) -- A leading U.S. direct
marketer has acquired an online business organization, creating
the world's largest trade association for business on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
The 81-year-old Direct Marketing Association (DMA) announced
Monday the acquisition of the Association for Interactive Media
(AIM), founded in 1993, during the ongoing DMA 81st annual
conference in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
"This acquisition is a sign of the times -- a snapshot of
what's going on in the business world today," DMA president and
CEO H. Robert Wientzen said in a statement. "Many mainstream,
stable and traditional businesses are merging with younger,
entrepreneurial start-ups on the verge of success. Each side needs
the other to move e-commerce into a successful future."
</P>
<P>
DMA's members include more than 4,100 businesses in interactive
and database marketing from the United States and 53 other
nations, while AIM's 250 members only do business online.
</P>
<P>
According to AIM president Andy Sernovitgz, the acquisition is
about sharing intellectual capital. Direct marketers have the
marketing know-how and the new media architects have the
technological know-how. Businesses using the Internet must marry
the new interactive nature of the Net with traditional marketing
tools to fulfil the promises made to consumers, he said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
DMA was founded in 1917. Its members include catalogers,
Internet retailers and service providers, financial services
providers, book and magazine publishers, book and music clubs,
retail stores and industrial manufacturers. In 1997, 705 billion
U.S. dollars in direct marketing purchases were made by consumers
and 554 billion dollars were made by businesses in the United
States, according to DMA.
</P>
<P>
Business-to-business direct marketing has recorded phenomenal
growth over the the past five years in the United States, DMA
said. Companies are increasingly utilizing direct mail, print, TV
and interactive advertising, in addition to the standard industry
practice of outbound telemarketing, to attract buyers for the
corporate market.
</P>
<P>
After the acquisition, AIM, headquartered in Washington, D.C.,
will operate as a subsidiary of the New York-based DMA. The
organization has experience in promoting consumer confidence in
e-commerce and providing business-to-business networking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981013.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
