<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leighton Announces Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Scotland's record cap-winning
goalkeeper Jim Leighton retired from international football on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
National boss Craig Brown announced in a press conference that
the 40-year-old Aberdeen goalkeeper was standing down "with
immediate effect".
</P>
<P>
The news comes as a huge surprise. Leighton earned his 91st
cap in the 3-2 victory over Estonia on Saturday and was due to
face the Faroe Islands in another Euro 2000 qualifier on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Brown said Leighton had given no reason for his decision - but
he had been criticised for his performance in the Estonia match.
</P>
<P>
The coach was clearly distressed at the news. He said: "I
respect his decision but I tried to dissuade him. Jim said he had
slept on it and he is the only one who knows why he has reached
that decision.
</P>
<P>
"He said he wasn't prepared to discuss it, that he had made
his decision and what we have lost is an experienced
professional."
</P>
<P>
In a roller-coaster international career spanning 16 years,
Leighton became the only Scot to go to four World Cups.
</P>
<P>
Former international teammates Arthur Albiston and Alex
Mcleish were quick to pay tribute to Leighton's service to
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
"There has always been this myth about Scottish goalkeepers
being no good, but I think Jim Leighton has certainly laid that
to rest with his performances," said Albiston.
</P>
<P>
"When I was playing with him in the mid 1980s he was probably
at his peak, but it says a lot about him that he continued at the
top for so long."
</P>
<P>
Hibernian manager McLeish said Leighton's "burning passion to
succeed" had never diminished.
</P>
<P>
"His desire was tremendous. He wanted to make it so badly and
it hurt him when at about 17 or 18 he was turned away by Rangers
because they said he was too small," he added.
</P>
<P>
Leighton, who formerly played for Manchester United, is the
second world-class keeper Scotland have lost in untimely
circumstances in the last four months.
</P>
<P>
Andy Goram quit the World Cup warm-up tour of the United
States in June, just before they were due to travel to France
98. 
</P>
</TEXT>
